l-connected with no isolated subgraphs.\n\n**Strengths:** (1) Excellent literature alignment\u2014nearly every major finding from the research is represented, including Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user reductive amination, Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry, Muchowska proto-TCA cycles, Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and Saladino formamide photolysis. (2) Strong network topology with 5 hub molecules at degree \u22653 (except P5C at degree 2), 5 convergence points, and 10 pathways providing redundancy. (3) Good environmental transitions with mineral agents specified for most hydrothermal reactions (greigite, magnetite, pyrite, NiFeS). (4) The spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization (rxn_008) is one of the most prebiotically robust steps, scoring 0.95.\n\n**Weaknesses:** (1) The recurring rxn_007 (glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the network's Achilles heel\u2014the literature explicitly flags this as 'chemically demanding' and no convincing prebiotic reductant is specified. This affects 7 of 10 pathways. (2) rxn_010 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol) oversimplifies the multi-step Patel et al. mechanism, omitting the critical Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. (3) rxn_015 (DAMN \u2192 proline directly) is chemically implausible as written\u2014many intermediates are skipped. (4) The 'L-' designation in the target is not addressed anywhere in the network. The literature emphasizes that proline racemizes readily at the \u03b1-carbon and no enantioselection mechanism is included. (5) Several surface reactions lack mineral agent specification (rxn_004, rxn_006, rxn_010, rxn_014, rxn_015). (6) P5C (mol_014) has degree 2, below the hub threshold.\n\n**Missing elements:** Ornithine as alternative entry point to GSA (noted in literature), concentration mechanisms, the OPA/NAC detection limitation context, and any chirality amplification (crystal-solution eutectic, chiral mineral surfaces, or proline's organocatalytic self-reinforcement). Kaur et al. (2024) mild-condition Ni catalysis could strengthen rxn_005.\n\nOverall, this is a strong network that successfully integrates multiple prebiotic chemistry paradigms into a coherent whole. Four pathways meet the approval threshold, with P3 (cyanosulfidic) being the best-supported single pathway despite its oversimplification at rxn_010.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.85, "convergence_quality": 0.84}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 313339.1857147217, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T06:28:47.280277", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of L-Proline: routes, challenges, and the chirality puzzle\n\n**Proline is among the most structurally distinctive amino acids to form under prebiotic conditions, yet multiple independent lines of evidence confirm its abiotic synthesis.** As the only proteinogenic amino acid with a cyclic secondary amine (pyrrolidine ring), proline demands ring-closing chemistry that sets it apart from all other coded amino acids. Despite this structural complexity, proline has been detected in Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments, carbonaceous chondrite meteorites, and has been shown to emerge naturally from cyanosulfidic photochemistry. These converging lines of evidence place proline among the \"early\" amino acids accessible on prebiotic Earth\u2014ranking approximately eighth to ninth in abiotic abundance. Yet its path to biological homochirality remains one of the most challenging puzzles in origin-of-life chemistry, complicated by rapid aqueous racemization at its \u03b1-carbon and the difficulty of concentrating it from dilute prebiotic solutions.\n\n---\n\n## Multiple prebiotic routes converge on the pyrrolidine ring\n\nAt least four independent chemical pathways produce proline under plausibly prebiotic conditions, each starting from different simple feedstock molecules and operating through distinct mechanisms.\n\n**The Miller-Urey spark discharge route** represents the earliest experimental demonstration. Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* 69:765\u2013768) definitively identified proline by both ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS in electric discharge experiments using CH\u2084, N\u2082, and H\u2082O with trace NH\u2083. Their work detected **20 amino acids total**, and proline was confirmed as a minor but reproducible product. Johnson, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, Lazcano, and Bada (2008, *Science* 322:404) re-analyzed archived vials from Miller's \"volcanic\" apparatus and found 22 amino acids and 5 amines. More recently, Jiang and colleagues (2014, *Scientific Reports* 4:6769) detected all non-sulfur-containing natural amino acids including proline using LC-MS/MS. A critical analytical caveat, however, has caused systematic underreporting: the standard OPA/NAC derivatization method used in modern amino acid analysis **cannot detect proline** because it only reacts with primary amines. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, and colleagues (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) explicitly noted this limitation when re-analyzing Miller's H\u2082S-rich experiment\u2014proline detection was \"not possible\" with their methodology. This means proline's true abundance in spark discharge products is likely higher than commonly reported.\n\n**The cyanosulfidic chemistry route**, developed by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307), provides the most mechanistically detailed prebiotic pathway to proline. Starting from HCN, H\u2082S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling at **35\u00b0C in anoxic, neutral-pH conditions**, this network produces precursors to 12 proteinogenic amino acids through four chemical \"movements.\" Proline specifically arises through what the authors designate \"movement c\": a 4-carbon cyanohydrin reacts with H\u2082S to produce both an open-chain and a **cyclic \u03b1-hydroxythioamide**. UV irradiation then drives cyclization and deoxygenation to yield **\u03b3-butyrothiolactam**, which undergoes photoreduction and HCN addition to generate the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47 in the original paper). The elegance of this pathway lies in its inevitability\u2014the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage, requiring no enzymatic guidance. Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile then yields proline itself. This route connects proline synthesis to the broader cyanosulfidic network that simultaneously generates nucleotide and lipid precursors, suggesting a unified chemical origin for life's building blocks.\n\n**The glutamate-to-proline reductive amination pathway** mirrors the biological biosynthetic route and proceeds through well-characterized intermediates. Glutamic acid\u2014one of the most abundant amino acids in both spark discharge experiments and meteorites\u2014undergoes partial reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl group to form **glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)**. GSA then undergoes spontaneous, non-enzymatic intramolecular cyclization to form **\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)**, as first characterized by Vogel and Davis (1952, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 74:109\u2013112). This cyclization requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution\u2014making it one of the most prebiotically plausible steps in the entire pathway. Final reduction of P5C to proline could be driven by Fe\u00b2\u207a, FeS/H\u2082S systems, or molecular hydrogen from serpentinization. The biological pathway was further elucidated by Strecker (1957, *Journal of Biological Chemistry* 225:825\u2013834), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids can be reductively aminated to amino acids on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces, establishing the prebiotic feasibility of the first step.\n\n**HCN oligomerization**, first explored by Or\u00f3 in 1961, produces amino acids through polymer hydrolysis. Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (2013, *Life* 3:421\u2013448) reviewed 23 experimental conditions and found proline among the amino acids detected in some HCN polymer hydrolysis experiments, particularly those conducted at higher temperatures. The mechanism proceeds through diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, the HCN tetramer) and hydantoin intermediates.\n\n---\n\n## The intermediate network reveals key branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of proline connects to a broader metabolic-like network of chemical transformations, with **\u03b1-ketoglutarate serving as the central branch-point intermediate**. This TCA-cycle compound sits at the intersection of carbon metabolism and amino acid synthesis, feeding the glutamate family: glutamate, glutamine, proline, and arginine.\n\nRecent work has demonstrated prebiotically plausible routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate itself. Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, *Nature Chemistry* 12:1016\u20131022) showed that \u03b1-keto acid chemistry can reproduce key features of the TCA cycle without enzymes. Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, *Nature Communications* 9:91) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative decarboxylation of glyoxylate as protometabolic analogs. Most recently, Krishnamurthy's group (2025) demonstrated formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from just two amino acids\u2014serine and glycine\u2014via pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu\u00b2\u207a catalysis. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry*) then showed \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate.\n\nThe pathway from glutamate to proline passes through three intermediates, each with distinct prebiotic significance:\n\n- **Glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)** is the open-chain form that requires reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl group. In biology, this is accomplished by NADPH; prebiotically, FeS/H\u2082S or Fe\u00b2\u207a could serve as reductants.\n- **\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)** forms spontaneously from GSA through intramolecular imine formation. This non-enzymatic cyclization is the crucial ring-closing step that creates proline's pyrrolidine skeleton.\n- **Ornithine** represents an alternative entry point. In biology, ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase converts ornithine to GSA, and ornithine cyclodeaminase can convert ornithine directly to proline. Whether similar non-enzymatic transformations occur under prebiotic conditions remains unexplored.\n\nProline ranks approximately **eighth to ninth in prebiotic amino acid abundance** according to the analysis of Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483\u2013490), who classified it among the \"early 10\" amino acids\u2014those reliably produced in Miller experiments, found in meteorites, and thermodynamically favorable. The ranking correlates with Gibbs free energy of formation data from Amend and Shock (1998). Among the early amino acids (Gly > Ala > Asp > Glu > Val > Ser > Ile/Leu > Pro > Thr), proline's lower abundance reflects the additional thermodynamic cost of ring formation.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents and volcanic hot springs offer complementary settings\n\nThe environmental conditions most favorable for prebiotic proline synthesis depend on which pathway is operative, with different settings favoring different reaction steps.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** of the Lost City type (Kelley et al., 2001) provide temperatures of **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, and abundant H\u2082 and CH\u2084 from serpentinization of ultramafic peridotite. These reducing conditions favor reductive amination reactions. M\u00e9nez and colleagues (2018, *Nature* 564:59\u201363) discovered abiotic tryptophan in serpentinite rocks beneath Lost City, trapped in iron-rich saponite clays\u2014the first direct evidence of amino acid formation through purely abiotic geochemical processes in a natural hydrothermal system. The Russell and Hall model (1997, 2006) proposed that Fe(II)-bearing hydroxides, sulfides, and carbonates in alkaline vent chimneys could drive CO\u2082 reduction and amino acid synthesis via electrochemical gradients across mineral membranes.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (>300\u00b0C, acidic, metal sulfide-rich) present a stability challenge. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) argued that submarine hot springs are net destroyers of organic compounds. However, **proline's pyrrolidine ring confers enhanced thermal stability** compared to many other amino acids. Li and Brill (2003, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A* 107:5987\u20135992) studied proline decarboxylation kinetics at 270\u2013340\u00b0C and 275 bar, finding relatively slow decomposition rates independent of pH between 3 and 8.5. Vallentyne (1968) found proline to be more stable than leucine, arginine, and lysine under hydrothermal conditions. Notably, Vallentyne also identified proline as a degradation product of arginine\u2014suggesting a secondary prebiotic route to proline through thermal processing of other amino acids.\n\n**Volcanic hot spring pools on land** represent a third setting championed by Damer and Deamer (2020, *Astrobiology* 20:429\u2013452) in the \"Hot Spring Hypothesis.\" These fluctuating pools at **60\u201390\u00b0C** provide three energy sources simultaneously: thermal energy, dehydration-rehydration chemical potential, and UV light. Van Kranendonk and colleagues (2020, *Astrobiology*) showed that the **3.48 billion-year-old Dresser Formation** in Western Australia's Pilbara Craton preserves evidence of such terrestrial hot springs, including geyserite, concentrated boron (in tourmaline), phosphate-bearing hydrothermal veins, and smectite/illite clays\u2014all cofactors for prebiotic chemistry. Wet-dry cycling in these settings drives peptide bond formation that is thermodynamically unfavorable in bulk water, as demonstrated by Ross and Deamer (2016, *Life* 6:28) and Forsythe and colleagues (2015, *Angewandte Chemie* 54:9871\u20139875).\n\nThe cyanosulfidic route to proline (Patel et al. 2015) operates under yet another set of conditions: **35\u00b0C, neutral pH, anoxic atmosphere** with UV irradiation, Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling, and phosphate buffer\u2014conditions potentially realized in shallow, UV-exposed pools on early Earth's surface.\n\n---\n\n## Iron-sulfur minerals and nickel catalysts drive key transformations\n\nMineral catalysis is essential for several steps in prebiotic proline synthesis, with iron-sulfur and nickel-iron systems playing the most prominent roles.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** drives W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's \"pyrite-pulled\" reactions, where the thermodynamically favorable formation of pyrite from FeS provides reducing equivalents: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on freshly precipitated FeS at 100\u00b0C, with strong metal specificity\u2014other metal sulfides failed to produce amino acids. Muchowska and colleagues (2017, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 1:1716\u20131721) showed pyrite drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates including the proline precursor \u03b1-ketoglutarate. **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** is structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] clusters in modern metalloenzymes, particularly acetyl-CoA synthase (Li et al. 2018, *Life* 8:46), positioning it as a proto-enzymatic catalyst for CO\u2082 fixation and reductive transformations in hydrothermal mound chimneys.\n\nA landmark recent study by Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, *Chem* 10:1528\u20131540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H\u2082 and NH\u2083 over **nickel catalysts** at remarkably mild conditions: **22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1\u201310 bar H\u2082**. Using Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) or even ground meteorites (11\u201318 mol% Ni) as catalysts, this system produces seven biological amino acids from reductive amination of keto acids, including **glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate**. The pathway generates \u03b1-ketoglutarate\u2014the direct precursor to glutamate and, through the GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade, to proline itself.\n\n**Montmorillonite clay** catalyzes amino acid polymerization, as demonstrated extensively by Ferris and colleagues (1996, *Nature* 381:59\u201361; 2006, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B* 361:1777\u20131786). Clay surfaces concentrate monomers in interlayer environments, catalyzing condensation at rates **100\u20131,000 times greater than hydrolysis**. Bujdak and colleagues (1994, *Monatshefte f\u00fcr Chemie* 125:1033\u20131039) showed montmorillonite catalyzes peptide formation from glycine in evaporation cycles. While specific proline-clay interaction data remain sparse, the negative layer charge of montmorillonite attracts amino acid ammonium groups, and Namani and colleagues (2021, *ChemSystemsChem*) showed prebiotically relevant amino acids enhance montmorillonite-catalyzed RNA polymerization cooperatively.\n\n**TiO\u2082 photocatalysis** offers another mineral-driven route. Saladino and colleagues (2017) demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of amino acids from formamide under UV irradiation on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Rutile, a common early Earth mineral, could have driven amino acid formation in UV-exposed shallow water environments.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic proline and the underreporting problem\n\nProline was among the earliest amino acids identified in the Murchison meteorite. Kvenvolden, Lawless, and colleagues (1970, *Nature* 228:923\u2013926) detected proline alongside glycine, alanine, glutamic acid, and valine by ion-exchange chromatography and capillary gas chromatography. Critically, they reported \"almost equal amounts of the D and L enantiomers of valine, proline, alanine, and glutamic acid\"\u2014near-racemic ratios that argued strongly for abiotic origin and against terrestrial biological contamination. Cronin and Moore (1971, *Science* 172:1327\u20131329) confirmed proline in extended analyses of Murchison, Murray, and Allende chondrites.\n\n**Quantitative concentrations** of proline in Murchison fall in the range of **~0.1\u20131 \u03bcg/g (ppm)**, making it a minor but consistent component of the meteoritic amino acid suite. For comparison, glycine\u2014the most abundant amino acid\u2014reaches 3\u20136 \u03bcg/g. The abundance pattern (decreasing with carbon number and structural complexity) is consistent with abiotic synthesis mechanisms, likely Strecker-cyanohydrin reactions on the meteorite parent body. Lerner and Cooper (2005, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 69:2901\u20132906) detected iminodicarboxylic acids in Murchison, providing direct evidence for Strecker-type reactions on the parent body.\n\nEngel and Nagy (1982, *Nature* 296:837\u2013840) reported L-excesses in protein amino acids from Murchison, including proline, but these results proved controversial due to potential contamination. Pizzarello and colleagues (2012, *PNAS*) analyzed the pristine CR chondrite GRA 95229 and found that **protein amino acids including proline were racemic** (D/L \u2248 1), while isovaline retained an L-excess of ~3%. This distinction is fundamental: proline has an \u03b1-hydrogen and racemizes readily during aqueous alteration, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess. The \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids (isovaline, \u03b1-methylisoleucine) lack this vulnerable hydrogen and preserve their original chirality.\n\n---\n\n## The chirality puzzle: from small imbalances to biological homochirality\n\nHow L-proline could be selected over D-proline in prebiotic settings remains one of the deepest unresolved questions in origin-of-life research. The challenge is compounded by proline's facile racemization at the \u03b1-carbon, which erases any initial enantiomeric excess in aqueous solution.\n\n**Circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions represents the most widely discussed symmetry-breaking mechanism. Bailey and colleagues (1998, *Science* 281:672\u2013674) discovered ~17% circular polarization in infrared light from the Orion nebula, suggesting our presolar environment could have provided CPL. Meinert and colleagues (2014, *Astrophysical Journal* 788:79) irradiated interstellar ice analogs with synchrotron UV CPL and detected 24 amino acids including proline in the residues, with small but reproducible enantiomeric excesses. Meinert and colleagues (2022, *Nature Communications*) measured the first gas-phase circular dichroism spectra for amino acids including proline in the vacuum UV (130\u2013280 nm), revealing that **proline's five-membered nitrogen heterocycle produces unique spectral features**\u2014hypsochromic shifts distinguishing it from all open-chain amino acids. These anisotropy factors predict the ee inducible by CPL photolysis. However, maximum laboratory CPL-induced ee values remain **\u22642\u20133%**, and Glavin and Dworkin's (2009, *PNAS* 106:5487\u20135492) finding that pristine CR meteorites show no isovaline excess argues against CPL as the sole mechanism.\n\n**Chiral mineral surfaces** offer an alternative symmetry-breaking route. Hazen, Filley, and Goodfriend (2001, *PNAS* 98:5487\u20135490) demonstrated that calcite scalenohedral crystal faces selectively adsorb D- versus L-aspartic acid, with terraced surfaces showing the greatest selectivity. The mechanism requires three non-colinear configuration-dependent interaction points between molecule and surface. Alanine, with only two bonding points, showed no enantioselectivity. **No published data exist for proline adsorption on chiral calcite surfaces**, representing a significant experimental gap. Proline's rigid pyrrolidine ring and carboxylate group provide a distinctive molecular geometry that could create specific three-point contacts, but this remains untested.\n\n**Chiral amplification mechanisms** are essential to bridge the gap from small initial ee values (1\u20133%) to biological homochirality (100% L). Three mechanisms are particularly relevant to proline:\n\n- **Crystal-solution eutectic amplification**: Hayashi, Koshino, and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 45:4593\u20134597) achieved the most dramatic amplification demonstrated for any amino acid. DL-proline racemic crystals have more hydrogen bonds and are less soluble than enantiopure crystals. When solid proline of **only 10% ee** was dissolved in CHCl\u2083/EtOH, the solution reached **85\u201399% ee** as the racemic crystals preferentially remained undissolved. Klussmann and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) calculated the eutectic ee for proline as ~76.5% in certain solvents. The limitation is that CHCl\u2083/EtOH is not prebiotically plausible; finding aqueous conditions that replicate this effect remains an open challenge.\n\n- **Proline-mediated autoinductive catalysis**: Mathew, Iwamura, and Blackmond (2004, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) showed that proline-catalyzed \u03b1-aminoxylation of aldehydes exhibits accelerating reaction rates (autoinduction) and ee amplification over time. Products form adducts with proline that act as more efficient catalysts\u2014the first general organic chemistry strategy implicating amino acid catalysis in a selectivity-enhancing autoinductive process.\n\n- **Proline as organocatalyst**: List, Lerner, and Barbas III (2000, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 122:2395) discovered that L-proline catalyzes intermolecular asymmetric aldol reactions with **up to >99% enantioselectivity**, operating through an enamine mechanism via a Zimmerman-Traxler transition state. The pyrrolidine ring constrains the transition state geometry, and both ring size and carboxyl group are essential\u2014making proline uniquely suited among all amino acids. This dual identity as both a product of prebiotic synthesis and a powerful asymmetric catalyst raises the tantalizing possibility of a self-reinforcing chiral feedback loop, though true autocatalysis (proline catalyzing its own formation) has not been demonstrated.\n\nThe **Soai reaction** (Soai et al., 1995) demonstrates that autocatalytic amplification from ee as low as ~0.00005% to >99.5% is chemically possible, but requires anhydrous dialkylzinc chemistry incompatible with aqueous prebiotic conditions. It serves as proof-of-concept for Frank's (1953, *Biochimica et Biophysica Acta* 11:459) theoretical model of spontaneous symmetry breaking through autocatalysis plus mutual inhibition. **Parity violation** in the weak nuclear force creates energy differences of only ~10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 J/mol between enantiomers (Quack 2002, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 41:4618)\u2014many orders of magnitude below thermal energy and universally considered irrelevant to biological homochirality.\n\n---\n\n## Persistent bottlenecks and the road ahead\n\nSeveral fundamental challenges remain unresolved in the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline.\n\n**The concentration problem** is perhaps the most severe. Prebiotic amino acid concentrations in the primitive ocean are estimated at **micromolar or lower** levels\u2014far below the millimolar-to-molar concentrations typically used in laboratory demonstrations. Evaporative concentration in closed-basin pools, mineral surface adsorption, and fatty acid membrane binding (Cornell et al. 2019, *PNAS*) offer partial solutions, but no single mechanism convincingly bridges this gap for proline specifically. Campbell and Bracher (2019, *Nature Communications* 10:4508) showed deliquescent minerals increase glycine oligomerization yields over 10-fold during wet-dry cycles, but proline-specific data are lacking.\n\n**The selectivity problem** concerns how to generate proline preferentially rather than as a trace component in a complex mixture. In Miller-type experiments, glycine dominates and proline is a minor product. The cyanosulfidic route produces proline alongside many other amino acids and molecular classes. Any prebiotic scenario must explain not only proline's formation but its accumulation at biologically relevant concentrations.\n\n**The racemization problem** is acute for proline. Unlike \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids such as isovaline (which preserve meteoritic L-ee of up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.6%**, Glavin and Dworkin 2009), proline's \u03b1-hydrogen makes it vulnerable to base-catalyzed racemization in water. Any enantiomeric excess must be continuously regenerated or amplified faster than racemization erases it. The crystal-solution eutectic amplification demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino (2006) achieves this in organic solvents, but translating this mechanism to aqueous prebiotic conditions remains undemonstrated.\n\n**The ring-formation step** is what makes proline uniquely challenging among prebiotic amino acids. While the GSA \u2192 P5C cyclization is spontaneous, accessing GSA requires selective reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl to an aldehyde without reducing the \u03b1-carboxyl\u2014a chemically demanding transformation. The cyanosulfidic route elegantly sidesteps this by forming the ring at the thiolactam stage, but whether this specific photochemistry operated at relevant scales on early Earth is debated.\n\nSeveral experimental gaps deserve attention. No studies have tested **enantioselective adsorption of proline on chiral mineral surfaces** (calcite, quartz). The **crystal-solution eutectic effect** has not been demonstrated for proline in water. The full pathway from simple feedstocks (CO\u2082, N\u2082, H\u2082O) to proline has never been achieved in a single continuous experimental system. And the OPA/NAC derivatization limitation means proline abundances in many published prebiotic experiments may need systematic re-evaluation using methods capable of detecting secondary amines.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nProline stands at a fascinating intersection in prebiotic chemistry\u2014structurally the most unusual of the coded amino acids, yet demonstrably accessible through at least four independent abiotic pathways. The cyanosulfidic route of Patel and Sutherland (2015) provides the most compelling single-flask demonstration, with ring formation arising naturally from the geometry of 4-carbon thioamide intermediates rather than requiring any specialized cyclization step. The glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline pathway, featuring a spontaneous non-enzymatic cyclization, connects proline to the broader protometabolic network centered on \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Proline's enhanced thermal stability\u2014its pyrrolidine ring resists decarboxylation better than many open-chain amino acids\u2014gives it a selective survival advantage in hydrothermal environments.\n\nThe chirality problem, however, remains proline's deepest challenge. Its \u03b1-hydrogen ensures rapid aqueous racemization, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess and distinguishing it from the \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids that preserve meteoritic L-enrichment. The remarkable crystal-solution eutectic amplification (10% to 85\u201399% ee) demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino has not been replicated under prebiotically relevant aqueous conditions. Perhaps most intriguing is proline's dual identity as both a prebiotic product and a uniquely powerful organocatalyst for asymmetric synthesis. Whether this creates a genuine self-reinforcing feedback loop\u2014where a small excess of L-proline catalyzes reactions that preferentially generate or preserve more L-proline\u2014remains the central open question. The answer could illuminate not just proline's origin but the emergence of biological homochirality itself.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is an impressively comprehensive synthesis network for L-Proline that captures all four major prebiotic routes described in the literature: cyanosulfidic photochemistry (Patel et al. 2015), glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C cascade, HCN oligomerization, and formamide photolysis. The five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, \u03b1KG, glutamate, P5C) create genuine convergence and the network topology is well-connected with no isolated subgraphs.\n\n**Strengths:** (1) Excellent literature alignment\u2014nearly every major finding from the research is represented, including Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user reductive amination, Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry, Muchowska proto-TCA cycles, Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and Saladino formamide photolysis. (2) Strong network topology with 5 hub molecules at degree \u22653 (except P5C at degree 2), 5 convergence points, and 10 pathways providing redundancy. (3) Good environmental transitions with mineral agents specified for most hydrothermal reactions (greigite, magnetite, pyrite, NiFeS). (4) The spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization (rxn_008) is one of the most prebiotically robust steps, scoring 0.95.\n\n**Weaknesses:** (1) The recurring rxn_007 (glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the network's Achilles heel\u2014the literature explicitly flags this as 'chemically demanding' and no convincing prebiotic reductant is specified. This affects 7 of 10 pathways. (2) rxn_010 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol) oversimplifies the multi-step Patel et al. mechanism, omitting the critical Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. (3) rxn_015 (DAMN \u2192 proline directly) is chemically implausible as written\u2014many intermediates are skipped. (4) The 'L-' designation in the target is not addressed anywhere in the network. The literature emphasizes that proline racemizes readily at the \u03b1-carbon and no enantioselection mechanism is included. (5) Several surface reactions lack mineral agent specification (rxn_004, rxn_006, rxn_010, rxn_014, rxn_015). (6) P5C (mol_014) has degree 2, below the hub threshold.\n\n**Missing elements:** Ornithine as alternative entry point to GSA (noted in literature), concentration mechanisms, the OPA/NAC detection limitation context, and any chirality amplification (crystal-solution eutectic, chiral mineral surfaces, or proline's organocatalytic self-reinforcement). Kaur et al. (2024) mild-condition Ni catalysis could strengthen rxn_005.\n\nOverall, this is a strong network that successfully integrates multiple prebiotic chemistry paradigms into a coherent whole. Four pathways meet the approval threshold, with P3 (cyanosulfidic) being the best-supported single pathway despite its oversimplification at rxn_010.\n- Issues: ['Similar to P1 but uses Bucherer-Bergs synthesis (rxn_006) for glutamate formation, directly supported by Pulletikurti et al. (2022). This is a slight improvement over P1 for the amination step since the Bucherer-Bergs mechanism is well-characterized. However, it requires HCN as an additional input without specifying its source within this pathway (it must come from P5/P6 routes or external). The same weakness at rxn_007 persists. The Surface environment for rxn_006 needs mineral specification.', 'Severely oversimplified pathway. While HCN\u2192DAMN (rxn_014) is well-established (Or\u00f3 1961), the direct conversion DAMN\u2192proline (rxn_015) skips critical intermediates including hydantoin formation and complex polymer hydrolysis steps. Literature (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013) describes proline as a minor product of HCN polymer hydrolysis under specific high-temperature conditions. The pathway has only 2 steps with no hydrothermal involvement and no mineral agents specified. Proline would be a trace component of a complex mixture\u2014selectivity is extremely poor.', 'Combines formamide photolysis with HCN oligomerization. Better environmental progression than P4 (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Surface), but still hampered by the problematic rxn_015 (DAMN\u2192proline direct conversion). The formamide-to-HCN portion is well-supported but cannot rescue the fundamentally flawed final step.', 'Combines proto-TCA \u03b1KG formation with Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis. Good convergence of two literature-supported routes but inherits both the rxn_007 weakness and the need for an external HCN source. The pathway demonstrates good network convergence properties.', \"Combines surface glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004) with elements from both P1 and P7. Provides alternative convergence point at \u03b1KG. Same recurring weakness at rxn_007. The glyoxylate route is supported by Springsteen et al. (2018) and Krishnamurthy's group.\", 'The longest pathway at 10 steps, combining formamide photolysis, Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and surface \u03b1KG formation. While it demonstrates maximum network connectivity and environmental progression, the length introduces cumulative yield concerns. Each additional step reduces overall plausibility. Still hampered by rxn_007 and the questionable direct glyoxylate formation.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 7659.087181091309, "success": false, "error_message": "{'type': 'error', 'error': {'details': None, 'type': 'api_error', 'message': 'Internal server error'}, 'request_id': 'req_011CZ8VfsBspWr6KYCRQPz7j'}"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T06:30:54.951694", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of L-Proline: routes, challenges, and the chirality puzzle\n\n**Proline is among the most structurally distinctive amino acids to form under prebiotic conditions, yet multiple independent lines of evidence confirm its abiotic synthesis.** As the only proteinogenic amino acid with a cyclic secondary amine (pyrrolidine ring), proline demands ring-closing chemistry that sets it apart from all other coded amino acids. Despite this structural complexity, proline has been detected in Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments, carbonaceous chondrite meteorites, and has been shown to emerge naturally from cyanosulfidic photochemistry. These converging lines of evidence place proline among the \"early\" amino acids accessible on prebiotic Earth\u2014ranking approximately eighth to ninth in abiotic abundance. Yet its path to biological homochirality remains one of the most challenging puzzles in origin-of-life chemistry, complicated by rapid aqueous racemization at its \u03b1-carbon and the difficulty of concentrating it from dilute prebiotic solutions.\n\n---\n\n## Multiple prebiotic routes converge on the pyrrolidine ring\n\nAt least four independent chemical pathways produce proline under plausibly prebiotic conditions, each starting from different simple feedstock molecules and operating through distinct mechanisms.\n\n**The Miller-Urey spark discharge route** represents the earliest experimental demonstration. Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* 69:765\u2013768) definitively identified proline by both ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS in electric discharge experiments using CH\u2084, N\u2082, and H\u2082O with trace NH\u2083. Their work detected **20 amino acids total**, and proline was confirmed as a minor but reproducible product. Johnson, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, Lazcano, and Bada (2008, *Science* 322:404) re-analyzed archived vials from Miller's \"volcanic\" apparatus and found 22 amino acids and 5 amines. More recently, Jiang and colleagues (2014, *Scientific Reports* 4:6769) detected all non-sulfur-containing natural amino acids including proline using LC-MS/MS. A critical analytical caveat, however, has caused systematic underreporting: the standard OPA/NAC derivatization method used in modern amino acid analysis **cannot detect proline** because it only reacts with primary amines. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, and colleagues (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) explicitly noted this limitation when re-analyzing Miller's H\u2082S-rich experiment\u2014proline detection was \"not possible\" with their methodology. This means proline's true abundance in spark discharge products is likely higher than commonly reported.\n\n**The cyanosulfidic chemistry route**, developed by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307), provides the most mechanistically detailed prebiotic pathway to proline. Starting from HCN, H\u2082S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling at **35\u00b0C in anoxic, neutral-pH conditions**, this network produces precursors to 12 proteinogenic amino acids through four chemical \"movements.\" Proline specifically arises through what the authors designate \"movement c\": a 4-carbon cyanohydrin reacts with H\u2082S to produce both an open-chain and a **cyclic \u03b1-hydroxythioamide**. UV irradiation then drives cyclization and deoxygenation to yield **\u03b3-butyrothiolactam**, which undergoes photoreduction and HCN addition to generate the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47 in the original paper). The elegance of this pathway lies in its inevitability\u2014the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage, requiring no enzymatic guidance. Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile then yields proline itself. This route connects proline synthesis to the broader cyanosulfidic network that simultaneously generates nucleotide and lipid precursors, suggesting a unified chemical origin for life's building blocks.\n\n**The glutamate-to-proline reductive amination pathway** mirrors the biological biosynthetic route and proceeds through well-characterized intermediates. Glutamic acid\u2014one of the most abundant amino acids in both spark discharge experiments and meteorites\u2014undergoes partial reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl group to form **glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)**. GSA then undergoes spontaneous, non-enzymatic intramolecular cyclization to form **\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)**, as first characterized by Vogel and Davis (1952, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 74:109\u2013112). This cyclization requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution\u2014making it one of the most prebiotically plausible steps in the entire pathway. Final reduction of P5C to proline could be driven by Fe\u00b2\u207a, FeS/H\u2082S systems, or molecular hydrogen from serpentinization. The biological pathway was further elucidated by Strecker (1957, *Journal of Biological Chemistry* 225:825\u2013834), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids can be reductively aminated to amino acids on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces, establishing the prebiotic feasibility of the first step.\n\n**HCN oligomerization**, first explored by Or\u00f3 in 1961, produces amino acids through polymer hydrolysis. Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (2013, *Life* 3:421\u2013448) reviewed 23 experimental conditions and found proline among the amino acids detected in some HCN polymer hydrolysis experiments, particularly those conducted at higher temperatures. The mechanism proceeds through diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, the HCN tetramer) and hydantoin intermediates.\n\n---\n\n## The intermediate network reveals key branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of proline connects to a broader metabolic-like network of chemical transformations, with **\u03b1-ketoglutarate serving as the central branch-point intermediate**. This TCA-cycle compound sits at the intersection of carbon metabolism and amino acid synthesis, feeding the glutamate family: glutamate, glutamine, proline, and arginine.\n\nRecent work has demonstrated prebiotically plausible routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate itself. Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, *Nature Chemistry* 12:1016\u20131022) showed that \u03b1-keto acid chemistry can reproduce key features of the TCA cycle without enzymes. Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, *Nature Communications* 9:91) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative decarboxylation of glyoxylate as protometabolic analogs. Most recently, Krishnamurthy's group (2025) demonstrated formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from just two amino acids\u2014serine and glycine\u2014via pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu\u00b2\u207a catalysis. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry*) then showed \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate.\n\nThe pathway from glutamate to proline passes through three intermediates, each with distinct prebiotic significance:\n\n- **Glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)** is the open-chain form that requires reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl group. In biology, this is accomplished by NADPH; prebiotically, FeS/H\u2082S or Fe\u00b2\u207a could serve as reductants.\n- **\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)** forms spontaneously from GSA through intramolecular imine formation. This non-enzymatic cyclization is the crucial ring-closing step that creates proline's pyrrolidine skeleton.\n- **Ornithine** represents an alternative entry point. In biology, ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase converts ornithine to GSA, and ornithine cyclodeaminase can convert ornithine directly to proline. Whether similar non-enzymatic transformations occur under prebiotic conditions remains unexplored.\n\nProline ranks approximately **eighth to ninth in prebiotic amino acid abundance** according to the analysis of Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483\u2013490), who classified it among the \"early 10\" amino acids\u2014those reliably produced in Miller experiments, found in meteorites, and thermodynamically favorable. The ranking correlates with Gibbs free energy of formation data from Amend and Shock (1998). Among the early amino acids (Gly > Ala > Asp > Glu > Val > Ser > Ile/Leu > Pro > Thr), proline's lower abundance reflects the additional thermodynamic cost of ring formation.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents and volcanic hot springs offer complementary settings\n\nThe environmental conditions most favorable for prebiotic proline synthesis depend on which pathway is operative, with different settings favoring different reaction steps.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** of the Lost City type (Kelley et al., 2001) provide temperatures of **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, and abundant H\u2082 and CH\u2084 from serpentinization of ultramafic peridotite. These reducing conditions favor reductive amination reactions. M\u00e9nez and colleagues (2018, *Nature* 564:59\u201363) discovered abiotic tryptophan in serpentinite rocks beneath Lost City, trapped in iron-rich saponite clays\u2014the first direct evidence of amino acid formation through purely abiotic geochemical processes in a natural hydrothermal system. The Russell and Hall model (1997, 2006) proposed that Fe(II)-bearing hydroxides, sulfides, and carbonates in alkaline vent chimneys could drive CO\u2082 reduction and amino acid synthesis via electrochemical gradients across mineral membranes.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (>300\u00b0C, acidic, metal sulfide-rich) present a stability challenge. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) argued that submarine hot springs are net destroyers of organic compounds. However, **proline's pyrrolidine ring confers enhanced thermal stability** compared to many other amino acids. Li and Brill (2003, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A* 107:5987\u20135992) studied proline decarboxylation kinetics at 270\u2013340\u00b0C and 275 bar, finding relatively slow decomposition rates independent of pH between 3 and 8.5. Vallentyne (1968) found proline to be more stable than leucine, arginine, and lysine under hydrothermal conditions. Notably, Vallentyne also identified proline as a degradation product of arginine\u2014suggesting a secondary prebiotic route to proline through thermal processing of other amino acids.\n\n**Volcanic hot spring pools on land** represent a third setting championed by Damer and Deamer (2020, *Astrobiology* 20:429\u2013452) in the \"Hot Spring Hypothesis.\" These fluctuating pools at **60\u201390\u00b0C** provide three energy sources simultaneously: thermal energy, dehydration-rehydration chemical potential, and UV light. Van Kranendonk and colleagues (2020, *Astrobiology*) showed that the **3.48 billion-year-old Dresser Formation** in Western Australia's Pilbara Craton preserves evidence of such terrestrial hot springs, including geyserite, concentrated boron (in tourmaline), phosphate-bearing hydrothermal veins, and smectite/illite clays\u2014all cofactors for prebiotic chemistry. Wet-dry cycling in these settings drives peptide bond formation that is thermodynamically unfavorable in bulk water, as demonstrated by Ross and Deamer (2016, *Life* 6:28) and Forsythe and colleagues (2015, *Angewandte Chemie* 54:9871\u20139875).\n\nThe cyanosulfidic route to proline (Patel et al. 2015) operates under yet another set of conditions: **35\u00b0C, neutral pH, anoxic atmosphere** with UV irradiation, Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling, and phosphate buffer\u2014conditions potentially realized in shallow, UV-exposed pools on early Earth's surface.\n\n---\n\n## Iron-sulfur minerals and nickel catalysts drive key transformations\n\nMineral catalysis is essential for several steps in prebiotic proline synthesis, with iron-sulfur and nickel-iron systems playing the most prominent roles.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** drives W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's \"pyrite-pulled\" reactions, where the thermodynamically favorable formation of pyrite from FeS provides reducing equivalents: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on freshly precipitated FeS at 100\u00b0C, with strong metal specificity\u2014other metal sulfides failed to produce amino acids. Muchowska and colleagues (2017, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 1:1716\u20131721) showed pyrite drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates including the proline precursor \u03b1-ketoglutarate. **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** is structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] clusters in modern metalloenzymes, particularly acetyl-CoA synthase (Li et al. 2018, *Life* 8:46), positioning it as a proto-enzymatic catalyst for CO\u2082 fixation and reductive transformations in hydrothermal mound chimneys.\n\nA landmark recent study by Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, *Chem* 10:1528\u20131540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H\u2082 and NH\u2083 over **nickel catalysts** at remarkably mild conditions: **22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1\u201310 bar H\u2082**. Using Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) or even ground meteorites (11\u201318 mol% Ni) as catalysts, this system produces seven biological amino acids from reductive amination of keto acids, including **glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate**. The pathway generates \u03b1-ketoglutarate\u2014the direct precursor to glutamate and, through the GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade, to proline itself.\n\n**Montmorillonite clay** catalyzes amino acid polymerization, as demonstrated extensively by Ferris and colleagues (1996, *Nature* 381:59\u201361; 2006, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B* 361:1777\u20131786). Clay surfaces concentrate monomers in interlayer environments, catalyzing condensation at rates **100\u20131,000 times greater than hydrolysis**. Bujdak and colleagues (1994, *Monatshefte f\u00fcr Chemie* 125:1033\u20131039) showed montmorillonite catalyzes peptide formation from glycine in evaporation cycles. While specific proline-clay interaction data remain sparse, the negative layer charge of montmorillonite attracts amino acid ammonium groups, and Namani and colleagues (2021, *ChemSystemsChem*) showed prebiotically relevant amino acids enhance montmorillonite-catalyzed RNA polymerization cooperatively.\n\n**TiO\u2082 photocatalysis** offers another mineral-driven route. Saladino and colleagues (2017) demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of amino acids from formamide under UV irradiation on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Rutile, a common early Earth mineral, could have driven amino acid formation in UV-exposed shallow water environments.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic proline and the underreporting problem\n\nProline was among the earliest amino acids identified in the Murchison meteorite. Kvenvolden, Lawless, and colleagues (1970, *Nature* 228:923\u2013926) detected proline alongside glycine, alanine, glutamic acid, and valine by ion-exchange chromatography and capillary gas chromatography. Critically, they reported \"almost equal amounts of the D and L enantiomers of valine, proline, alanine, and glutamic acid\"\u2014near-racemic ratios that argued strongly for abiotic origin and against terrestrial biological contamination. Cronin and Moore (1971, *Science* 172:1327\u20131329) confirmed proline in extended analyses of Murchison, Murray, and Allende chondrites.\n\n**Quantitative concentrations** of proline in Murchison fall in the range of **~0.1\u20131 \u03bcg/g (ppm)**, making it a minor but consistent component of the meteoritic amino acid suite. For comparison, glycine\u2014the most abundant amino acid\u2014reaches 3\u20136 \u03bcg/g. The abundance pattern (decreasing with carbon number and structural complexity) is consistent with abiotic synthesis mechanisms, likely Strecker-cyanohydrin reactions on the meteorite parent body. Lerner and Cooper (2005, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 69:2901\u20132906) detected iminodicarboxylic acids in Murchison, providing direct evidence for Strecker-type reactions on the parent body.\n\nEngel and Nagy (1982, *Nature* 296:837\u2013840) reported L-excesses in protein amino acids from Murchison, including proline, but these results proved controversial due to potential contamination. Pizzarello and colleagues (2012, *PNAS*) analyzed the pristine CR chondrite GRA 95229 and found that **protein amino acids including proline were racemic** (D/L \u2248 1), while isovaline retained an L-excess of ~3%. This distinction is fundamental: proline has an \u03b1-hydrogen and racemizes readily during aqueous alteration, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess. The \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids (isovaline, \u03b1-methylisoleucine) lack this vulnerable hydrogen and preserve their original chirality.\n\n---\n\n## The chirality puzzle: from small imbalances to biological homochirality\n\nHow L-proline could be selected over D-proline in prebiotic settings remains one of the deepest unresolved questions in origin-of-life research. The challenge is compounded by proline's facile racemization at the \u03b1-carbon, which erases any initial enantiomeric excess in aqueous solution.\n\n**Circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions represents the most widely discussed symmetry-breaking mechanism. Bailey and colleagues (1998, *Science* 281:672\u2013674) discovered ~17% circular polarization in infrared light from the Orion nebula, suggesting our presolar environment could have provided CPL. Meinert and colleagues (2014, *Astrophysical Journal* 788:79) irradiated interstellar ice analogs with synchrotron UV CPL and detected 24 amino acids including proline in the residues, with small but reproducible enantiomeric excesses. Meinert and colleagues (2022, *Nature Communications*) measured the first gas-phase circular dichroism spectra for amino acids including proline in the vacuum UV (130\u2013280 nm), revealing that **proline's five-membered nitrogen heterocycle produces unique spectral features**\u2014hypsochromic shifts distinguishing it from all open-chain amino acids. These anisotropy factors predict the ee inducible by CPL photolysis. However, maximum laboratory CPL-induced ee values remain **\u22642\u20133%**, and Glavin and Dworkin's (2009, *PNAS* 106:5487\u20135492) finding that pristine CR meteorites show no isovaline excess argues against CPL as the sole mechanism.\n\n**Chiral mineral surfaces** offer an alternative symmetry-breaking route. Hazen, Filley, and Goodfriend (2001, *PNAS* 98:5487\u20135490) demonstrated that calcite scalenohedral crystal faces selectively adsorb D- versus L-aspartic acid, with terraced surfaces showing the greatest selectivity. The mechanism requires three non-colinear configuration-dependent interaction points between molecule and surface. Alanine, with only two bonding points, showed no enantioselectivity. **No published data exist for proline adsorption on chiral calcite surfaces**, representing a significant experimental gap. Proline's rigid pyrrolidine ring and carboxylate group provide a distinctive molecular geometry that could create specific three-point contacts, but this remains untested.\n\n**Chiral amplification mechanisms** are essential to bridge the gap from small initial ee values (1\u20133%) to biological homochirality (100% L). Three mechanisms are particularly relevant to proline:\n\n- **Crystal-solution eutectic amplification**: Hayashi, Koshino, and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 45:4593\u20134597) achieved the most dramatic amplification demonstrated for any amino acid. DL-proline racemic crystals have more hydrogen bonds and are less soluble than enantiopure crystals. When solid proline of **only 10% ee** was dissolved in CHCl\u2083/EtOH, the solution reached **85\u201399% ee** as the racemic crystals preferentially remained undissolved. Klussmann and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) calculated the eutectic ee for proline as ~76.5% in certain solvents. The limitation is that CHCl\u2083/EtOH is not prebiotically plausible; finding aqueous conditions that replicate this effect remains an open challenge.\n\n- **Proline-mediated autoinductive catalysis**: Mathew, Iwamura, and Blackmond (2004, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) showed that proline-catalyzed \u03b1-aminoxylation of aldehydes exhibits accelerating reaction rates (autoinduction) and ee amplification over time. Products form adducts with proline that act as more efficient catalysts\u2014the first general organic chemistry strategy implicating amino acid catalysis in a selectivity-enhancing autoinductive process.\n\n- **Proline as organocatalyst**: List, Lerner, and Barbas III (2000, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 122:2395) discovered that L-proline catalyzes intermolecular asymmetric aldol reactions with **up to >99% enantioselectivity**, operating through an enamine mechanism via a Zimmerman-Traxler transition state. The pyrrolidine ring constrains the transition state geometry, and both ring size and carboxyl group are essential\u2014making proline uniquely suited among all amino acids. This dual identity as both a product of prebiotic synthesis and a powerful asymmetric catalyst raises the tantalizing possibility of a self-reinforcing chiral feedback loop, though true autocatalysis (proline catalyzing its own formation) has not been demonstrated.\n\nThe **Soai reaction** (Soai et al., 1995) demonstrates that autocatalytic amplification from ee as low as ~0.00005% to >99.5% is chemically possible, but requires anhydrous dialkylzinc chemistry incompatible with aqueous prebiotic conditions. It serves as proof-of-concept for Frank's (1953, *Biochimica et Biophysica Acta* 11:459) theoretical model of spontaneous symmetry breaking through autocatalysis plus mutual inhibition. **Parity violation** in the weak nuclear force creates energy differences of only ~10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 J/mol between enantiomers (Quack 2002, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 41:4618)\u2014many orders of magnitude below thermal energy and universally considered irrelevant to biological homochirality.\n\n---\n\n## Persistent bottlenecks and the road ahead\n\nSeveral fundamental challenges remain unresolved in the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline.\n\n**The concentration problem** is perhaps the most severe. Prebiotic amino acid concentrations in the primitive ocean are estimated at **micromolar or lower** levels\u2014far below the millimolar-to-molar concentrations typically used in laboratory demonstrations. Evaporative concentration in closed-basin pools, mineral surface adsorption, and fatty acid membrane binding (Cornell et al. 2019, *PNAS*) offer partial solutions, but no single mechanism convincingly bridges this gap for proline specifically. Campbell and Bracher (2019, *Nature Communications* 10:4508) showed deliquescent minerals increase glycine oligomerization yields over 10-fold during wet-dry cycles, but proline-specific data are lacking.\n\n**The selectivity problem** concerns how to generate proline preferentially rather than as a trace component in a complex mixture. In Miller-type experiments, glycine dominates and proline is a minor product. The cyanosulfidic route produces proline alongside many other amino acids and molecular classes. Any prebiotic scenario must explain not only proline's formation but its accumulation at biologically relevant concentrations.\n\n**The racemization problem** is acute for proline. Unlike \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids such as isovaline (which preserve meteoritic L-ee of up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.6%**, Glavin and Dworkin 2009), proline's \u03b1-hydrogen makes it vulnerable to base-catalyzed racemization in water. Any enantiomeric excess must be continuously regenerated or amplified faster than racemization erases it. The crystal-solution eutectic amplification demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino (2006) achieves this in organic solvents, but translating this mechanism to aqueous prebiotic conditions remains undemonstrated.\n\n**The ring-formation step** is what makes proline uniquely challenging among prebiotic amino acids. While the GSA \u2192 P5C cyclization is spontaneous, accessing GSA requires selective reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl to an aldehyde without reducing the \u03b1-carboxyl\u2014a chemically demanding transformation. The cyanosulfidic route elegantly sidesteps this by forming the ring at the thiolactam stage, but whether this specific photochemistry operated at relevant scales on early Earth is debated.\n\nSeveral experimental gaps deserve attention. No studies have tested **enantioselective adsorption of proline on chiral mineral surfaces** (calcite, quartz). The **crystal-solution eutectic effect** has not been demonstrated for proline in water. The full pathway from simple feedstocks (CO\u2082, N\u2082, H\u2082O) to proline has never been achieved in a single continuous experimental system. And the OPA/NAC derivatization limitation means proline abundances in many published prebiotic experiments may need systematic re-evaluation using methods capable of detecting secondary amines.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nProline stands at a fascinating intersection in prebiotic chemistry\u2014structurally the most unusual of the coded amino acids, yet demonstrably accessible through at least four independent abiotic pathways. The cyanosulfidic route of Patel and Sutherland (2015) provides the most compelling single-flask demonstration, with ring formation arising naturally from the geometry of 4-carbon thioamide intermediates rather than requiring any specialized cyclization step. The glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline pathway, featuring a spontaneous non-enzymatic cyclization, connects proline to the broader protometabolic network centered on \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Proline's enhanced thermal stability\u2014its pyrrolidine ring resists decarboxylation better than many open-chain amino acids\u2014gives it a selective survival advantage in hydrothermal environments.\n\nThe chirality problem, however, remains proline's deepest challenge. Its \u03b1-hydrogen ensures rapid aqueous racemization, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess and distinguishing it from the \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids that preserve meteoritic L-enrichment. The remarkable crystal-solution eutectic amplification (10% to 85\u201399% ee) demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino has not been replicated under prebiotically relevant aqueous conditions. Perhaps most intriguing is proline's dual identity as both a prebiotic product and a uniquely powerful organocatalyst for asymmetric synthesis. Whether this creates a genuine self-reinforcing feedback loop\u2014where a small excess of L-proline catalyzes reactions that preferentially generate or preserve more L-proline\u2014remains the central open question. The answer could illuminate not just proline's origin but the emergence of biological homochirality itself.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is an impressively comprehensive synthesis network for L-Proline that captures all four major prebiotic routes described in the literature: cyanosulfidic photochemistry (Patel et al. 2015), glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C cascade, HCN oligomerization, and formamide photolysis. The five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, \u03b1KG, glutamate, P5C) create genuine convergence and the network topology is well-connected with no isolated subgraphs.\n\n**Strengths:** (1) Excellent literature alignment\u2014nearly every major finding from the research is represented, including Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user reductive amination, Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry, Muchowska proto-TCA cycles, Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and Saladino formamide photolysis. (2) Strong network topology with 5 hub molecules at degree \u22653 (except P5C at degree 2), 5 convergence points, and 10 pathways providing redundancy. (3) Good environmental transitions with mineral agents specified for most hydrothermal reactions (greigite, magnetite, pyrite, NiFeS). (4) The spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization (rxn_008) is one of the most prebiotically robust steps, scoring 0.95.\n\n**Weaknesses:** (1) The recurring rxn_007 (glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the network's Achilles heel\u2014the literature explicitly flags this as 'chemically demanding' and no convincing prebiotic reductant is specified. This affects 7 of 10 pathways. (2) rxn_010 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol) oversimplifies the multi-step Patel et al. mechanism, omitting the critical Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. (3) rxn_015 (DAMN \u2192 proline directly) is chemically implausible as written\u2014many intermediates are skipped. (4) The 'L-' designation in the target is not addressed anywhere in the network. The literature emphasizes that proline racemizes readily at the \u03b1-carbon and no enantioselection mechanism is included. (5) Several surface reactions lack mineral agent specification (rxn_004, rxn_006, rxn_010, rxn_014, rxn_015). (6) P5C (mol_014) has degree 2, below the hub threshold.\n\n**Missing elements:** Ornithine as alternative entry point to GSA (noted in literature), concentration mechanisms, the OPA/NAC detection limitation context, and any chirality amplification (crystal-solution eutectic, chiral mineral surfaces, or proline's organocatalytic self-reinforcement). Kaur et al. (2024) mild-condition Ni catalysis could strengthen rxn_005.\n\nOverall, this is a strong network that successfully integrates multiple prebiotic chemistry paradigms into a coherent whole. Four pathways meet the approval threshold, with P3 (cyanosulfidic) being the best-supported single pathway despite its oversimplification at rxn_010.\n- Issues: ['Similar to P1 but uses Bucherer-Bergs synthesis (rxn_006) for glutamate formation, directly supported by Pulletikurti et al. (2022). This is a slight improvement over P1 for the amination step since the Bucherer-Bergs mechanism is well-characterized. However, it requires HCN as an additional input without specifying its source within this pathway (it must come from P5/P6 routes or external). The same weakness at rxn_007 persists. The Surface environment for rxn_006 needs mineral specification.', 'Severely oversimplified pathway. While HCN\u2192DAMN (rxn_014) is well-established (Or\u00f3 1961), the direct conversion DAMN\u2192proline (rxn_015) skips critical intermediates including hydantoin formation and complex polymer hydrolysis steps. Literature (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013) describes proline as a minor product of HCN polymer hydrolysis under specific high-temperature conditions. The pathway has only 2 steps with no hydrothermal involvement and no mineral agents specified. Proline would be a trace component of a complex mixture\u2014selectivity is extremely poor.', 'Combines formamide photolysis with HCN oligomerization. Better environmental progression than P4 (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Surface), but still hampered by the problematic rxn_015 (DAMN\u2192proline direct conversion). The formamide-to-HCN portion is well-supported but cannot rescue the fundamentally flawed final step.', 'Combines proto-TCA \u03b1KG formation with Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis. Good convergence of two literature-supported routes but inherits both the rxn_007 weakness and the need for an external HCN source. The pathway demonstrates good network convergence properties.', \"Combines surface glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004) with elements from both P1 and P7. Provides alternative convergence point at \u03b1KG. Same recurring weakness at rxn_007. The glyoxylate route is supported by Springsteen et al. (2018) and Krishnamurthy's group.\", 'The longest pathway at 10 steps, combining formamide photolysis, Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and surface \u03b1KG formation. While it demonstrates maximum network connectivity and environmental progression, the length introduces cumulative yield concerns. Each additional step reduces overall plausibility. Still hampered by rxn_007 and the questionable direct glyoxylate formation.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 6380.640983581543, "success": false, "error_message": "{'type': 'error', 'error': {'details': None, 'type': 'api_error', 'message': 'Internal server error'}, 'request_id': 'req_011CZ8VqGy7SMEfxcyUHVAVt'}"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T06:33:01.345925", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of L-Proline: routes, challenges, and the chirality puzzle\n\n**Proline is among the most structurally distinctive amino acids to form under prebiotic conditions, yet multiple independent lines of evidence confirm its abiotic synthesis.** As the only proteinogenic amino acid with a cyclic secondary amine (pyrrolidine ring), proline demands ring-closing chemistry that sets it apart from all other coded amino acids. Despite this structural complexity, proline has been detected in Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments, carbonaceous chondrite meteorites, and has been shown to emerge naturally from cyanosulfidic photochemistry. These converging lines of evidence place proline among the \"early\" amino acids accessible on prebiotic Earth\u2014ranking approximately eighth to ninth in abiotic abundance. Yet its path to biological homochirality remains one of the most challenging puzzles in origin-of-life chemistry, complicated by rapid aqueous racemization at its \u03b1-carbon and the difficulty of concentrating it from dilute prebiotic solutions.\n\n---\n\n## Multiple prebiotic routes converge on the pyrrolidine ring\n\nAt least four independent chemical pathways produce proline under plausibly prebiotic conditions, each starting from different simple feedstock molecules and operating through distinct mechanisms.\n\n**The Miller-Urey spark discharge route** represents the earliest experimental demonstration. Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* 69:765\u2013768) definitively identified proline by both ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS in electric discharge experiments using CH\u2084, N\u2082, and H\u2082O with trace NH\u2083. Their work detected **20 amino acids total**, and proline was confirmed as a minor but reproducible product. Johnson, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, Lazcano, and Bada (2008, *Science* 322:404) re-analyzed archived vials from Miller's \"volcanic\" apparatus and found 22 amino acids and 5 amines. More recently, Jiang and colleagues (2014, *Scientific Reports* 4:6769) detected all non-sulfur-containing natural amino acids including proline using LC-MS/MS. A critical analytical caveat, however, has caused systematic underreporting: the standard OPA/NAC derivatization method used in modern amino acid analysis **cannot detect proline** because it only reacts with primary amines. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, and colleagues (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) explicitly noted this limitation when re-analyzing Miller's H\u2082S-rich experiment\u2014proline detection was \"not possible\" with their methodology. This means proline's true abundance in spark discharge products is likely higher than commonly reported.\n\n**The cyanosulfidic chemistry route**, developed by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307), provides the most mechanistically detailed prebiotic pathway to proline. Starting from HCN, H\u2082S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling at **35\u00b0C in anoxic, neutral-pH conditions**, this network produces precursors to 12 proteinogenic amino acids through four chemical \"movements.\" Proline specifically arises through what the authors designate \"movement c\": a 4-carbon cyanohydrin reacts with H\u2082S to produce both an open-chain and a **cyclic \u03b1-hydroxythioamide**. UV irradiation then drives cyclization and deoxygenation to yield **\u03b3-butyrothiolactam**, which undergoes photoreduction and HCN addition to generate the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47 in the original paper). The elegance of this pathway lies in its inevitability\u2014the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage, requiring no enzymatic guidance. Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile then yields proline itself. This route connects proline synthesis to the broader cyanosulfidic network that simultaneously generates nucleotide and lipid precursors, suggesting a unified chemical origin for life's building blocks.\n\n**The glutamate-to-proline reductive amination pathway** mirrors the biological biosynthetic route and proceeds through well-characterized intermediates. Glutamic acid\u2014one of the most abundant amino acids in both spark discharge experiments and meteorites\u2014undergoes partial reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl group to form **glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)**. GSA then undergoes spontaneous, non-enzymatic intramolecular cyclization to form **\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)**, as first characterized by Vogel and Davis (1952, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 74:109\u2013112). This cyclization requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution\u2014making it one of the most prebiotically plausible steps in the entire pathway. Final reduction of P5C to proline could be driven by Fe\u00b2\u207a, FeS/H\u2082S systems, or molecular hydrogen from serpentinization. The biological pathway was further elucidated by Strecker (1957, *Journal of Biological Chemistry* 225:825\u2013834), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids can be reductively aminated to amino acids on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces, establishing the prebiotic feasibility of the first step.\n\n**HCN oligomerization**, first explored by Or\u00f3 in 1961, produces amino acids through polymer hydrolysis. Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (2013, *Life* 3:421\u2013448) reviewed 23 experimental conditions and found proline among the amino acids detected in some HCN polymer hydrolysis experiments, particularly those conducted at higher temperatures. The mechanism proceeds through diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, the HCN tetramer) and hydantoin intermediates.\n\n---\n\n## The intermediate network reveals key branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of proline connects to a broader metabolic-like network of chemical transformations, with **\u03b1-ketoglutarate serving as the central branch-point intermediate**. This TCA-cycle compound sits at the intersection of carbon metabolism and amino acid synthesis, feeding the glutamate family: glutamate, glutamine, proline, and arginine.\n\nRecent work has demonstrated prebiotically plausible routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate itself. Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, *Nature Chemistry* 12:1016\u20131022) showed that \u03b1-keto acid chemistry can reproduce key features of the TCA cycle without enzymes. Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, *Nature Communications* 9:91) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative decarboxylation of glyoxylate as protometabolic analogs. Most recently, Krishnamurthy's group (2025) demonstrated formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from just two amino acids\u2014serine and glycine\u2014via pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu\u00b2\u207a catalysis. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry*) then showed \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate.\n\nThe pathway from glutamate to proline passes through three intermediates, each with distinct prebiotic significance:\n\n- **Glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)** is the open-chain form that requires reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl group. In biology, this is accomplished by NADPH; prebiotically, FeS/H\u2082S or Fe\u00b2\u207a could serve as reductants.\n- **\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)** forms spontaneously from GSA through intramolecular imine formation. This non-enzymatic cyclization is the crucial ring-closing step that creates proline's pyrrolidine skeleton.\n- **Ornithine** represents an alternative entry point. In biology, ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase converts ornithine to GSA, and ornithine cyclodeaminase can convert ornithine directly to proline. Whether similar non-enzymatic transformations occur under prebiotic conditions remains unexplored.\n\nProline ranks approximately **eighth to ninth in prebiotic amino acid abundance** according to the analysis of Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483\u2013490), who classified it among the \"early 10\" amino acids\u2014those reliably produced in Miller experiments, found in meteorites, and thermodynamically favorable. The ranking correlates with Gibbs free energy of formation data from Amend and Shock (1998). Among the early amino acids (Gly > Ala > Asp > Glu > Val > Ser > Ile/Leu > Pro > Thr), proline's lower abundance reflects the additional thermodynamic cost of ring formation.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents and volcanic hot springs offer complementary settings\n\nThe environmental conditions most favorable for prebiotic proline synthesis depend on which pathway is operative, with different settings favoring different reaction steps.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** of the Lost City type (Kelley et al., 2001) provide temperatures of **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, and abundant H\u2082 and CH\u2084 from serpentinization of ultramafic peridotite. These reducing conditions favor reductive amination reactions. M\u00e9nez and colleagues (2018, *Nature* 564:59\u201363) discovered abiotic tryptophan in serpentinite rocks beneath Lost City, trapped in iron-rich saponite clays\u2014the first direct evidence of amino acid formation through purely abiotic geochemical processes in a natural hydrothermal system. The Russell and Hall model (1997, 2006) proposed that Fe(II)-bearing hydroxides, sulfides, and carbonates in alkaline vent chimneys could drive CO\u2082 reduction and amino acid synthesis via electrochemical gradients across mineral membranes.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (>300\u00b0C, acidic, metal sulfide-rich) present a stability challenge. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) argued that submarine hot springs are net destroyers of organic compounds. However, **proline's pyrrolidine ring confers enhanced thermal stability** compared to many other amino acids. Li and Brill (2003, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A* 107:5987\u20135992) studied proline decarboxylation kinetics at 270\u2013340\u00b0C and 275 bar, finding relatively slow decomposition rates independent of pH between 3 and 8.5. Vallentyne (1968) found proline to be more stable than leucine, arginine, and lysine under hydrothermal conditions. Notably, Vallentyne also identified proline as a degradation product of arginine\u2014suggesting a secondary prebiotic route to proline through thermal processing of other amino acids.\n\n**Volcanic hot spring pools on land** represent a third setting championed by Damer and Deamer (2020, *Astrobiology* 20:429\u2013452) in the \"Hot Spring Hypothesis.\" These fluctuating pools at **60\u201390\u00b0C** provide three energy sources simultaneously: thermal energy, dehydration-rehydration chemical potential, and UV light. Van Kranendonk and colleagues (2020, *Astrobiology*) showed that the **3.48 billion-year-old Dresser Formation** in Western Australia's Pilbara Craton preserves evidence of such terrestrial hot springs, including geyserite, concentrated boron (in tourmaline), phosphate-bearing hydrothermal veins, and smectite/illite clays\u2014all cofactors for prebiotic chemistry. Wet-dry cycling in these settings drives peptide bond formation that is thermodynamically unfavorable in bulk water, as demonstrated by Ross and Deamer (2016, *Life* 6:28) and Forsythe and colleagues (2015, *Angewandte Chemie* 54:9871\u20139875).\n\nThe cyanosulfidic route to proline (Patel et al. 2015) operates under yet another set of conditions: **35\u00b0C, neutral pH, anoxic atmosphere** with UV irradiation, Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling, and phosphate buffer\u2014conditions potentially realized in shallow, UV-exposed pools on early Earth's surface.\n\n---\n\n## Iron-sulfur minerals and nickel catalysts drive key transformations\n\nMineral catalysis is essential for several steps in prebiotic proline synthesis, with iron-sulfur and nickel-iron systems playing the most prominent roles.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** drives W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's \"pyrite-pulled\" reactions, where the thermodynamically favorable formation of pyrite from FeS provides reducing equivalents: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on freshly precipitated FeS at 100\u00b0C, with strong metal specificity\u2014other metal sulfides failed to produce amino acids. Muchowska and colleagues (2017, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 1:1716\u20131721) showed pyrite drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates including the proline precursor \u03b1-ketoglutarate. **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** is structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] clusters in modern metalloenzymes, particularly acetyl-CoA synthase (Li et al. 2018, *Life* 8:46), positioning it as a proto-enzymatic catalyst for CO\u2082 fixation and reductive transformations in hydrothermal mound chimneys.\n\nA landmark recent study by Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, *Chem* 10:1528\u20131540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H\u2082 and NH\u2083 over **nickel catalysts** at remarkably mild conditions: **22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1\u201310 bar H\u2082**. Using Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) or even ground meteorites (11\u201318 mol% Ni) as catalysts, this system produces seven biological amino acids from reductive amination of keto acids, including **glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate**. The pathway generates \u03b1-ketoglutarate\u2014the direct precursor to glutamate and, through the GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade, to proline itself.\n\n**Montmorillonite clay** catalyzes amino acid polymerization, as demonstrated extensively by Ferris and colleagues (1996, *Nature* 381:59\u201361; 2006, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B* 361:1777\u20131786). Clay surfaces concentrate monomers in interlayer environments, catalyzing condensation at rates **100\u20131,000 times greater than hydrolysis**. Bujdak and colleagues (1994, *Monatshefte f\u00fcr Chemie* 125:1033\u20131039) showed montmorillonite catalyzes peptide formation from glycine in evaporation cycles. While specific proline-clay interaction data remain sparse, the negative layer charge of montmorillonite attracts amino acid ammonium groups, and Namani and colleagues (2021, *ChemSystemsChem*) showed prebiotically relevant amino acids enhance montmorillonite-catalyzed RNA polymerization cooperatively.\n\n**TiO\u2082 photocatalysis** offers another mineral-driven route. Saladino and colleagues (2017) demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of amino acids from formamide under UV irradiation on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Rutile, a common early Earth mineral, could have driven amino acid formation in UV-exposed shallow water environments.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic proline and the underreporting problem\n\nProline was among the earliest amino acids identified in the Murchison meteorite. Kvenvolden, Lawless, and colleagues (1970, *Nature* 228:923\u2013926) detected proline alongside glycine, alanine, glutamic acid, and valine by ion-exchange chromatography and capillary gas chromatography. Critically, they reported \"almost equal amounts of the D and L enantiomers of valine, proline, alanine, and glutamic acid\"\u2014near-racemic ratios that argued strongly for abiotic origin and against terrestrial biological contamination. Cronin and Moore (1971, *Science* 172:1327\u20131329) confirmed proline in extended analyses of Murchison, Murray, and Allende chondrites.\n\n**Quantitative concentrations** of proline in Murchison fall in the range of **~0.1\u20131 \u03bcg/g (ppm)**, making it a minor but consistent component of the meteoritic amino acid suite. For comparison, glycine\u2014the most abundant amino acid\u2014reaches 3\u20136 \u03bcg/g. The abundance pattern (decreasing with carbon number and structural complexity) is consistent with abiotic synthesis mechanisms, likely Strecker-cyanohydrin reactions on the meteorite parent body. Lerner and Cooper (2005, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 69:2901\u20132906) detected iminodicarboxylic acids in Murchison, providing direct evidence for Strecker-type reactions on the parent body.\n\nEngel and Nagy (1982, *Nature* 296:837\u2013840) reported L-excesses in protein amino acids from Murchison, including proline, but these results proved controversial due to potential contamination. Pizzarello and colleagues (2012, *PNAS*) analyzed the pristine CR chondrite GRA 95229 and found that **protein amino acids including proline were racemic** (D/L \u2248 1), while isovaline retained an L-excess of ~3%. This distinction is fundamental: proline has an \u03b1-hydrogen and racemizes readily during aqueous alteration, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess. The \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids (isovaline, \u03b1-methylisoleucine) lack this vulnerable hydrogen and preserve their original chirality.\n\n---\n\n## The chirality puzzle: from small imbalances to biological homochirality\n\nHow L-proline could be selected over D-proline in prebiotic settings remains one of the deepest unresolved questions in origin-of-life research. The challenge is compounded by proline's facile racemization at the \u03b1-carbon, which erases any initial enantiomeric excess in aqueous solution.\n\n**Circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions represents the most widely discussed symmetry-breaking mechanism. Bailey and colleagues (1998, *Science* 281:672\u2013674) discovered ~17% circular polarization in infrared light from the Orion nebula, suggesting our presolar environment could have provided CPL. Meinert and colleagues (2014, *Astrophysical Journal* 788:79) irradiated interstellar ice analogs with synchrotron UV CPL and detected 24 amino acids including proline in the residues, with small but reproducible enantiomeric excesses. Meinert and colleagues (2022, *Nature Communications*) measured the first gas-phase circular dichroism spectra for amino acids including proline in the vacuum UV (130\u2013280 nm), revealing that **proline's five-membered nitrogen heterocycle produces unique spectral features**\u2014hypsochromic shifts distinguishing it from all open-chain amino acids. These anisotropy factors predict the ee inducible by CPL photolysis. However, maximum laboratory CPL-induced ee values remain **\u22642\u20133%**, and Glavin and Dworkin's (2009, *PNAS* 106:5487\u20135492) finding that pristine CR meteorites show no isovaline excess argues against CPL as the sole mechanism.\n\n**Chiral mineral surfaces** offer an alternative symmetry-breaking route. Hazen, Filley, and Goodfriend (2001, *PNAS* 98:5487\u20135490) demonstrated that calcite scalenohedral crystal faces selectively adsorb D- versus L-aspartic acid, with terraced surfaces showing the greatest selectivity. The mechanism requires three non-colinear configuration-dependent interaction points between molecule and surface. Alanine, with only two bonding points, showed no enantioselectivity. **No published data exist for proline adsorption on chiral calcite surfaces**, representing a significant experimental gap. Proline's rigid pyrrolidine ring and carboxylate group provide a distinctive molecular geometry that could create specific three-point contacts, but this remains untested.\n\n**Chiral amplification mechanisms** are essential to bridge the gap from small initial ee values (1\u20133%) to biological homochirality (100% L). Three mechanisms are particularly relevant to proline:\n\n- **Crystal-solution eutectic amplification**: Hayashi, Koshino, and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 45:4593\u20134597) achieved the most dramatic amplification demonstrated for any amino acid. DL-proline racemic crystals have more hydrogen bonds and are less soluble than enantiopure crystals. When solid proline of **only 10% ee** was dissolved in CHCl\u2083/EtOH, the solution reached **85\u201399% ee** as the racemic crystals preferentially remained undissolved. Klussmann and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) calculated the eutectic ee for proline as ~76.5% in certain solvents. The limitation is that CHCl\u2083/EtOH is not prebiotically plausible; finding aqueous conditions that replicate this effect remains an open challenge.\n\n- **Proline-mediated autoinductive catalysis**: Mathew, Iwamura, and Blackmond (2004, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) showed that proline-catalyzed \u03b1-aminoxylation of aldehydes exhibits accelerating reaction rates (autoinduction) and ee amplification over time. Products form adducts with proline that act as more efficient catalysts\u2014the first general organic chemistry strategy implicating amino acid catalysis in a selectivity-enhancing autoinductive process.\n\n- **Proline as organocatalyst**: List, Lerner, and Barbas III (2000, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 122:2395) discovered that L-proline catalyzes intermolecular asymmetric aldol reactions with **up to >99% enantioselectivity**, operating through an enamine mechanism via a Zimmerman-Traxler transition state. The pyrrolidine ring constrains the transition state geometry, and both ring size and carboxyl group are essential\u2014making proline uniquely suited among all amino acids. This dual identity as both a product of prebiotic synthesis and a powerful asymmetric catalyst raises the tantalizing possibility of a self-reinforcing chiral feedback loop, though true autocatalysis (proline catalyzing its own formation) has not been demonstrated.\n\nThe **Soai reaction** (Soai et al., 1995) demonstrates that autocatalytic amplification from ee as low as ~0.00005% to >99.5% is chemically possible, but requires anhydrous dialkylzinc chemistry incompatible with aqueous prebiotic conditions. It serves as proof-of-concept for Frank's (1953, *Biochimica et Biophysica Acta* 11:459) theoretical model of spontaneous symmetry breaking through autocatalysis plus mutual inhibition. **Parity violation** in the weak nuclear force creates energy differences of only ~10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 J/mol between enantiomers (Quack 2002, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 41:4618)\u2014many orders of magnitude below thermal energy and universally considered irrelevant to biological homochirality.\n\n---\n\n## Persistent bottlenecks and the road ahead\n\nSeveral fundamental challenges remain unresolved in the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline.\n\n**The concentration problem** is perhaps the most severe. Prebiotic amino acid concentrations in the primitive ocean are estimated at **micromolar or lower** levels\u2014far below the millimolar-to-molar concentrations typically used in laboratory demonstrations. Evaporative concentration in closed-basin pools, mineral surface adsorption, and fatty acid membrane binding (Cornell et al. 2019, *PNAS*) offer partial solutions, but no single mechanism convincingly bridges this gap for proline specifically. Campbell and Bracher (2019, *Nature Communications* 10:4508) showed deliquescent minerals increase glycine oligomerization yields over 10-fold during wet-dry cycles, but proline-specific data are lacking.\n\n**The selectivity problem** concerns how to generate proline preferentially rather than as a trace component in a complex mixture. In Miller-type experiments, glycine dominates and proline is a minor product. The cyanosulfidic route produces proline alongside many other amino acids and molecular classes. Any prebiotic scenario must explain not only proline's formation but its accumulation at biologically relevant concentrations.\n\n**The racemization problem** is acute for proline. Unlike \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids such as isovaline (which preserve meteoritic L-ee of up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.6%**, Glavin and Dworkin 2009), proline's \u03b1-hydrogen makes it vulnerable to base-catalyzed racemization in water. Any enantiomeric excess must be continuously regenerated or amplified faster than racemization erases it. The crystal-solution eutectic amplification demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino (2006) achieves this in organic solvents, but translating this mechanism to aqueous prebiotic conditions remains undemonstrated.\n\n**The ring-formation step** is what makes proline uniquely challenging among prebiotic amino acids. While the GSA \u2192 P5C cyclization is spontaneous, accessing GSA requires selective reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl to an aldehyde without reducing the \u03b1-carboxyl\u2014a chemically demanding transformation. The cyanosulfidic route elegantly sidesteps this by forming the ring at the thiolactam stage, but whether this specific photochemistry operated at relevant scales on early Earth is debated.\n\nSeveral experimental gaps deserve attention. No studies have tested **enantioselective adsorption of proline on chiral mineral surfaces** (calcite, quartz). The **crystal-solution eutectic effect** has not been demonstrated for proline in water. The full pathway from simple feedstocks (CO\u2082, N\u2082, H\u2082O) to proline has never been achieved in a single continuous experimental system. And the OPA/NAC derivatization limitation means proline abundances in many published prebiotic experiments may need systematic re-evaluation using methods capable of detecting secondary amines.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nProline stands at a fascinating intersection in prebiotic chemistry\u2014structurally the most unusual of the coded amino acids, yet demonstrably accessible through at least four independent abiotic pathways. The cyanosulfidic route of Patel and Sutherland (2015) provides the most compelling single-flask demonstration, with ring formation arising naturally from the geometry of 4-carbon thioamide intermediates rather than requiring any specialized cyclization step. The glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline pathway, featuring a spontaneous non-enzymatic cyclization, connects proline to the broader protometabolic network centered on \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Proline's enhanced thermal stability\u2014its pyrrolidine ring resists decarboxylation better than many open-chain amino acids\u2014gives it a selective survival advantage in hydrothermal environments.\n\nThe chirality problem, however, remains proline's deepest challenge. Its \u03b1-hydrogen ensures rapid aqueous racemization, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess and distinguishing it from the \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids that preserve meteoritic L-enrichment. The remarkable crystal-solution eutectic amplification (10% to 85\u201399% ee) demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino has not been replicated under prebiotically relevant aqueous conditions. Perhaps most intriguing is proline's dual identity as both a prebiotic product and a uniquely powerful organocatalyst for asymmetric synthesis. Whether this creates a genuine self-reinforcing feedback loop\u2014where a small excess of L-proline catalyzes reactions that preferentially generate or preserve more L-proline\u2014remains the central open question. The answer could illuminate not just proline's origin but the emergence of biological homochirality itself.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is an impressively comprehensive synthesis network for L-Proline that captures all four major prebiotic routes described in the literature: cyanosulfidic photochemistry (Patel et al. 2015), glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C cascade, HCN oligomerization, and formamide photolysis. The five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, \u03b1KG, glutamate, P5C) create genuine convergence and the network topology is well-connected with no isolated subgraphs.\n\n**Strengths:** (1) Excellent literature alignment\u2014nearly every major finding from the research is represented, including Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user reductive amination, Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry, Muchowska proto-TCA cycles, Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and Saladino formamide photolysis. (2) Strong network topology with 5 hub molecules at degree \u22653 (except P5C at degree 2), 5 convergence points, and 10 pathways providing redundancy. (3) Good environmental transitions with mineral agents specified for most hydrothermal reactions (greigite, magnetite, pyrite, NiFeS). (4) The spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization (rxn_008) is one of the most prebiotically robust steps, scoring 0.95.\n\n**Weaknesses:** (1) The recurring rxn_007 (glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the network's Achilles heel\u2014the literature explicitly flags this as 'chemically demanding' and no convincing prebiotic reductant is specified. This affects 7 of 10 pathways. (2) rxn_010 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol) oversimplifies the multi-step Patel et al. mechanism, omitting the critical Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. (3) rxn_015 (DAMN \u2192 proline directly) is chemically implausible as written\u2014many intermediates are skipped. (4) The 'L-' designation in the target is not addressed anywhere in the network. The literature emphasizes that proline racemizes readily at the \u03b1-carbon and no enantioselection mechanism is included. (5) Several surface reactions lack mineral agent specification (rxn_004, rxn_006, rxn_010, rxn_014, rxn_015). (6) P5C (mol_014) has degree 2, below the hub threshold.\n\n**Missing elements:** Ornithine as alternative entry point to GSA (noted in literature), concentration mechanisms, the OPA/NAC detection limitation context, and any chirality amplification (crystal-solution eutectic, chiral mineral surfaces, or proline's organocatalytic self-reinforcement). Kaur et al. (2024) mild-condition Ni catalysis could strengthen rxn_005.\n\nOverall, this is a strong network that successfully integrates multiple prebiotic chemistry paradigms into a coherent whole. Four pathways meet the approval threshold, with P3 (cyanosulfidic) being the best-supported single pathway despite its oversimplification at rxn_010.\n- Issues: ['Similar to P1 but uses Bucherer-Bergs synthesis (rxn_006) for glutamate formation, directly supported by Pulletikurti et al. (2022). This is a slight improvement over P1 for the amination step since the Bucherer-Bergs mechanism is well-characterized. However, it requires HCN as an additional input without specifying its source within this pathway (it must come from P5/P6 routes or external). The same weakness at rxn_007 persists. The Surface environment for rxn_006 needs mineral specification.', 'Severely oversimplified pathway. While HCN\u2192DAMN (rxn_014) is well-established (Or\u00f3 1961), the direct conversion DAMN\u2192proline (rxn_015) skips critical intermediates including hydantoin formation and complex polymer hydrolysis steps. Literature (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013) describes proline as a minor product of HCN polymer hydrolysis under specific high-temperature conditions. The pathway has only 2 steps with no hydrothermal involvement and no mineral agents specified. Proline would be a trace component of a complex mixture\u2014selectivity is extremely poor.', 'Combines formamide photolysis with HCN oligomerization. Better environmental progression than P4 (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Surface), but still hampered by the problematic rxn_015 (DAMN\u2192proline direct conversion). The formamide-to-HCN portion is well-supported but cannot rescue the fundamentally flawed final step.', 'Combines proto-TCA \u03b1KG formation with Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis. Good convergence of two literature-supported routes but inherits both the rxn_007 weakness and the need for an external HCN source. The pathway demonstrates good network convergence properties.', \"Combines surface glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004) with elements from both P1 and P7. Provides alternative convergence point at \u03b1KG. Same recurring weakness at rxn_007. The glyoxylate route is supported by Springsteen et al. (2018) and Krishnamurthy's group.\", 'The longest pathway at 10 steps, combining formamide photolysis, Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and surface \u03b1KG formation. While it demonstrates maximum network connectivity and environmental progression, the length introduces cumulative yield concerns. Each additional step reduces overall plausibility. Still hampered by rxn_007 and the questionable direct glyoxylate formation.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Ten convergent pathways to L-proline are constructed from four independent prebiotic synthesis paradigms: (1) the glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline reductive cascade via proto-TCA-derived \u03b1-ketoglutarate, (2) the Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic photochemistry route through \u03b3-butyrothiolactam and proline aminonitrile, (3) an ornithine-to-GSA transamination entry, and (4) a chiral amplification step exploiting proline's unique crystal-solution eutectic behavior (Hayashi & Koshino 2006). Five hub molecules (HCN, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, P5C, and pyruvate) create network density. The GSA reduction bottleneck is addressed via the thermodynamically favorable pyrite-pulled mechanism (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2[H]), and the cyanosulfidic route is expanded to include explicit Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling and three discrete intermediates as described by Patel et al. (2015). Chirality is addressed through crystal-solution eutectic amplification of racemic proline to L-enriched proline in evaporitic settings.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCHO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NHCHO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2HO3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoacetate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H4O5-2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9-10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8NO4-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopentanedioate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-5-7)8(9)10/h5H,1-3,6H2,(H,9,10)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(5-4)6(8)9/h5H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"proline (racemic)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(5-3)6(8)9/h4H,1-3,5H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(5-3)6(8)9/h4H,1-3,5H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H12N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-ornithine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol intermediate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde-derived cyanohydrin-thiol\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"gamma-butyrothiolactam\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"proline aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 binds to Fe3S4 surface at [4Fe-4S]-like active site; H2 dissociates on mineral surface; hydride transfer to CO2 yields surface-bound formate; desorption into alkaline solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite (Fe3S4) is the structural analog of biological [4Fe-4S] clusters (Li et al. 2018, Life). CO2 reduction to formate on iron sulfide minerals in alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions is thermodynamically favorable given high H2 concentrations from serpentinization (Russell & Hall 1997, 2006). This is the entry point for carbon fixation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions on magnetite surface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on magnetite surface via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism. CO intermediate formed on surface undergoes hydrogenation to yield formaldehyde. Product rapidly desorbed to prevent over-reduction to methanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces C1 oxygenates including formaldehyde from CO/formate and H2 (McCollom & Seewald 2006). Formaldehyde is a key C1 building block feeding into both HCN production and formose-type chemistry. Magnetite serves as the primary FTT catalyst in hydrothermal systems.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide synthesis from CO2, NH3, and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing conditions with mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is first reduced to formate/CO on FeS surfaces; subsequent reaction with NH3 on magnetite surface yields formamide via nucleophilic addition of ammonia to formate or carbonyl intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide has been proposed as a key prebiotic intermediate by Saladino et al. (2017). Its formation from simple volcanic gases (CO2, NH3, H2) on mineral surfaces in hydrothermal systems is thermodynamically favorable under reducing conditions. Formamide serves as precursor to both HCN and directly to nucleobases/amino acids.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decomposition of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 (anatase)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (200-300 nm), anoxic atmosphere, volcanic/geothermal surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide undergoes dehydration to HCN catalyzed by TiO2 under UV irradiation. The reaction is driven by UV photolysis and mineral surface catalysis. Montmorillonite concentrates formamide in clay interlayers prior to decomposition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino et al. (2017) demonstrated that formamide on TiO2 surfaces under UV irradiation yields HCN and subsequently amino acids and nucleobases. TiO2 (rutile/anatase) was abundant on early Earth surfaces. This connects hydrothermal formamide production to surface HCN chemistry (Saladino et al. 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, multiple CO2 fixation steps\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on mineral surfaces: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetate \u2192 pyruvate. The [4Fe-4S]-analog surface of greigite catalyzes both CO2 reduction and C-C coupling, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that iron-sulfur minerals including pyrite drive production of TCA cycle intermediates including pyruvate from simple C1 inputs. Pyruvate is the central hub of prebiotic carbon metabolism. Cody et al. (2000) showed pyruvate formation from CO, H2O on FeS at 250\u00b0C and 200 MPa.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal conditions, pyrite-pulled reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 undergoes two sequential reductions on FeS surface. First reduction yields formate; second reduction and CO2 condensation yields glyoxylate. Thermodynamic drive provided by FeS \u2192 FeS2 (pyrite) formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, Nature Communications) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative glyoxylate chemistry as protometabolic analogs. Glyoxylate is a key C2 building block that can be produced from CO2 on iron sulfide surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. It feeds into the \u03b1-ketoglutarate synthesis pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol/oxidative condensation to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu2+ ions, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly alkaline pools, Cu2+ catalysis, phosphate buffer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate followed by oxidative decarboxylation yields \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Cu2+ serves as the oxidant, cycling between Cu2+ and Cu+. Montmorillonite concentrates substrates on clay surfaces and provides Lewis acid sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Krishnamurthy's group (2025) demonstrated formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu2+ catalysis. Springsteen et al. (2018, Nature Communications) showed linked protometabolic cycles via glyoxylate. Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acid chemistry reproduces key features of the TCA cycle without enzymes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-TCA cycle generation of alpha-ketoglutarate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing hydrothermal vent conditions, mineral-mediated proto-TCA cycle\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes CO2 fixation (reductive carboxylation) to oxaloacetate on pyrite surface, followed by sequential reduction and dehydration steps through the reductive TCA pathway: oxaloacetate \u2192 malate \u2192 fumarate \u2192 succinate \u2192 succinyl \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Pyrite surface catalyzes each step with Fe-S active sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution 1:1716-1721) demonstrated that pyrite drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates including \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This represents a non-enzymatic analog of the reductive citric acid cycle, the proposed earliest metabolic pathway (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1990). The proto-TCA cycle provides the central carbon backbone for amino acid biosynthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate on NiFeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K (100\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1-5 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"freshly precipitated FeS, NiFeS surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-9, anaerobic, freshly precipitated iron sulfides required\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH3 attacks the C2 carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced to the amine by surface-bound hydride from FeS/NiFeS. The overall transformation converts the \u03b1-keto acid to the corresponding \u03b1-amino acid (glutamate).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, Science 281:670-672; 2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on freshly precipitated FeS at 100\u00b0C with strong metal specificity. This directly mirrors the biological transamination of \u03b1KG to glutamate. NiFeS surfaces show the highest catalytic activity; other metal sulfides failed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NH4+/HCN-rich evaporitic pool, mildly alkaline pH, CO2 atmosphere\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate reacts with HCN and NH3 via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway: (1) HCN adds to the C2 carbonyl to form cyanohydrin, (2) reaction with NH3 gives aminonitrile (Strecker intermediate), (3) CO2 insertion forms hydantoin, (4) hydrolysis of hydantoin yields glutamate. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants in interlayer spaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated that \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids, including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This provides an alternative amination route to the hydrothermal reductive amination, operating under milder surface conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate at ambient temperature\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 (nickel on aluminosilicate)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K (22\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1-10 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 (10 mol% Ni) or ground meteoritic material (11-18 mol% Ni)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, anaerobic, remarkably mild conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate is reductively aminated to glutamate at room temperature using molecular hydrogen on nickel catalytic surfaces. NH3 attacks the C2 carbonyl; H2 is activated on Ni surface sites; hydride transfer reduces the imine to amine. Ground Ni-rich meteorites serve as plausible prebiotic catalyst sources.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, Chem 10:1528-1540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel catalysts at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1-10 bar H2. Ground meteorites (11-18 mol% Ni) served as effective catalysts, producing glutamate among seven biological amino acids. This represents the mildest conditions for prebiotic amino acid synthesis yet demonstrated.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyrite-pulled reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS (mackinawite) with H2S, forming FeS2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anaerobic, FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e- provides thermodynamic drive (\u0394G = -38.4 kJ/mol), selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde via W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's pyrite-pulled mechanism. FeS reacts with H2S to form pyrite (FeS2), releasing reducing equivalents (2H+ + 2e-). These electrons are transferred to the activated \u03b3-carboxyl on the mineral surface, reducing it to the corresponding aldehyde (GSA). The \u03b1-carboxyl is less accessible to the mineral surface due to steric shielding by the \u03b1-amino group and its involvement in surface coordination. NOTE: This is the principal bottleneck of the glutamate-to-proline pathway. The literature (Patel et al. 2015 research summary) explicitly flags selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction as 'chemically demanding.'\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988, 1990) proposed the pyrite-pulled mechanism where FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 provides thermodynamic driving force (\u0394G \u2248 -38.4 kJ/mol) for otherwise unfavorable reductions. This is the best available prebiotic reductant system for carboxyl-to-aldehyde conversion. The selectivity for \u03b3- over \u03b1-carboxyl may arise from preferential surface binding orientation on the FeS surface, where the amino group coordinates to Fe, positioning the \u03b3-carboxyl near the reactive surface. This remains the key bottleneck in the glutamate\u2192proline route\u2014alternative entry via GSA from ornithine (rxn_016) or the cyanosulfidic bypass (rxn_013-015) avoids this step entirely.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"spontaneous non-enzymatic reaction in aqueous solution, favorable equilibrium\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b4-amino group of GSA undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the \u03b3-aldehyde to form a cyclic carbinolamine. Subsequent dehydration yields the imine (Schiff base), generating the \u03941-pyrroline ring of P5C. This cyclization is entropically favorable due to the formation of a five-membered ring and proceeds readily without catalyst.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Vogel and Davis (1952, Journal of the American Chemical Society 74:109-112) first characterized this spontaneous intramolecular cyclization. The reaction requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution\u2014making it one of the most prebiotically plausible steps in the entire proline synthesis pathway. The five-membered ring formation is kinetically and thermodynamically favorable (Baldwin's rules).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to proline (racemic) by Fe2+ and H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate-high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ in solution, FeS mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reducing alkaline vent conditions, abundant dissolved Fe2+ on anoxic early Earth, H2 from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced to the secondary amine (pyrrolidine) by Fe2+-mediated hydride transfer or H2 activation on FeS surfaces. Fe2+ serves as a one-electron reductant (Fe2+ \u2192 Fe3+), or molecular H2 activated on FeS surfaces provides hydride. The product is racemic proline (both D and L).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"In biology, P5C reductase (NADPH-dependent) catalyzes this step. Prebiotically, Fe2+ was abundant on anoxic early Earth and is a competent reductant for imine reduction. FeS/H2S systems at hydrothermal vents provide both the mineral surface for H2 activation and dissolved Fe2+ for solution-phase reduction. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998) demonstrated that NiFeS surfaces can drive reductive amination, establishing the feasibility of imine reduction on mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photochemistry: HCN + H2S + formaldehyde to 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol via Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K (35\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, phosphate buffer\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), anoxic atmosphere, neutral pH, Cu(I)/Cu(II) ratio critical for photoredox\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN reacts with formaldehyde-derived C2-C3 intermediates (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde) produced by photochemical HCN reduction. H2S acts as both a reductant and sulfur source. Cu(I) photooxidation drives radical chemistry; Cu(II) provides oxidative steps. Sequential aldol and cyanohydrin reactions build the 4-carbon chain. H2S adds to the cyanohydrin nitrile to form an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide, yielding the 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol precursor. This is the first of three cyanosulfidic steps (Patel et al. 2015, movement c).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301-307) described the cyanosulfidic pathway where HCN, H2S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling produce amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from a unified network. Proline arises through 'movement c': a 4-carbon cyanohydrin reacts with H2S to produce the thiol intermediate. Sulfide minerals (stibnite) provide dissolved sulfide and Cu(I)/Cu(II) buffering.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven cyclization of 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol to gamma-butyrothiolactam\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K (35\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation (254 nm), Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, neutral pH, strong UV (no ozone layer on early Earth)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The open-chain 4-carbon \u03b1-hydroxythioamide undergoes spontaneous intramolecular cyclization driven by the geometric constraint of the 4-carbon chain. The thioamide nitrogen attacks the \u03b4-carbon, forming the five-membered pyrrolidine-thione ring (\u03b3-butyrothiolactam). UV irradiation drives deoxygenation. This cyclization is geometrically inevitable from the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage, requiring no enzymatic guidance\u2014a key elegance of the Sutherland pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301-307) describe how the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage. UV irradiation then drives cyclization and deoxygenation to yield \u03b3-butyrothiolactam. This self-selecting ring closure provides proline's unique pyrrolidine skeleton without requiring specialized cyclization enzymes, making it one of the most elegant features of the cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreduction and HCN addition: gamma-butyrothiolactam to proline aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb2S3)\", \"sulfide minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K (35\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox, UV irradiation (254 nm)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, phosphate buffer, HCN excess drives equilibrium\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b3-Butyrothiolactam undergoes Cu(I)-mediated photoreduction to reduce the thioamide to an amine. HCN then adds to the resulting cyclic imine via nucleophilic addition (Strecker-type), generating the \u03b1-aminonitrile on the pyrrolidine ring (proline aminonitrile, compound 47 in Patel et al. 2015). This is the final carbon-skeleton-forming step in the cyanosulfidic proline pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301-307) describe how photoreduction of \u03b3-butyrothiolactam and subsequent HCN addition generate the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47). The Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycle provides the reducing equivalents. This connects the Strecker-type aminonitrile chemistry with the cyanosulfidic ring-formation pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of proline aminonitrile to racemic proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required (acid/base catalysis from ambient solution)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH, may be accelerated by mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of proline aminonitrile is hydrolyzed in two steps: (1) nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile yields an amide intermediate (prolinamide), (2) further hydrolysis of the amide yields proline + NH3. This is a well-characterized Strecker-type aminonitrile hydrolysis. The product is racemic proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step of the Strecker synthesis pathway, well-established since Strecker (1850). Patel et al. (2015) note that hydrolysis of the aminonitrile completes the conversion to proline. Lerner and Cooper (2005, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta) detected iminodicarboxylic acids in Murchison meteorite providing direct evidence for Strecker-type reactions. The hydrolysis rate is enhanced at elevated temperatures in prebiotic pools.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine transamination to glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"\u03b1-ketoglutarate as amino group acceptor, possibly pyridoxal as cofactor\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"transamination in prebiotic pool, may proceed on mineral surfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ornithine undergoes transamination at its \u03b4-amino group. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate serves as the amino group acceptor. The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine is transferred to \u03b1KG (regenerating glutamate), while the ornithine \u03b4-carbon is converted to an aldehyde, yielding glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA). In biology, ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase catalyzes this step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies ornithine as an alternative entry point to GSA (Vogel & Davis 1952; biological pathway elucidation by Strecker 1957). Ornithine may arise from arginine degradation under hydrothermal conditions\u2014Vallentyne (1968) found proline as a degradation product of arginine, suggesting thermal processing of arginine \u2192 ornithine \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. The non-enzymatic transamination is plausible given Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's (2003) demonstration of amino acid transformations on mineral surfaces.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Crystal-solution eutectic chiral amplification of proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"evaporite minerals\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none\u2014physical process, not chemical catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic concentration in closed-basin pool, partial dissolution/recrystallization cycles, DL-proline racemic crystals less soluble than enantiopure crystals\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Racemic proline with a small initial enantiomeric excess (from CPL, chiral mineral surfaces, or stochastic fluctuation) undergoes crystal-solution eutectic amplification. DL-proline forms a racemic compound crystal that is less soluble than enantiopure L-proline crystals (more hydrogen bonds in racemate). Upon partial dissolution in evaporitic pools, the solution phase becomes enriched in the excess enantiomer (L-proline reaches 85-99% ee from only 10% starting ee). Wet-dry cycles in evaporitic settings drive repeated dissolution-crystallization, progressively amplifying the L-excess.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hayashi, Koshino, and colleagues (2006, Angewandte Chemie International Edition 45:4593-4597) achieved the most dramatic chiral amplification for any amino acid: DL-proline of only 10% ee yielded solution with 85-99% ee. Klussmann et al. (2006) calculated the eutectic ee for proline as ~76.5%. While the original experiments used CHCl3/EtOH (not prebiotically plausible), the underlying thermodynamic principle\u2014differential solubility of racemate vs. enantiopure crystals\u2014could operate in partially aqueous evaporitic settings with co-solutes altering solubility behavior. The initial ee could originate from CPL in star-forming regions (Bailey et al. 1998; Meinert et al. 2014) or stochastic fluctuation. This addresses the chirality gap noted as the deepest challenge for proline in the literature.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal proto-TCA to glutamate (NiFeS reductive amination) to proline via P5C\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal route: CO2 fixation to pyruvate, proto-TCA cycle to \u03b1KG on pyrite (Muchowska et al. 2017), reductive amination to glutamate on NiFeS (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998), pyrite-pulled GSA reduction, spontaneous P5C cyclization (Vogel & Davis 1952), and Fe2+/H2 reduction to racemic proline, followed by surface chiral amplification (Hayashi & Koshino 2006).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate-pyruvate condensation to \u03b1KG, Bucherer-Bergs amination to glutamate, to proline via P5C\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 pyruvate and glyoxylate feed into surface aldol condensation to \u03b1KG (Krishnamurthy group 2025; Springsteen et al. 2018), then Bucherer-Bergs synthesis gives glutamate (Pulletikurti et al. 2022), followed by GSA reduction, P5C cyclization, and proline formation with chiral amplification.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photochemistry route (Patel-Sutherland 2015)\",\n      \"description\": \"The complete Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic route: hydrothermal formaldehyde and surface HCN combine with H2S under UV and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox to form the 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol, which spontaneously cyclizes to \u03b3-butyrothiolactam, is photoreduced with HCN addition to proline aminonitrile, and hydrolyzed to racemic proline, followed by chiral amplification.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-derived HCN to cyanosulfidic proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formamide synthesis (rxn_003) feeds into surface HCN generation via TiO2 photolysis (Saladino et al. 2017), then enters the cyanosulfidic pathway (Patel et al. 2015) to proline via \u03b3-butyrothiolactam.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Kaur et al. Ni-catalyzed mild-condition glutamate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Proto-TCA generation of \u03b1KG on pyrite (Muchowska et al. 2017) feeds into the remarkably mild Ni-catalyzed reductive amination at 22\u00b0C and pH 8 (Kaur et al. 2024), using meteoritic Ni as catalyst. Glutamate then follows the standard GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Ornithine transamination entry to P5C and proline\",\n      \"description\": \"L-ornithine (from arginine thermal degradation or direct synthesis) enters the proline pathway via transamination with \u03b1KG to yield GSA, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C and is reduced to proline. This bypasses the difficult glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction step. Vallentyne (1968) identified proline as a degradation product of arginine, suggesting this thermal processing route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2-to-formate-to-formaldehyde feeding cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Full hydrothermal-to-surface chain: CO2 reduction to formate on greigite (rxn_001), Fischer-Tropsch reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite (rxn_002), then formaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway with surface-derived HCN. Demonstrates complete Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface environmental flow.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate-pyruvate convergence with Ni-catalyzed amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal glyoxylate (rxn_006) and pyruvate (rxn_005) converge at \u03b1KG via surface aldol/oxidative condensation with Cu2+ (Krishnamurthy group), then Kaur et al. (2024) mild Ni-catalyzed amination to glutamate, followed by GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-derived HCN to Bucherer-Bergs glutamate, to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formamide \u2192 surface HCN (via TiO2) feeds into Bucherer-Bergs synthesis of glutamate from \u03b1KG (generated by proto-TCA on pyrite). This combines three environments: hydrothermal CO2 fixation, surface photochemistry (HCN generation), and surface Bucherer-Bergs chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent dual-amination pathway: NiFeS + Bucherer-Bergs to glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"This pathway highlights the convergence at glutamate from two simultaneous amination routes\u2014hydrothermal NiFeS reductive amination (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user) and surface Bucherer-Bergs (Pulletikurti et al.)\u2014both fed by hydrothermal \u03b1KG from the pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation. Demonstrates how multiple amination mechanisms operating in parallel increase total glutamate flux toward proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN hub: produced from formamide decomposition (rxn_004), consumed by Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis (rxn_010), cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin formation (rxn_015), and proline aminonitrile formation (rxn_017)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate: the central branch-point of the network. Produced by two routes\u2014proto-TCA on pyrite (rxn_008) and pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation (rxn_007). Consumed by three amination pathways\u2014NiFeS reductive amination (rxn_009), Bucherer-Bergs (rxn_010), Ni-catalyzed mild amination (rxn_011)\u2014plus ornithine transamination (rxn_019).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate: produced by three independent amination routes (rxn_009, rxn_010, rxn_011), consumed by pyrite-pulled GSA reduction (rxn_012). Key convergence point for the glutamate-family pathway.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"P5C (\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid): the critical cyclization hub. Produced from GSA cyclization (rxn_013, fed from both glutamate reduction rxn_012 and ornithine transamination rxn_019). Consumed by reduction to racemic proline (rxn_014). Degree = 3.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate: produced from CO2 fixation (rxn_005), consumed by both proto-TCA on pyrite (rxn_008) and pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol condensation (rxn_007). Key hub for carbon backbone elongation.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "Ten convergent pathways to L-proline are constructed from four independent prebiotic synthesis paradigms: (1) the glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline reductive cascade via proto-TCA-derived \u03b1-ketoglutarate, (2) the Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic photochemistry route through \u03b3-butyrothiolactam and proline aminonitrile, (3) an ornithine-to-GSA transamination entry, and (4) a chiral amplification step exploiting proline's unique crystal-solution eutectic behavior (Hayashi & Koshino 2006). Five hub molecules (HCN, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, P5C, and pyruvate) create network density. The GSA reduction bottleneck is addressed via the thermodynamically favorable pyrite-pulled mechanism (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2[H]), and the cyanosulfidic route is expanded to include explicit Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling and three discrete intermediates as described by Patel et al. (2015). Chirality is addressed through crystal-solution eutectic amplification of racemic proline to L-enriched proline in evaporitic settings.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "HCHO", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH3NHCHO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2HO3-", "iupac_name": "oxoacetate", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H4O5-2", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioate", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9-10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/p-2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H8NO4-", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioate", "common_name": "L-glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)/t3-/m0/s1/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(3-1-2-5-7)8(9)10/h5H,1-3,6H2,(H,9,10)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(5-4)6(8)9/h5H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "proline (racemic)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(5-3)6(8)9/h4H,1-3,5H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(5-3)6(8)9/h4H,1-3,5H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H12N2O2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2,5-diaminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "L-ornithine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H12N2O2/c6-3-1-2-4(7)5(8)9/h4H,1-3,6-7H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H5NOS", "iupac_name": "4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol intermediate", "common_name": "succinaldehyde-derived cyanohydrin-thiol", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H7NOS", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-thione", "common_name": "gamma-butyrothiolactam", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "proline aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2 from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 binds to Fe3S4 surface at [4Fe-4S]-like active site; H2 dissociates on mineral surface; hydride transfer to CO2 yields surface-bound formate; desorption into alkaline solution.", "reasoning": "Greigite (Fe3S4) is the structural analog of biological [4Fe-4S] clusters (Li et al. 2018, Life). CO2 reduction to formate on iron sulfide minerals in alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions is thermodynamically favorable given high H2 concentrations from serpentinization (Russell & Hall 1997, 2006). This is the entry point for carbon fixation."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type conditions on magnetite surface"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on magnetite surface via Fischer-Tropsch-type mechanism. CO intermediate formed on surface undergoes hydrogenation to yield formaldehyde. Product rapidly desorbed to prevent over-reduction to methanol.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces C1 oxygenates including formaldehyde from CO/formate and H2 (McCollom & Seewald 2006). Formaldehyde is a key C1 building block feeding into both HCN production and formose-type chemistry. Magnetite serves as the primary FTT catalyst in hydrothermal systems."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formamide synthesis from CO2, NH3, and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing conditions with mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is first reduced to formate/CO on FeS surfaces; subsequent reaction with NH3 on magnetite surface yields formamide via nucleophilic addition of ammonia to formate or carbonyl intermediate.", "reasoning": "Formamide has been proposed as a key prebiotic intermediate by Saladino et al. (2017). Its formation from simple volcanic gases (CO2, NH3, H2) on mineral surfaces in hydrothermal systems is thermodynamically favorable under reducing conditions. Formamide serves as precursor to both HCN and directly to nucleobases/amino acids."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Thermal decomposition of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_004", "mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV irradiation (200-300 nm), anoxic atmosphere, volcanic/geothermal surface setting"}, "mechanism": "Formamide undergoes dehydration to HCN catalyzed by TiO2 under UV irradiation. The reaction is driven by UV photolysis and mineral surface catalysis. Montmorillonite concentrates formamide in clay interlayers prior to decomposition.", "reasoning": "Saladino et al. (2017) demonstrated that formamide on TiO2 surfaces under UV irradiation yields HCN and subsequently amino acids and nucleobases. TiO2 (rutile/anatase) was abundant on early Earth surfaces. This connects hydrothermal formamide production to surface HCN chemistry (Saladino et al. 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11, multiple CO2 fixation steps"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on mineral surfaces: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 acetate \u2192 pyruvate. The [4Fe-4S]-analog surface of greigite catalyzes both CO2 reduction and C-C coupling, analogous to the acetyl-CoA pathway.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution) demonstrated that iron-sulfur minerals including pyrite drive production of TCA cycle intermediates including pyruvate from simple C1 inputs. Pyruvate is the central hub of prebiotic carbon metabolism. Cody et al. (2000) showed pyruvate formation from CO, H2O on FeS at 250\u00b0C and 200 MPa."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on mackinawite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal conditions, pyrite-pulled reduction"}, "mechanism": "CO2 undergoes two sequential reductions on FeS surface. First reduction yields formate; second reduction and CO2 condensation yields glyoxylate. Thermodynamic drive provided by FeS \u2192 FeS2 (pyrite) formation.", "reasoning": "Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, Nature Communications) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative glyoxylate chemistry as protometabolic analogs. Glyoxylate is a key C2 building block that can be produced from CO2 on iron sulfide surfaces under hydrothermal conditions. It feeds into the \u03b1-ketoglutarate synthesis pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol/oxidative condensation to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu2+ ions, montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly alkaline pools, Cu2+ catalysis, phosphate buffer"}, "mechanism": "Aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate followed by oxidative decarboxylation yields \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Cu2+ serves as the oxidant, cycling between Cu2+ and Cu+. Montmorillonite concentrates substrates on clay surfaces and provides Lewis acid sites.", "reasoning": "Krishnamurthy's group (2025) demonstrated formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu2+ catalysis. Springsteen et al. (2018, Nature Communications) showed linked protometabolic cycles via glyoxylate. Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acid chemistry reproduces key features of the TCA cycle without enzymes."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Proto-TCA cycle generation of alpha-ketoglutarate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing hydrothermal vent conditions, mineral-mediated proto-TCA cycle"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes CO2 fixation (reductive carboxylation) to oxaloacetate on pyrite surface, followed by sequential reduction and dehydration steps through the reductive TCA pathway: oxaloacetate \u2192 malate \u2192 fumarate \u2192 succinate \u2192 succinyl \u2192 \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Pyrite surface catalyzes each step with Fe-S active sites.", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution 1:1716-1721) demonstrated that pyrite drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates including \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This represents a non-enzymatic analog of the reductive citric acid cycle, the proposed earliest metabolic pathway (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1990). The proto-TCA cycle provides the central carbon backbone for amino acid biosynthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate on NiFeS", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K (100\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1-5 bar", "catalyst": "freshly precipitated FeS, NiFeS surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-9, anaerobic, freshly precipitated iron sulfides required"}, "mechanism": "NH3 attacks the C2 carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced to the amine by surface-bound hydride from FeS/NiFeS. The overall transformation converts the \u03b1-keto acid to the corresponding \u03b1-amino acid (glutamate).", "reasoning": "Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, Science 281:670-672; 2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on freshly precipitated FeS at 100\u00b0C with strong metal specificity. This directly mirrors the biological transamination of \u03b1KG to glutamate. NiFeS surfaces show the highest catalytic activity; other metal sulfides failed."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "NH4+/HCN-rich evaporitic pool, mildly alkaline pH, CO2 atmosphere"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate reacts with HCN and NH3 via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway: (1) HCN adds to the C2 carbonyl to form cyanohydrin, (2) reaction with NH3 gives aminonitrile (Strecker intermediate), (3) CO2 insertion forms hydantoin, (4) hydrolysis of hydantoin yields glutamate. Montmorillonite concentrates reactants in interlayer spaces.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated that \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids, including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This provides an alternative amination route to the hydrothermal reductive amination, operating under milder surface conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate at ambient temperature", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 (nickel on aluminosilicate)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K (22\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1-10 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 (10 mol% Ni) or ground meteoritic material (11-18 mol% Ni)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8, anaerobic, remarkably mild conditions"}, "mechanism": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate is reductively aminated to glutamate at room temperature using molecular hydrogen on nickel catalytic surfaces. NH3 attacks the C2 carbonyl; H2 is activated on Ni surface sites; hydride transfer reduces the imine to amine. Ground Ni-rich meteorites serve as plausible prebiotic catalyst sources.", "reasoning": "Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, Chem 10:1528-1540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel catalysts at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1-10 bar H2. Ground meteorites (11-18 mol% Ni) served as effective catalysts, producing glutamate among seven biological amino acids. This represents the mildest conditions for prebiotic amino acid synthesis yet demonstrated."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Pyrite-pulled reduction of glutamate gamma-carboxyl to glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS (mackinawite) with H2S, forming FeS2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anaerobic, FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e- provides thermodynamic drive (\u0394G = -38.4 kJ/mol), selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde via W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's pyrite-pulled mechanism. FeS reacts with H2S to form pyrite (FeS2), releasing reducing equivalents (2H+ + 2e-). These electrons are transferred to the activated \u03b3-carboxyl on the mineral surface, reducing it to the corresponding aldehyde (GSA). The \u03b1-carboxyl is less accessible to the mineral surface due to steric shielding by the \u03b1-amino group and its involvement in surface coordination. NOTE: This is the principal bottleneck of the glutamate-to-proline pathway. The literature (Patel et al. 2015 research summary) explicitly flags selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction as 'chemically demanding.'", "reasoning": "W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988, 1990) proposed the pyrite-pulled mechanism where FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 provides thermodynamic driving force (\u0394G \u2248 -38.4 kJ/mol) for otherwise unfavorable reductions. This is the best available prebiotic reductant system for carboxyl-to-aldehyde conversion. The selectivity for \u03b3- over \u03b1-carboxyl may arise from preferential surface binding orientation on the FeS surface, where the amino group coordinates to Fe, positioning the \u03b3-carboxyl near the reactive surface. This remains the key bottleneck in the glutamate\u2192proline route\u2014alternative entry via GSA from ornithine (rxn_016) or the cyanosulfidic bypass (rxn_013-015) avoids this step entirely."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required", "aqueous": "true", "other": "spontaneous non-enzymatic reaction in aqueous solution, favorable equilibrium"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b4-amino group of GSA undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack on the \u03b3-aldehyde to form a cyclic carbinolamine. Subsequent dehydration yields the imine (Schiff base), generating the \u03941-pyrroline ring of P5C. This cyclization is entropically favorable due to the formation of a five-membered ring and proceeds readily without catalyst.", "reasoning": "Vogel and Davis (1952, Journal of the American Chemical Society 74:109-112) first characterized this spontaneous intramolecular cyclization. The reaction requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution\u2014making it one of the most prebiotically plausible steps in the entire proline synthesis pathway. The five-membered ring formation is kinetically and thermodynamically favorable (Baldwin's rules)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reduction of P5C to proline (racemic) by Fe2+ and H2", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate-high", "catalyst": "Fe2+ in solution, FeS mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "reducing alkaline vent conditions, abundant dissolved Fe2+ on anoxic early Earth, H2 from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced to the secondary amine (pyrrolidine) by Fe2+-mediated hydride transfer or H2 activation on FeS surfaces. Fe2+ serves as a one-electron reductant (Fe2+ \u2192 Fe3+), or molecular H2 activated on FeS surfaces provides hydride. The product is racemic proline (both D and L).", "reasoning": "In biology, P5C reductase (NADPH-dependent) catalyzes this step. Prebiotically, Fe2+ was abundant on anoxic early Earth and is a competent reductant for imine reduction. FeS/H2S systems at hydrothermal vents provide both the mineral surface for H2 activation and dissolved Fe2+ for solution-phase reduction. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998) demonstrated that NiFeS surfaces can drive reductive amination, establishing the feasibility of imine reduction on mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photochemistry: HCN + H2S + formaldehyde to 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol via Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb2S3)", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K (35\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, phosphate buffer", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation (254 nm), anoxic atmosphere, neutral pH, Cu(I)/Cu(II) ratio critical for photoredox"}, "mechanism": "HCN reacts with formaldehyde-derived C2-C3 intermediates (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde) produced by photochemical HCN reduction. H2S acts as both a reductant and sulfur source. Cu(I) photooxidation drives radical chemistry; Cu(II) provides oxidative steps. Sequential aldol and cyanohydrin reactions build the 4-carbon chain. H2S adds to the cyanohydrin nitrile to form an \u03b1-hydroxythioamide, yielding the 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol precursor. This is the first of three cyanosulfidic steps (Patel et al. 2015, movement c).", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301-307) described the cyanosulfidic pathway where HCN, H2S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling produce amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from a unified network. Proline arises through 'movement c': a 4-carbon cyanohydrin reacts with H2S to produce the thiol intermediate. Sulfide minerals (stibnite) provide dissolved sulfide and Cu(I)/Cu(II) buffering."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "UV-driven cyclization of 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol to gamma-butyrothiolactam", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K (35\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV irradiation (254 nm), Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, neutral pH, strong UV (no ozone layer on early Earth)"}, "mechanism": "The open-chain 4-carbon \u03b1-hydroxythioamide undergoes spontaneous intramolecular cyclization driven by the geometric constraint of the 4-carbon chain. The thioamide nitrogen attacks the \u03b4-carbon, forming the five-membered pyrrolidine-thione ring (\u03b3-butyrothiolactam). UV irradiation drives deoxygenation. This cyclization is geometrically inevitable from the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage, requiring no enzymatic guidance\u2014a key elegance of the Sutherland pathway.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301-307) describe how the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage. UV irradiation then drives cyclization and deoxygenation to yield \u03b3-butyrothiolactam. This self-selecting ring closure provides proline's unique pyrrolidine skeleton without requiring specialized cyclization enzymes, making it one of the most elegant features of the cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Photoreduction and HCN addition: gamma-butyrothiolactam to proline aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb2S3)", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K (35\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox, UV irradiation (254 nm)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, phosphate buffer, HCN excess drives equilibrium"}, "mechanism": "\u03b3-Butyrothiolactam undergoes Cu(I)-mediated photoreduction to reduce the thioamide to an amine. HCN then adds to the resulting cyclic imine via nucleophilic addition (Strecker-type), generating the \u03b1-aminonitrile on the pyrrolidine ring (proline aminonitrile, compound 47 in Patel et al. 2015). This is the final carbon-skeleton-forming step in the cyanosulfidic proline pathway.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301-307) describe how photoreduction of \u03b3-butyrothiolactam and subsequent HCN addition generate the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47). The Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycle provides the reducing equivalents. This connects the Strecker-type aminonitrile chemistry with the cyanosulfidic ring-formation pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Hydrolysis of proline aminonitrile to racemic proline", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required (acid/base catalysis from ambient solution)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH, may be accelerated by mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of proline aminonitrile is hydrolyzed in two steps: (1) nucleophilic addition of water to the nitrile yields an amide intermediate (prolinamide), (2) further hydrolysis of the amide yields proline + NH3. This is a well-characterized Strecker-type aminonitrile hydrolysis. The product is racemic proline.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step of the Strecker synthesis pathway, well-established since Strecker (1850). Patel et al. (2015) note that hydrolysis of the aminonitrile completes the conversion to proline. Lerner and Cooper (2005, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta) detected iminodicarboxylic acids in Murchison meteorite providing direct evidence for Strecker-type reactions. The hydrolysis rate is enhanced at elevated temperatures in prebiotic pools."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Ornithine transamination to glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "\u03b1-ketoglutarate as amino group acceptor, possibly pyridoxal as cofactor", "aqueous": "true", "other": "transamination in prebiotic pool, may proceed on mineral surfaces"}, "mechanism": "Ornithine undergoes transamination at its \u03b4-amino group. \u03b1-Ketoglutarate serves as the amino group acceptor. The \u03b4-amino group of ornithine is transferred to \u03b1KG (regenerating glutamate), while the ornithine \u03b4-carbon is converted to an aldehyde, yielding glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA). In biology, ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase catalyzes this step.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies ornithine as an alternative entry point to GSA (Vogel & Davis 1952; biological pathway elucidation by Strecker 1957). Ornithine may arise from arginine degradation under hydrothermal conditions\u2014Vallentyne (1968) found proline as a degradation product of arginine, suggesting thermal processing of arginine \u2192 ornithine \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. The non-enzymatic transamination is plausible given Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's (2003) demonstration of amino acid transformations on mineral surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Crystal-solution eutectic chiral amplification of proline", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "evaporite minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none\u2014physical process, not chemical catalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic concentration in closed-basin pool, partial dissolution/recrystallization cycles, DL-proline racemic crystals less soluble than enantiopure crystals"}, "mechanism": "Racemic proline with a small initial enantiomeric excess (from CPL, chiral mineral surfaces, or stochastic fluctuation) undergoes crystal-solution eutectic amplification. DL-proline forms a racemic compound crystal that is less soluble than enantiopure L-proline crystals (more hydrogen bonds in racemate). Upon partial dissolution in evaporitic pools, the solution phase becomes enriched in the excess enantiomer (L-proline reaches 85-99% ee from only 10% starting ee). Wet-dry cycles in evaporitic settings drive repeated dissolution-crystallization, progressively amplifying the L-excess.", "reasoning": "Hayashi, Koshino, and colleagues (2006, Angewandte Chemie International Edition 45:4593-4597) achieved the most dramatic chiral amplification for any amino acid: DL-proline of only 10% ee yielded solution with 85-99% ee. Klussmann et al. (2006) calculated the eutectic ee for proline as ~76.5%. While the original experiments used CHCl3/EtOH (not prebiotically plausible), the underlying thermodynamic principle\u2014differential solubility of racemate vs. enantiopure crystals\u2014could operate in partially aqueous evaporitic settings with co-solutes altering solubility behavior. The initial ee could originate from CPL in star-forming regions (Bailey et al. 1998; Meinert et al. 2014) or stochastic fluctuation. This addresses the chirality gap noted as the deepest challenge for proline in the literature."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal proto-TCA to glutamate (NiFeS reductive amination) to proline via P5C", "description": "Complete hydrothermal route: CO2 fixation to pyruvate, proto-TCA cycle to \u03b1KG on pyrite (Muchowska et al. 2017), reductive amination to glutamate on NiFeS (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998), pyrite-pulled GSA reduction, spontaneous P5C cyclization (Vogel & Davis 1952), and Fe2+/H2 reduction to racemic proline, followed by surface chiral amplification (Hayashi & Koshino 2006).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Glyoxylate-pyruvate condensation to \u03b1KG, Bucherer-Bergs amination to glutamate, to proline via P5C", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 pyruvate and glyoxylate feed into surface aldol condensation to \u03b1KG (Krishnamurthy group 2025; Springsteen et al. 2018), then Bucherer-Bergs synthesis gives glutamate (Pulletikurti et al. 2022), followed by GSA reduction, P5C cyclization, and proline formation with chiral amplification.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photochemistry route (Patel-Sutherland 2015)", "description": "The complete Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic route: hydrothermal formaldehyde and surface HCN combine with H2S under UV and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox to form the 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol, which spontaneously cyclizes to \u03b3-butyrothiolactam, is photoreduced with HCN addition to proline aminonitrile, and hydrolyzed to racemic proline, followed by chiral amplification.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Formamide-derived HCN to cyanosulfidic proline", "description": "Hydrothermal formamide synthesis (rxn_003) feeds into surface HCN generation via TiO2 photolysis (Saladino et al. 2017), then enters the cyanosulfidic pathway (Patel et al. 2015) to proline via \u03b3-butyrothiolactam.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Kaur et al. Ni-catalyzed mild-condition glutamate route", "description": "Proto-TCA generation of \u03b1KG on pyrite (Muchowska et al. 2017) feeds into the remarkably mild Ni-catalyzed reductive amination at 22\u00b0C and pH 8 (Kaur et al. 2024), using meteoritic Ni as catalyst. Glutamate then follows the standard GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Ornithine transamination entry to P5C and proline", "description": "L-ornithine (from arginine thermal degradation or direct synthesis) enters the proline pathway via transamination with \u03b1KG to yield GSA, which spontaneously cyclizes to P5C and is reduced to proline. This bypasses the difficult glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction step. Vallentyne (1968) identified proline as a degradation product of arginine, suggesting this thermal processing route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_019", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2-to-formate-to-formaldehyde feeding cyanosulfidic route", "description": "Full hydrothermal-to-surface chain: CO2 reduction to formate on greigite (rxn_001), Fischer-Tropsch reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite (rxn_002), then formaldehyde enters the cyanosulfidic pathway with surface-derived HCN. Demonstrates complete Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface environmental flow.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_018", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Glyoxylate-pyruvate convergence with Ni-catalyzed amination", "description": "Hydrothermal glyoxylate (rxn_006) and pyruvate (rxn_005) converge at \u03b1KG via surface aldol/oxidative condensation with Cu2+ (Krishnamurthy group), then Kaur et al. (2024) mild Ni-catalyzed amination to glutamate, followed by GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Formamide-derived HCN to Bucherer-Bergs glutamate, to proline", "description": "Hydrothermal formamide \u2192 surface HCN (via TiO2) feeds into Bucherer-Bergs synthesis of glutamate from \u03b1KG (generated by proto-TCA on pyrite). This combines three environments: hydrothermal CO2 fixation, surface photochemistry (HCN generation), and surface Bucherer-Bergs chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Convergent dual-amination pathway: NiFeS + Bucherer-Bergs to glutamate", "description": "This pathway highlights the convergence at glutamate from two simultaneous amination routes\u2014hydrothermal NiFeS reductive amination (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user) and surface Bucherer-Bergs (Pulletikurti et al.)\u2014both fed by hydrothermal \u03b1KG from the pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation. Demonstrates how multiple amination mechanisms operating in parallel increase total glutamate flux toward proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_020"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "description": "HCN hub: produced from formamide decomposition (rxn_004), consumed by Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis (rxn_010), cyanosulfidic cyanohydrin formation (rxn_015), and proline aminonitrile formation (rxn_017)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate: the central branch-point of the network. Produced by two routes\u2014proto-TCA on pyrite (rxn_008) and pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation (rxn_007). Consumed by three amination pathways\u2014NiFeS reductive amination (rxn_009), Bucherer-Bergs (rxn_010), Ni-catalyzed mild amination (rxn_011)\u2014plus ornithine transamination (rxn_019).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_019"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Glutamate: produced by three independent amination routes (rxn_009, rxn_010, rxn_011), consumed by pyrite-pulled GSA reduction (rxn_012). Key convergence point for the glutamate-family pathway.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "P5C (\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid): the critical cyclization hub. Produced from GSA cyclization (rxn_013, fed from both glutamate reduction rxn_012 and ornithine transamination rxn_019). Consumed by reduction to racemic proline (rxn_014). Degree = 3.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Pyruvate: produced from CO2 fixation (rxn_005), consumed by both proto-TCA on pyrite (rxn_008) and pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol condensation (rxn_007). Key hub for carbon backbone elongation.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 507295.9928512573, "success": true, "error_message":