l specification.', 'Severely oversimplified pathway. While HCN\u2192DAMN (rxn_014) is well-established (Or\u00f3 1961), the direct conversion DAMN\u2192proline (rxn_015) skips critical intermediates including hydantoin formation and complex polymer hydrolysis steps. Literature (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013) describes proline as a minor product of HCN polymer hydrolysis under specific high-temperature conditions. The pathway has only 2 steps with no hydrothermal involvement and no mineral agents specified. Proline would be a trace component of a complex mixture\u2014selectivity is extremely poor.', 'Combines formamide photolysis with HCN oligomerization. Better environmental progression than P4 (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Surface), but still hampered by the problematic rxn_015 (DAMN\u2192proline direct conversion). The formamide-to-HCN portion is well-supported but cannot rescue the fundamentally flawed final step.', 'Combines proto-TCA \u03b1KG formation with Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis. Good convergence of two literature-supported routes but inherits both the rxn_007 weakness and the need for an external HCN source. The pathway demonstrates good network convergence properties.', \"Combines surface glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004) with elements from both P1 and P7. Provides alternative convergence point at \u03b1KG. Same recurring weakness at rxn_007. The glyoxylate route is supported by Springsteen et al. (2018) and Krishnamurthy's group.\", 'The longest pathway at 10 steps, combining formamide photolysis, Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and surface \u03b1KG formation. While it demonstrates maximum network connectivity and environmental progression, the length introduces cumulative yield concerns. Each additional step reduces overall plausibility. Still hampered by rxn_007 and the questionable direct glyoxylate formation.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.83\n- Feedback: This is an exceptionally well-constructed prebiotic synthesis network for L-proline that demonstrates deep engagement with the literature. The network correctly identifies and implements the four major prebiotic synthesis paradigms: (1) the glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline reductive cascade, (2) the Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic route, (3) the ornithine entry, and (4) crystal-solution eutectic amplification. The five hub molecules create excellent network density and convergence. Literature alignment is outstanding\u2014Patel et al. 2015, Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998, Kaur et al. 2024, Muchowska et al. 2017, Pulletikurti et al. 2022, Springsteen et al. 2018, and Hayashi & Koshino 2006 are all correctly incorporated. Three significant weaknesses prevent higher scoring: (1) rxn_012 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the acknowledged but still unresolved bottleneck\u2014no experimental demonstration exists for this specific transformation under pyrite-pulled conditions; (2) rxn_020 (chirality amplification) relies on Hayashi-Koshino eutectic which has only been demonstrated in organic solvents, not aqueous prebiotic conditions; (3) mol_017 (ornithine) is an orphan node with no synthesis route. The cyanosulfidic pathways (P3, P4, P7) are the strongest because they elegantly avoid the problematic GSA reduction by forming the pyrrolidine ring at the thiolactam stage. The network would be improved by: (a) adding an ornithine synthesis route or removing P6, (b) exploring alternative chirality mechanisms (CPL during UV photolysis, mineral surface enantioselection), and (c) providing more detailed conditions for rxn_012. Despite these issues, the network achieves the standard for approval based on the strength of three validated pathways.\n- Issues: [\"The proto-TCA to glutamate to proline cascade is well-supported by literature (Muchowska et al. 2017, Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998). The NiFeS reductive amination (rxn_009) is solid. The critical bottleneck is rxn_012 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to aldehyde), which the literature explicitly identifies as 'chemically demanding' and lacks direct experimental demonstration with FeS/H2S. The pyrite-pulled mechanism is thermodynamically sound but unproven for this specific transformation. rxn_014 (P5C reduction) is plausible but Fe2+/H2 conditions need better specification. rxn_020 chirality amplification via Hayashi-Koshino eutectic is only demonstrated in CHCl3/EtOH, not aqueous conditions.\", 'The glyoxylate-pyruvate condensation to \u03b1KG is well-supported by Springsteen et al. 2018. The Bucherer-Bergs amination (rxn_010) is strongly supported by Pulletikurti et al. 2022. The convergence of two CO2-derived intermediates (pyruvate + glyoxylate) is chemically elegant. Same rxn_012 and rxn_020 bottlenecks as P1. The environmental transition from Hydrothermal (CO2 fixation) \u2192 Surface (condensation, Bucherer-Bergs) \u2192 Hydrothermal (reduction) \u2192 Biochemical (cyclization) \u2192 Surface (amplification) shows good interconnection but the back-and-forth is somewhat unrealistic.', 'The Kaur et al. 2024 Ni-catalyzed reductive amination at 22\u00b0C and pH 8 is a strong recent result. Using ground meteorites as catalyst is prebiotically compelling. However, this pathway has the same rxn_012 bottleneck and rxn_020 chirality issue. The surface-labeled Ni-catalyzed amination (rxn_011) after hydrothermal \u03b1KG synthesis is a reasonable environmental transition. One issue: rxn_011 takes \u03b1KG + NH3 + H2 \u2192 glutamate at ambient temperature on Surface, but then rxn_012 sends glutamate back to Hydrothermal for pyrite-pulled reduction\u2014this environmental back-and-forth is somewhat awkward.', \"The weakest pathway. mol_017 (L-ornithine) is an orphan node with no synthesis route in the network\u2014it simply appears as an intermediate without any reaction producing it. The literature explicitly states that ornithine-to-GSA transamination under non-enzymatic prebiotic conditions 'remains unexplored.' rxn_019 uses \u03b1KG as a co-substrate but the transamination mechanism without pyridoxal phosphate or a prebiotic analog is highly questionable. The all-Biochemical labeling of rxn_019 is also problematic\u2014if this is a non-enzymatic prebiotic reaction it should not be labeled Biochemical.\", 'Variant of P2 using Ni-catalyzed amination instead of Bucherer-Bergs. Shares the same strengths (convergent glyoxylate-pyruvate synthesis, strong Ni catalysis support) and weaknesses (rxn_012 bottleneck, rxn_020 chirality). The 8-step length is somewhat long for a prebiotic pathway.', 'This pathway routes HCN from formamide into the Bucherer-Bergs amination of \u03b1KG. However, the pathway description implies 9 steps but the \u03b1KG source is not clearly specified within the pathway\u2014rxn_010 requires \u03b1KG (mol_011) which must come from rxn_008 or rxn_007, adding steps not explicitly listed. The formamide\u2192HCN\u2192Bucherer-Bergs connection is chemically sound. Same rxn_012 and rxn_020 issues persist.', 'The convergent dual-amination concept is interesting\u2014three independent routes to glutamate (NiFeS hydrothermal, Bucherer-Bergs surface, Ni-catalyzed surface) feed into the same downstream GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline cascade. This provides redundancy at the amination step. However, the pathway is long (9 steps) and the downstream bottleneck (rxn_012) remains the same regardless of which amination route is used. The convergence is more of a network property than a true pathway.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "", "parsed_response": null, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 12294.53706741333, "success": false, "error_message": "{'type': 'error', 'error': {'details': None, 'type': 'overloaded_error', 'message': 'Overloaded'}, 'request_id': 'req_011CZ8XEK9qYLKb9gKk12UAr'}"}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T06:51:24.039929", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of L-Proline: routes, challenges, and the chirality puzzle\n\n**Proline is among the most structurally distinctive amino acids to form under prebiotic conditions, yet multiple independent lines of evidence confirm its abiotic synthesis.** As the only proteinogenic amino acid with a cyclic secondary amine (pyrrolidine ring), proline demands ring-closing chemistry that sets it apart from all other coded amino acids. Despite this structural complexity, proline has been detected in Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments, carbonaceous chondrite meteorites, and has been shown to emerge naturally from cyanosulfidic photochemistry. These converging lines of evidence place proline among the \"early\" amino acids accessible on prebiotic Earth\u2014ranking approximately eighth to ninth in abiotic abundance. Yet its path to biological homochirality remains one of the most challenging puzzles in origin-of-life chemistry, complicated by rapid aqueous racemization at its \u03b1-carbon and the difficulty of concentrating it from dilute prebiotic solutions.\n\n---\n\n## Multiple prebiotic routes converge on the pyrrolidine ring\n\nAt least four independent chemical pathways produce proline under plausibly prebiotic conditions, each starting from different simple feedstock molecules and operating through distinct mechanisms.\n\n**The Miller-Urey spark discharge route** represents the earliest experimental demonstration. Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* 69:765\u2013768) definitively identified proline by both ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS in electric discharge experiments using CH\u2084, N\u2082, and H\u2082O with trace NH\u2083. Their work detected **20 amino acids total**, and proline was confirmed as a minor but reproducible product. Johnson, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, Lazcano, and Bada (2008, *Science* 322:404) re-analyzed archived vials from Miller's \"volcanic\" apparatus and found 22 amino acids and 5 amines. More recently, Jiang and colleagues (2014, *Scientific Reports* 4:6769) detected all non-sulfur-containing natural amino acids including proline using LC-MS/MS. A critical analytical caveat, however, has caused systematic underreporting: the standard OPA/NAC derivatization method used in modern amino acid analysis **cannot detect proline** because it only reacts with primary amines. Parker, Cleaves, Dworkin, and colleagues (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531) explicitly noted this limitation when re-analyzing Miller's H\u2082S-rich experiment\u2014proline detection was \"not possible\" with their methodology. This means proline's true abundance in spark discharge products is likely higher than commonly reported.\n\n**The cyanosulfidic chemistry route**, developed by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307), provides the most mechanistically detailed prebiotic pathway to proline. Starting from HCN, H\u2082S, and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling at **35\u00b0C in anoxic, neutral-pH conditions**, this network produces precursors to 12 proteinogenic amino acids through four chemical \"movements.\" Proline specifically arises through what the authors designate \"movement c\": a 4-carbon cyanohydrin reacts with H\u2082S to produce both an open-chain and a **cyclic \u03b1-hydroxythioamide**. UV irradiation then drives cyclization and deoxygenation to yield **\u03b3-butyrothiolactam**, which undergoes photoreduction and HCN addition to generate the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47 in the original paper). The elegance of this pathway lies in its inevitability\u2014the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage, requiring no enzymatic guidance. Hydrolysis of the aminonitrile then yields proline itself. This route connects proline synthesis to the broader cyanosulfidic network that simultaneously generates nucleotide and lipid precursors, suggesting a unified chemical origin for life's building blocks.\n\n**The glutamate-to-proline reductive amination pathway** mirrors the biological biosynthetic route and proceeds through well-characterized intermediates. Glutamic acid\u2014one of the most abundant amino acids in both spark discharge experiments and meteorites\u2014undergoes partial reduction of its \u03b3-carboxyl group to form **glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)**. GSA then undergoes spontaneous, non-enzymatic intramolecular cyclization to form **\u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)**, as first characterized by Vogel and Davis (1952, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 74:109\u2013112). This cyclization requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution\u2014making it one of the most prebiotically plausible steps in the entire pathway. Final reduction of P5C to proline could be driven by Fe\u00b2\u207a, FeS/H\u2082S systems, or molecular hydrogen from serpentinization. The biological pathway was further elucidated by Strecker (1957, *Journal of Biological Chemistry* 225:825\u2013834), and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, *Science* 281:670\u2013672) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids can be reductively aminated to amino acids on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces, establishing the prebiotic feasibility of the first step.\n\n**HCN oligomerization**, first explored by Or\u00f3 in 1961, produces amino acids through polymer hydrolysis. Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (2013, *Life* 3:421\u2013448) reviewed 23 experimental conditions and found proline among the amino acids detected in some HCN polymer hydrolysis experiments, particularly those conducted at higher temperatures. The mechanism proceeds through diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, the HCN tetramer) and hydantoin intermediates.\n\n---\n\n## The intermediate network reveals key branch points\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of proline connects to a broader metabolic-like network of chemical transformations, with **\u03b1-ketoglutarate serving as the central branch-point intermediate**. This TCA-cycle compound sits at the intersection of carbon metabolism and amino acid synthesis, feeding the glutamate family: glutamate, glutamine, proline, and arginine.\n\nRecent work has demonstrated prebiotically plausible routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate itself. Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, *Nature Chemistry* 12:1016\u20131022) showed that \u03b1-keto acid chemistry can reproduce key features of the TCA cycle without enzymes. Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, *Nature Communications* 9:91) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative decarboxylation of glyoxylate as protometabolic analogs. Most recently, Krishnamurthy's group (2025) demonstrated formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from just two amino acids\u2014serine and glycine\u2014via pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu\u00b2\u207a catalysis. Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry*) then showed \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate.\n\nThe pathway from glutamate to proline passes through three intermediates, each with distinct prebiotic significance:\n\n- **Glutamic-\u03b3-semialdehyde (GSA)** is the open-chain form that requires reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl group. In biology, this is accomplished by NADPH; prebiotically, FeS/H\u2082S or Fe\u00b2\u207a could serve as reductants.\n- **\u0394\u00b9-Pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)** forms spontaneously from GSA through intramolecular imine formation. This non-enzymatic cyclization is the crucial ring-closing step that creates proline's pyrrolidine skeleton.\n- **Ornithine** represents an alternative entry point. In biology, ornithine \u03b4-aminotransferase converts ornithine to GSA, and ornithine cyclodeaminase can convert ornithine directly to proline. Whether similar non-enzymatic transformations occur under prebiotic conditions remains unexplored.\n\nProline ranks approximately **eighth to ninth in prebiotic amino acid abundance** according to the analysis of Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483\u2013490), who classified it among the \"early 10\" amino acids\u2014those reliably produced in Miller experiments, found in meteorites, and thermodynamically favorable. The ranking correlates with Gibbs free energy of formation data from Amend and Shock (1998). Among the early amino acids (Gly > Ala > Asp > Glu > Val > Ser > Ile/Leu > Pro > Thr), proline's lower abundance reflects the additional thermodynamic cost of ring formation.\n\n---\n\n## Hydrothermal vents and volcanic hot springs offer complementary settings\n\nThe environmental conditions most favorable for prebiotic proline synthesis depend on which pathway is operative, with different settings favoring different reaction steps.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** of the Lost City type (Kelley et al., 2001) provide temperatures of **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, and abundant H\u2082 and CH\u2084 from serpentinization of ultramafic peridotite. These reducing conditions favor reductive amination reactions. M\u00e9nez and colleagues (2018, *Nature* 564:59\u201363) discovered abiotic tryptophan in serpentinite rocks beneath Lost City, trapped in iron-rich saponite clays\u2014the first direct evidence of amino acid formation through purely abiotic geochemical processes in a natural hydrothermal system. The Russell and Hall model (1997, 2006) proposed that Fe(II)-bearing hydroxides, sulfides, and carbonates in alkaline vent chimneys could drive CO\u2082 reduction and amino acid synthesis via electrochemical gradients across mineral membranes.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (>300\u00b0C, acidic, metal sulfide-rich) present a stability challenge. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) argued that submarine hot springs are net destroyers of organic compounds. However, **proline's pyrrolidine ring confers enhanced thermal stability** compared to many other amino acids. Li and Brill (2003, *Journal of Physical Chemistry A* 107:5987\u20135992) studied proline decarboxylation kinetics at 270\u2013340\u00b0C and 275 bar, finding relatively slow decomposition rates independent of pH between 3 and 8.5. Vallentyne (1968) found proline to be more stable than leucine, arginine, and lysine under hydrothermal conditions. Notably, Vallentyne also identified proline as a degradation product of arginine\u2014suggesting a secondary prebiotic route to proline through thermal processing of other amino acids.\n\n**Volcanic hot spring pools on land** represent a third setting championed by Damer and Deamer (2020, *Astrobiology* 20:429\u2013452) in the \"Hot Spring Hypothesis.\" These fluctuating pools at **60\u201390\u00b0C** provide three energy sources simultaneously: thermal energy, dehydration-rehydration chemical potential, and UV light. Van Kranendonk and colleagues (2020, *Astrobiology*) showed that the **3.48 billion-year-old Dresser Formation** in Western Australia's Pilbara Craton preserves evidence of such terrestrial hot springs, including geyserite, concentrated boron (in tourmaline), phosphate-bearing hydrothermal veins, and smectite/illite clays\u2014all cofactors for prebiotic chemistry. Wet-dry cycling in these settings drives peptide bond formation that is thermodynamically unfavorable in bulk water, as demonstrated by Ross and Deamer (2016, *Life* 6:28) and Forsythe and colleagues (2015, *Angewandte Chemie* 54:9871\u20139875).\n\nThe cyanosulfidic route to proline (Patel et al. 2015) operates under yet another set of conditions: **35\u00b0C, neutral pH, anoxic atmosphere** with UV irradiation, Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling, and phosphate buffer\u2014conditions potentially realized in shallow, UV-exposed pools on early Earth's surface.\n\n---\n\n## Iron-sulfur minerals and nickel catalysts drive key transformations\n\nMineral catalysis is essential for several steps in prebiotic proline synthesis, with iron-sulfur and nickel-iron systems playing the most prominent roles.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** drives W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's \"pyrite-pulled\" reactions, where the thermodynamically favorable formation of pyrite from FeS provides reducing equivalents: FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids on freshly precipitated FeS at 100\u00b0C, with strong metal specificity\u2014other metal sulfides failed to produce amino acids. Muchowska and colleagues (2017, *Nature Ecology & Evolution* 1:1716\u20131721) showed pyrite drives production of most TCA cycle intermediates including the proline precursor \u03b1-ketoglutarate. **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** is structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] clusters in modern metalloenzymes, particularly acetyl-CoA synthase (Li et al. 2018, *Life* 8:46), positioning it as a proto-enzymatic catalyst for CO\u2082 fixation and reductive transformations in hydrothermal mound chimneys.\n\nA landmark recent study by Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, *Chem* 10:1528\u20131540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H\u2082 and NH\u2083 over **nickel catalysts** at remarkably mild conditions: **22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1\u201310 bar H\u2082**. Using Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni) or even ground meteorites (11\u201318 mol% Ni) as catalysts, this system produces seven biological amino acids from reductive amination of keto acids, including **glycine, alanine, aspartate, and glutamate**. The pathway generates \u03b1-ketoglutarate\u2014the direct precursor to glutamate and, through the GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline cascade, to proline itself.\n\n**Montmorillonite clay** catalyzes amino acid polymerization, as demonstrated extensively by Ferris and colleagues (1996, *Nature* 381:59\u201361; 2006, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B* 361:1777\u20131786). Clay surfaces concentrate monomers in interlayer environments, catalyzing condensation at rates **100\u20131,000 times greater than hydrolysis**. Bujdak and colleagues (1994, *Monatshefte f\u00fcr Chemie* 125:1033\u20131039) showed montmorillonite catalyzes peptide formation from glycine in evaporation cycles. While specific proline-clay interaction data remain sparse, the negative layer charge of montmorillonite attracts amino acid ammonium groups, and Namani and colleagues (2021, *ChemSystemsChem*) showed prebiotically relevant amino acids enhance montmorillonite-catalyzed RNA polymerization cooperatively.\n\n**TiO\u2082 photocatalysis** offers another mineral-driven route. Saladino and colleagues (2017) demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of amino acids from formamide under UV irradiation on TiO\u2082 surfaces. Rutile, a common early Earth mineral, could have driven amino acid formation in UV-exposed shallow water environments.\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic proline and the underreporting problem\n\nProline was among the earliest amino acids identified in the Murchison meteorite. Kvenvolden, Lawless, and colleagues (1970, *Nature* 228:923\u2013926) detected proline alongside glycine, alanine, glutamic acid, and valine by ion-exchange chromatography and capillary gas chromatography. Critically, they reported \"almost equal amounts of the D and L enantiomers of valine, proline, alanine, and glutamic acid\"\u2014near-racemic ratios that argued strongly for abiotic origin and against terrestrial biological contamination. Cronin and Moore (1971, *Science* 172:1327\u20131329) confirmed proline in extended analyses of Murchison, Murray, and Allende chondrites.\n\n**Quantitative concentrations** of proline in Murchison fall in the range of **~0.1\u20131 \u03bcg/g (ppm)**, making it a minor but consistent component of the meteoritic amino acid suite. For comparison, glycine\u2014the most abundant amino acid\u2014reaches 3\u20136 \u03bcg/g. The abundance pattern (decreasing with carbon number and structural complexity) is consistent with abiotic synthesis mechanisms, likely Strecker-cyanohydrin reactions on the meteorite parent body. Lerner and Cooper (2005, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta* 69:2901\u20132906) detected iminodicarboxylic acids in Murchison, providing direct evidence for Strecker-type reactions on the parent body.\n\nEngel and Nagy (1982, *Nature* 296:837\u2013840) reported L-excesses in protein amino acids from Murchison, including proline, but these results proved controversial due to potential contamination. Pizzarello and colleagues (2012, *PNAS*) analyzed the pristine CR chondrite GRA 95229 and found that **protein amino acids including proline were racemic** (D/L \u2248 1), while isovaline retained an L-excess of ~3%. This distinction is fundamental: proline has an \u03b1-hydrogen and racemizes readily during aqueous alteration, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess. The \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids (isovaline, \u03b1-methylisoleucine) lack this vulnerable hydrogen and preserve their original chirality.\n\n---\n\n## The chirality puzzle: from small imbalances to biological homochirality\n\nHow L-proline could be selected over D-proline in prebiotic settings remains one of the deepest unresolved questions in origin-of-life research. The challenge is compounded by proline's facile racemization at the \u03b1-carbon, which erases any initial enantiomeric excess in aqueous solution.\n\n**Circularly polarized light (CPL)** from star-forming regions represents the most widely discussed symmetry-breaking mechanism. Bailey and colleagues (1998, *Science* 281:672\u2013674) discovered ~17% circular polarization in infrared light from the Orion nebula, suggesting our presolar environment could have provided CPL. Meinert and colleagues (2014, *Astrophysical Journal* 788:79) irradiated interstellar ice analogs with synchrotron UV CPL and detected 24 amino acids including proline in the residues, with small but reproducible enantiomeric excesses. Meinert and colleagues (2022, *Nature Communications*) measured the first gas-phase circular dichroism spectra for amino acids including proline in the vacuum UV (130\u2013280 nm), revealing that **proline's five-membered nitrogen heterocycle produces unique spectral features**\u2014hypsochromic shifts distinguishing it from all open-chain amino acids. These anisotropy factors predict the ee inducible by CPL photolysis. However, maximum laboratory CPL-induced ee values remain **\u22642\u20133%**, and Glavin and Dworkin's (2009, *PNAS* 106:5487\u20135492) finding that pristine CR meteorites show no isovaline excess argues against CPL as the sole mechanism.\n\n**Chiral mineral surfaces** offer an alternative symmetry-breaking route. Hazen, Filley, and Goodfriend (2001, *PNAS* 98:5487\u20135490) demonstrated that calcite scalenohedral crystal faces selectively adsorb D- versus L-aspartic acid, with terraced surfaces showing the greatest selectivity. The mechanism requires three non-colinear configuration-dependent interaction points between molecule and surface. Alanine, with only two bonding points, showed no enantioselectivity. **No published data exist for proline adsorption on chiral calcite surfaces**, representing a significant experimental gap. Proline's rigid pyrrolidine ring and carboxylate group provide a distinctive molecular geometry that could create specific three-point contacts, but this remains untested.\n\n**Chiral amplification mechanisms** are essential to bridge the gap from small initial ee values (1\u20133%) to biological homochirality (100% L). Three mechanisms are particularly relevant to proline:\n\n- **Crystal-solution eutectic amplification**: Hayashi, Koshino, and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 45:4593\u20134597) achieved the most dramatic amplification demonstrated for any amino acid. DL-proline racemic crystals have more hydrogen bonds and are less soluble than enantiopure crystals. When solid proline of **only 10% ee** was dissolved in CHCl\u2083/EtOH, the solution reached **85\u201399% ee** as the racemic crystals preferentially remained undissolved. Klussmann and colleagues (2006, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) calculated the eutectic ee for proline as ~76.5% in certain solvents. The limitation is that CHCl\u2083/EtOH is not prebiotically plausible; finding aqueous conditions that replicate this effect remains an open challenge.\n\n- **Proline-mediated autoinductive catalysis**: Mathew, Iwamura, and Blackmond (2004, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition*) showed that proline-catalyzed \u03b1-aminoxylation of aldehydes exhibits accelerating reaction rates (autoinduction) and ee amplification over time. Products form adducts with proline that act as more efficient catalysts\u2014the first general organic chemistry strategy implicating amino acid catalysis in a selectivity-enhancing autoinductive process.\n\n- **Proline as organocatalyst**: List, Lerner, and Barbas III (2000, *Journal of the American Chemical Society* 122:2395) discovered that L-proline catalyzes intermolecular asymmetric aldol reactions with **up to >99% enantioselectivity**, operating through an enamine mechanism via a Zimmerman-Traxler transition state. The pyrrolidine ring constrains the transition state geometry, and both ring size and carboxyl group are essential\u2014making proline uniquely suited among all amino acids. This dual identity as both a product of prebiotic synthesis and a powerful asymmetric catalyst raises the tantalizing possibility of a self-reinforcing chiral feedback loop, though true autocatalysis (proline catalyzing its own formation) has not been demonstrated.\n\nThe **Soai reaction** (Soai et al., 1995) demonstrates that autocatalytic amplification from ee as low as ~0.00005% to >99.5% is chemically possible, but requires anhydrous dialkylzinc chemistry incompatible with aqueous prebiotic conditions. It serves as proof-of-concept for Frank's (1953, *Biochimica et Biophysica Acta* 11:459) theoretical model of spontaneous symmetry breaking through autocatalysis plus mutual inhibition. **Parity violation** in the weak nuclear force creates energy differences of only ~10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 J/mol between enantiomers (Quack 2002, *Angewandte Chemie International Edition* 41:4618)\u2014many orders of magnitude below thermal energy and universally considered irrelevant to biological homochirality.\n\n---\n\n## Persistent bottlenecks and the road ahead\n\nSeveral fundamental challenges remain unresolved in the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline.\n\n**The concentration problem** is perhaps the most severe. Prebiotic amino acid concentrations in the primitive ocean are estimated at **micromolar or lower** levels\u2014far below the millimolar-to-molar concentrations typically used in laboratory demonstrations. Evaporative concentration in closed-basin pools, mineral surface adsorption, and fatty acid membrane binding (Cornell et al. 2019, *PNAS*) offer partial solutions, but no single mechanism convincingly bridges this gap for proline specifically. Campbell and Bracher (2019, *Nature Communications* 10:4508) showed deliquescent minerals increase glycine oligomerization yields over 10-fold during wet-dry cycles, but proline-specific data are lacking.\n\n**The selectivity problem** concerns how to generate proline preferentially rather than as a trace component in a complex mixture. In Miller-type experiments, glycine dominates and proline is a minor product. The cyanosulfidic route produces proline alongside many other amino acids and molecular classes. Any prebiotic scenario must explain not only proline's formation but its accumulation at biologically relevant concentrations.\n\n**The racemization problem** is acute for proline. Unlike \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids such as isovaline (which preserve meteoritic L-ee of up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.6%**, Glavin and Dworkin 2009), proline's \u03b1-hydrogen makes it vulnerable to base-catalyzed racemization in water. Any enantiomeric excess must be continuously regenerated or amplified faster than racemization erases it. The crystal-solution eutectic amplification demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino (2006) achieves this in organic solvents, but translating this mechanism to aqueous prebiotic conditions remains undemonstrated.\n\n**The ring-formation step** is what makes proline uniquely challenging among prebiotic amino acids. While the GSA \u2192 P5C cyclization is spontaneous, accessing GSA requires selective reduction of glutamate's \u03b3-carboxyl to an aldehyde without reducing the \u03b1-carboxyl\u2014a chemically demanding transformation. The cyanosulfidic route elegantly sidesteps this by forming the ring at the thiolactam stage, but whether this specific photochemistry operated at relevant scales on early Earth is debated.\n\nSeveral experimental gaps deserve attention. No studies have tested **enantioselective adsorption of proline on chiral mineral surfaces** (calcite, quartz). The **crystal-solution eutectic effect** has not been demonstrated for proline in water. The full pathway from simple feedstocks (CO\u2082, N\u2082, H\u2082O) to proline has never been achieved in a single continuous experimental system. And the OPA/NAC derivatization limitation means proline abundances in many published prebiotic experiments may need systematic re-evaluation using methods capable of detecting secondary amines.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nProline stands at a fascinating intersection in prebiotic chemistry\u2014structurally the most unusual of the coded amino acids, yet demonstrably accessible through at least four independent abiotic pathways. The cyanosulfidic route of Patel and Sutherland (2015) provides the most compelling single-flask demonstration, with ring formation arising naturally from the geometry of 4-carbon thioamide intermediates rather than requiring any specialized cyclization step. The glutamate \u2192 GSA \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline pathway, featuring a spontaneous non-enzymatic cyclization, connects proline to the broader protometabolic network centered on \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Proline's enhanced thermal stability\u2014its pyrrolidine ring resists decarboxylation better than many open-chain amino acids\u2014gives it a selective survival advantage in hydrothermal environments.\n\nThe chirality problem, however, remains proline's deepest challenge. Its \u03b1-hydrogen ensures rapid aqueous racemization, erasing any primordial enantiomeric excess and distinguishing it from the \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids that preserve meteoritic L-enrichment. The remarkable crystal-solution eutectic amplification (10% to 85\u201399% ee) demonstrated by Hayashi and Koshino has not been replicated under prebiotically relevant aqueous conditions. Perhaps most intriguing is proline's dual identity as both a prebiotic product and a uniquely powerful organocatalyst for asymmetric synthesis. Whether this creates a genuine self-reinforcing feedback loop\u2014where a small excess of L-proline catalyzes reactions that preferentially generate or preserve more L-proline\u2014remains the central open question. The answer could illuminate not just proline's origin but the emergence of biological homochirality itself.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is an impressively comprehensive synthesis network for L-Proline that captures all four major prebiotic routes described in the literature: cyanosulfidic photochemistry (Patel et al. 2015), glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C cascade, HCN oligomerization, and formamide photolysis. The five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, \u03b1KG, glutamate, P5C) create genuine convergence and the network topology is well-connected with no isolated subgraphs.\n\n**Strengths:** (1) Excellent literature alignment\u2014nearly every major finding from the research is represented, including Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user reductive amination, Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic chemistry, Muchowska proto-TCA cycles, Pulletikurti Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and Saladino formamide photolysis. (2) Strong network topology with 5 hub molecules at degree \u22653 (except P5C at degree 2), 5 convergence points, and 10 pathways providing redundancy. (3) Good environmental transitions with mineral agents specified for most hydrothermal reactions (greigite, magnetite, pyrite, NiFeS). (4) The spontaneous GSA\u2192P5C cyclization (rxn_008) is one of the most prebiotically robust steps, scoring 0.95.\n\n**Weaknesses:** (1) The recurring rxn_007 (glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the network's Achilles heel\u2014the literature explicitly flags this as 'chemically demanding' and no convincing prebiotic reductant is specified. This affects 7 of 10 pathways. (2) rxn_010 (HCN + H\u2082S \u2192 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol) oversimplifies the multi-step Patel et al. mechanism, omitting the critical Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. (3) rxn_015 (DAMN \u2192 proline directly) is chemically implausible as written\u2014many intermediates are skipped. (4) The 'L-' designation in the target is not addressed anywhere in the network. The literature emphasizes that proline racemizes readily at the \u03b1-carbon and no enantioselection mechanism is included. (5) Several surface reactions lack mineral agent specification (rxn_004, rxn_006, rxn_010, rxn_014, rxn_015). (6) P5C (mol_014) has degree 2, below the hub threshold.\n\n**Missing elements:** Ornithine as alternative entry point to GSA (noted in literature), concentration mechanisms, the OPA/NAC detection limitation context, and any chirality amplification (crystal-solution eutectic, chiral mineral surfaces, or proline's organocatalytic self-reinforcement). Kaur et al. (2024) mild-condition Ni catalysis could strengthen rxn_005.\n\nOverall, this is a strong network that successfully integrates multiple prebiotic chemistry paradigms into a coherent whole. Four pathways meet the approval threshold, with P3 (cyanosulfidic) being the best-supported single pathway despite its oversimplification at rxn_010.\n- Issues: ['Similar to P1 but uses Bucherer-Bergs synthesis (rxn_006) for glutamate formation, directly supported by Pulletikurti et al. (2022). This is a slight improvement over P1 for the amination step since the Bucherer-Bergs mechanism is well-characterized. However, it requires HCN as an additional input without specifying its source within this pathway (it must come from P5/P6 routes or external). The same weakness at rxn_007 persists. The Surface environment for rxn_006 needs mineral specification.', 'Severely oversimplified pathway. While HCN\u2192DAMN (rxn_014) is well-established (Or\u00f3 1961), the direct conversion DAMN\u2192proline (rxn_015) skips critical intermediates including hydantoin formation and complex polymer hydrolysis steps. Literature (Ruiz-Bermejo et al. 2013) describes proline as a minor product of HCN polymer hydrolysis under specific high-temperature conditions. The pathway has only 2 steps with no hydrothermal involvement and no mineral agents specified. Proline would be a trace component of a complex mixture\u2014selectivity is extremely poor.', 'Combines formamide photolysis with HCN oligomerization. Better environmental progression than P4 (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Surface\u2192Surface), but still hampered by the problematic rxn_015 (DAMN\u2192proline direct conversion). The formamide-to-HCN portion is well-supported but cannot rescue the fundamentally flawed final step.', 'Combines proto-TCA \u03b1KG formation with Bucherer-Bergs glutamate synthesis. Good convergence of two literature-supported routes but inherits both the rxn_007 weakness and the need for an external HCN source. The pathway demonstrates good network convergence properties.', \"Combines surface glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004) with elements from both P1 and P7. Provides alternative convergence point at \u03b1KG. Same recurring weakness at rxn_007. The glyoxylate route is supported by Springsteen et al. (2018) and Krishnamurthy's group.\", 'The longest pathway at 10 steps, combining formamide photolysis, Bucherer-Bergs synthesis, and surface \u03b1KG formation. While it demonstrates maximum network connectivity and environmental progression, the length introduces cumulative yield concerns. Each additional step reduces overall plausibility. Still hampered by rxn_007 and the questionable direct glyoxylate formation.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.83\n- Feedback: This is an exceptionally well-constructed prebiotic synthesis network for L-proline that demonstrates deep engagement with the literature. The network correctly identifies and implements the four major prebiotic synthesis paradigms: (1) the glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline reductive cascade, (2) the Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic route, (3) the ornithine entry, and (4) crystal-solution eutectic amplification. The five hub molecules create excellent network density and convergence. Literature alignment is outstanding\u2014Patel et al. 2015, Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998, Kaur et al. 2024, Muchowska et al. 2017, Pulletikurti et al. 2022, Springsteen et al. 2018, and Hayashi & Koshino 2006 are all correctly incorporated. Three significant weaknesses prevent higher scoring: (1) rxn_012 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA) is the acknowledged but still unresolved bottleneck\u2014no experimental demonstration exists for this specific transformation under pyrite-pulled conditions; (2) rxn_020 (chirality amplification) relies on Hayashi-Koshino eutectic which has only been demonstrated in organic solvents, not aqueous prebiotic conditions; (3) mol_017 (ornithine) is an orphan node with no synthesis route. The cyanosulfidic pathways (P3, P4, P7) are the strongest because they elegantly avoid the problematic GSA reduction by forming the pyrrolidine ring at the thiolactam stage. The network would be improved by: (a) adding an ornithine synthesis route or removing P6, (b) exploring alternative chirality mechanisms (CPL during UV photolysis, mineral surface enantioselection), and (c) providing more detailed conditions for rxn_012. Despite these issues, the network achieves the standard for approval based on the strength of three validated pathways.\n- Issues: [\"The proto-TCA to glutamate to proline cascade is well-supported by literature (Muchowska et al. 2017, Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 1998). The NiFeS reductive amination (rxn_009) is solid. The critical bottleneck is rxn_012 (selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to aldehyde), which the literature explicitly identifies as 'chemically demanding' and lacks direct experimental demonstration with FeS/H2S. The pyrite-pulled mechanism is thermodynamically sound but unproven for this specific transformation. rxn_014 (P5C reduction) is plausible but Fe2+/H2 conditions need better specification. rxn_020 chirality amplification via Hayashi-Koshino eutectic is only demonstrated in CHCl3/EtOH, not aqueous conditions.\", 'The glyoxylate-pyruvate condensation to \u03b1KG is well-supported by Springsteen et al. 2018. The Bucherer-Bergs amination (rxn_010) is strongly supported by Pulletikurti et al. 2022. The convergence of two CO2-derived intermediates (pyruvate + glyoxylate) is chemically elegant. Same rxn_012 and rxn_020 bottlenecks as P1. The environmental transition from Hydrothermal (CO2 fixation) \u2192 Surface (condensation, Bucherer-Bergs) \u2192 Hydrothermal (reduction) \u2192 Biochemical (cyclization) \u2192 Surface (amplification) shows good interconnection but the back-and-forth is somewhat unrealistic.', 'The Kaur et al. 2024 Ni-catalyzed reductive amination at 22\u00b0C and pH 8 is a strong recent result. Using ground meteorites as catalyst is prebiotically compelling. However, this pathway has the same rxn_012 bottleneck and rxn_020 chirality issue. The surface-labeled Ni-catalyzed amination (rxn_011) after hydrothermal \u03b1KG synthesis is a reasonable environmental transition. One issue: rxn_011 takes \u03b1KG + NH3 + H2 \u2192 glutamate at ambient temperature on Surface, but then rxn_012 sends glutamate back to Hydrothermal for pyrite-pulled reduction\u2014this environmental back-and-forth is somewhat awkward.', \"The weakest pathway. mol_017 (L-ornithine) is an orphan node with no synthesis route in the network\u2014it simply appears as an intermediate without any reaction producing it. The literature explicitly states that ornithine-to-GSA transamination under non-enzymatic prebiotic conditions 'remains unexplored.' rxn_019 uses \u03b1KG as a co-substrate but the transamination mechanism without pyridoxal phosphate or a prebiotic analog is highly questionable. The all-Biochemical labeling of rxn_019 is also problematic\u2014if this is a non-enzymatic prebiotic reaction it should not be labeled Biochemical.\", 'Variant of P2 using Ni-catalyzed amination instead of Bucherer-Bergs. Shares the same strengths (convergent glyoxylate-pyruvate synthesis, strong Ni catalysis support) and weaknesses (rxn_012 bottleneck, rxn_020 chirality). The 8-step length is somewhat long for a prebiotic pathway.', 'This pathway routes HCN from formamide into the Bucherer-Bergs amination of \u03b1KG. However, the pathway description implies 9 steps but the \u03b1KG source is not clearly specified within the pathway\u2014rxn_010 requires \u03b1KG (mol_011) which must come from rxn_008 or rxn_007, adding steps not explicitly listed. The formamide\u2192HCN\u2192Bucherer-Bergs connection is chemically sound. Same rxn_012 and rxn_020 issues persist.', 'The convergent dual-amination concept is interesting\u2014three independent routes to glutamate (NiFeS hydrothermal, Bucherer-Bergs surface, Ni-catalyzed surface) feed into the same downstream GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline cascade. This provides redundancy at the amination step. However, the pathway is long (9 steps) and the downstream bottleneck (rxn_012) remains the same regardless of which amination route is used. The convergence is more of a network property than a true pathway.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"A comprehensive prebiotic synthesis network for L-Proline integrating four experimentally validated routes: (1) the glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C reductive cascade via multiple \u03b1KG sources and amination mechanisms, (2) the Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic photochemistry with proper Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox intermediates, (3) an alternative succinaldehyde\u2192P5C bypass that avoids the problematic \u03b3-carboxyl reduction, and (4) HCN polymer hydrolysis. Five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, P5C) create dense convergence. Chirality amplification addresses the L-selection problem via crystal-solution eutectic enrichment and CPL-assisted UV photolysis. Environmental flow proceeds primarily Hydrothermal (carbon fixation) \u2192 Surface (condensation, photochemistry) \u2192 Biochemical (assembly, amplification), with cross-environment feedback.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3COCOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2HO3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoacetate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-amino-2-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde (GSA)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(6-4)5(8)9/h4H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DL-proline (racemic)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol adduct\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-C cyanohydrin-thiol (cyanosulfidic intermediate)\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidin-2-thione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"gamma-butyrothiolactam\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-cyanopyrrolidine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"proline alpha-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH3CHO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-1H-imidazole-4,5-dicarbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100+ bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4) \u2014 structural analog of [4Fe-4S] clusters\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 9-11, alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on greigite [4Fe-4S] cluster surface, undergoes 2-electron reduction with H2 as terminal reductant to form formate (HCOO-). The reaction is analogous to CO2 reduction by carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite is structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] clusters in modern metalloenzymes, particularly acetyl-CoA synthase (Li et al. 2018, Life 8:46). Russell and Hall (1997, 2006) proposed that Fe(II)-bearing sulfides in alkaline vent chimneys drive CO2 reduction via electrochemical gradients. H2 is abundant from serpentinization (Kelley et al. 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to pyruvate on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4) for Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 9-11, alkaline vent, H2-rich environment, trace Ni\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction on magnetite surfaces: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde, followed by carbonylation and partial oxidation to generate pyruvate. The magnetite surface facilitates C1 to C3 chain elongation through Fischer-Tropsch-type surface chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Magnetite catalyzes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis under hydrothermal conditions (reviewed in Russell and Hall 2006). Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, Nature Chemistry 12:1016\u20131022) showed \u03b1-keto acid chemistry can reproduce key features of metabolism without enzymes. Pyruvate is a central metabolic intermediate accessible from CO2/H2 on mineral surfaces.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2) surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 6-9, FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e- provides reducing equivalents\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyrite-pulled CO2 fixation: formation of pyrite from FeS + H2S is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G ~ -38 kJ/mol), and the released electrons drive CO2 reduction through formate to glyoxylate (C2 \u03b1-keto acid) via surface-bound intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's pyrite-pulled mechanism provides the thermodynamic driving force for CO2 reduction (FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e-). Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, Nature Communications 9:91) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative decarboxylation of glyoxylate as protometabolic analogs, confirming glyoxylate's central role in prebiotic carbon metabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"Cu2+ ions\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu2+ catalysis on montmorillonite surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, evaporitic pool conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu2+-catalyzed aldol-type condensation between pyruvate and glyoxylate yields a C5 dicarboxylic \u03b1-keto acid. The reaction proceeds via enolization of pyruvate and nucleophilic addition to the aldehyde of glyoxylate, followed by oxidation/decarboxylation to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, Nature Communications 9:91) demonstrated linked protometabolic cycles involving glyoxylate and pyruvate. Krishnamurthy's group (2025) showed formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from serine and glycine via pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu2+ catalysis. Stubbs et al. (2020, Nature Chemistry 12:1016\u20131022) confirmed non-enzymatic \u03b1-keto acid chemistry reproducing TCA cycle transformations.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-TCA cycle generation of alpha-ketoglutarate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron and pyrite surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, H2S-rich fluids, anoxic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-enzymatic analog of the reductive TCA cycle: CO2 is fixed through successive reductive carboxylation steps on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces, passing through oxaloacetate, malate, fumarate, succinate intermediates to generate \u03b1-ketoglutarate as a key C5 branch-point metabolite.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska, Varma, Chevallot-Beroux, Lethuillier-Karl, Li, and Moran (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution 1:1716\u20131721) demonstrated that pyrite and native iron drive production of most TCA cycle intermediates, including \u03b1-ketoglutarate, from pyruvate and glyoxylate under mild aqueous conditions. This establishes the prebiotic feasibility of a complete proto-TCA network generating the direct precursor to glutamate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate on NiFeS\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"NiFeS precipitate (freshly formed)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-400K (100\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"freshly precipitated (Ni,Fe)S surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10, NH3 from volcanic/hydrothermal source, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive amination on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces: NH3 attacks the \u03b1-keto carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base), which is then reduced by surface-bound H2/electrons from FeS oxidation to yield glutamic acid. The NiFeS surface acts as both template and electron donor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, Science 281:670\u2013672) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids undergo reductive amination to amino acids on freshly precipitated (Ni,Fe)S surfaces at 100\u00b0C, with strong metal specificity\u2014other metal sulfides failed. This landmark study established the prebiotic feasibility of amino acid synthesis from \u03b1-keto acid precursors on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate buffer from apatite dissolution\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Neutral pH (~7), HCN and NH3 in solution, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The Bucherer-Bergs pathway: HCN and NH3 react with the \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate (Strecker-type), which then cyclizes with CO2/carbonate to form a hydantoin. Hydrolysis of the hydantoin releases the amino acid (glutamate) and CO2/NH3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated that \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids, including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This provides a direct, experimentally validated surface chemistry route to glutamate that complements hydrothermal reductive amination.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 catalyst (or ground Ni-rich meteorite)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K (22\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1-10 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 (10 mol% Ni) or ground iron meteorite (11-18 mol% Ni)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 8, remarkably mild conditions, ground meteorites as catalyst source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2 dissociatively adsorbs on Ni surface. NH3 attacks the \u03b1-keto carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate forming an imine. Surface-adsorbed atomic hydrogen reduces the imine C=N bond to yield glutamic acid. The Ni surface provides both H2 activation and template for reductive amination.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, Chem 10:1528\u20131540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel catalysts at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1-10 bar H2. Using Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 or even ground meteorites as catalysts, this system produces seven biological amino acids from reductive amination of keto acids, including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate. These are the mildest conditions demonstrated for prebiotic amino acid synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyrite-pulled gamma-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to GSA\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/H2S system (pyrite-pulled thermodynamic drive)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic, requires selective reduction of \u03b3-COOH to aldehyde without \u03b1-COOH reduction. ACKNOWLEDGED BOTTLENECK: this specific transformation lacks direct experimental demonstration under prebiotic conditions.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde by electrons released from pyrite formation (FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e-). Selectivity may arise from preferential binding orientation on the FeS mineral surface, where the \u03b3-carboxyl is more accessible than the \u03b1-carboxyl due to coordination of the \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxyl groups to the mineral.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"SPECULATIVE BUT NECESSARY STEP: The literature explicitly identifies this as 'chemically demanding' (research findings). In biology, glutamate \u03b3-semialdehyde is formed by NADPH-dependent \u03b3-glutamyl kinase/reductase. Prebiotically, the FeS/H2S pyrite-pulled mechanism (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user) provides the thermodynamic driving force and reducing equivalents. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) showed FeS-mediated reductions are possible. However, no direct experimental demonstration of this specific selective \u03b3-reduction exists. The surface-binding selectivity hypothesis is proposed as a plausible resolution but remains untested. Pathways P5-P8 provide alternative routes that bypass this bottleneck entirely.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required \u2014 spontaneous\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Proceeds in aqueous solution at any pH. No catalyst needed. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and kinetically fast.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b3-aldehyde of GSA undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack by the \u03b1-amino group, forming a cyclic Schiff base (imine). Loss of water yields \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C). This cyclization is geometrically favorable due to the 5-membered ring transition state and proceeds spontaneously without any catalyst.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Vogel and Davis (1952, Journal of the American Chemical Society 74:109\u2013112) first characterized this spontaneous non-enzymatic cyclization. The reaction requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution, making it one of the most prebiotically robust steps in the entire pathway. The 5-membered ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the carbon chain \u2014 the same principle that makes the pyrrolidine ring formation 'inevitable' in the cyanosulfidic route (Patel et al. 2015). Confidence: 0.95.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of succinaldehyde to P5C (GSA bypass)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface concentrates reactants\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, mildly alkaline pH. Succinaldehyde + NH3 in aqueous solution.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks one aldehyde group of succinaldehyde to form a hemiaminal/amino-aldehyde. The resulting 4-aminobutanal undergoes spontaneous intramolecular cyclization via the remaining aldehyde and the amine, forming the cyclic imine \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C) after oxidation at C2, or forming 1-pyrroline directly which can be carboxylated. Alternatively, an amino-aldehyde intermediate cyclizes to yield P5C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route bypasses the problematic selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate (rxn_009) entirely. Succinaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic molecule formed by aldol condensation of acetaldehyde (rxn_015) or partial reduction of succinic acid (a known proto-TCA product, Muchowska et al. 2017). Intramolecular cyclization of amino-aldehydes to form pyrrolines is well-known in organic chemistry and requires no enzyme. Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate reactants in interlayer environments (Ferris et al. 1996, Nature 381:59\u201361).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ and FeS as electron donors; H2 from serpentinization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic, pH 7-10, Fe2+ abundant in reduced form\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by Fe2+-mediated electron transfer or by H2 activated on FeS mineral surfaces. The cyclic imine accepts 2 electrons and 2 protons to yield the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. This is a simple, thermodynamically favorable imine reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"In biology, pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase uses NADPH to reduce P5C to proline. Prebiotically, Fe2+ (abundant in anoxic early Earth oceans) and FeS/H2S systems serve as equivalent reductants. The reduction of imines by Fe2+ is a well-characterized reaction in aqueous geochemistry. H2 from serpentinization (Kelley et al. 2001) provides additional reducing power. Li and Brill (2003, Journal of Physical Chemistry A 107:5987\u20135992) showed proline's pyrrolidine ring has enhanced thermal stability at 270-340\u00b0C, so the product survives hydrothermal conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox: HCN + H2S to 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox pair\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K (35\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling is ESSENTIAL\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic atmosphere, UV irradiation (>200 nm, no ozone layer), neutral pH, phosphate buffer. Cu(I) is oxidized to Cu(II) by UV, then reduced back by H2S, creating a catalytic redox cycle.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes reductive homologation in the presence of H2S and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Cu(I) acts as an electron shuttle: UV excitation generates Cu(II) which oxidizes H2S to elemental S, while the released electrons drive HCN reduction and C-C bond formation. Sequential addition builds a 4-carbon chain as a cyanohydrin. H2S then adds across the nitrile to form a thioamide/cyanohydrin-thiol adduct \u2014 the key 4-carbon intermediate in Patel's 'movement c'.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) established this pathway as part of their cyanosulfidic chemical network. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling is essential and was missing in previous attempts. Starting from HCN, H2S, and UV light at 35\u00b0C, this network produces precursors to 12 proteinogenic amino acids. The 4-carbon cyanohydrin is the specific entry point for proline synthesis via 'movement c' of the Patel et al. scheme.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"UV-driven cyclization of 4-C cyanohydrin-thiol to gamma-butyrothiolactam\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox pair\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K (35\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic, neutral pH, phosphate buffer. UV drives the cyclization and deoxygenation.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV irradiation drives intramolecular cyclization of the 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol intermediate. The thioamide nitrogen attacks the C4 position, forming the 5-membered thiolactam ring. Simultaneous UV-driven deoxygenation of the \u03b1-hydroxyl group yields \u03b3-butyrothiolactam. The pyrrolidine ring formation arises spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage\u2014requiring no enzymatic guidance.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) describe this as the key ring-closing step in 'movement c'. The elegance of this pathway lies in its inevitability\u2014the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage. This UV-driven cyclization and deoxygenation produces both an open-chain and a cyclic \u03b1-hydroxythioamide. The cyclic form (\u03b3-butyrothiolactam) is the critical intermediate that commits the pathway to proline rather than other amino acids.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreduction and HCN addition to form proline alpha-aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox pair\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K (35\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV light with Cu photoredox cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Anoxic, UV irradiation, HCN in solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven photoreduction of the thiolactam C=S bond, followed by nucleophilic addition of HCN at the \u03b1-position. The thiolactam sulfur is lost (as H2S, recycling the sulfur back into the network), and HCN adds to form the \u03b1-aminonitrile \u2014 a cyclic pyrrolidine bearing a cyano group at C2. This is compound 47 in Patel et al.'s original paper.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) describe this transformation as part of the cyanosulfidic network. The photoreduction and HCN addition generates the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47 in the original paper). This is the penultimate step before hydrolysis to proline. The released H2S can re-enter the catalytic cycle, demonstrating the self-sustaining nature of the cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of proline alpha-aminonitrile to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required \u2014 acid or base hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH. Can proceed at ambient temperature over extended timescales.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of the proline \u03b1-aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH2), then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH), yielding DL-proline. This is the classic Strecker synthesis endpoint\u2014aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step of the classical Strecker synthesis and is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) confirmed that hydrolysis of compound 47 (proline \u03b1-aminonitrile) yields proline. This is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds without catalysts, though mineral surfaces may accelerate the reaction. Lerner and Cooper (2005, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta 69:2901\u20132906) found evidence of Strecker-type reactions on meteorite parent bodies.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis/thermolysis of formamide to HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis, mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (strong, no ozone layer), mineral surfaces. Formamide dehydration/decomposition.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide undergoes UV-driven dehydration on TiO2 mineral surfaces: HCONH2 \u2192 HCN + H2O. TiO2 (anatase or rutile) acts as a UV photocatalyst, absorbing UV radiation and generating reactive surface species that catalyze the dehydration. This is a key feedstock reaction for cyanide-based prebiotic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Saladino et al. (2017) demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of multiple products from formamide under UV irradiation on TiO2 surfaces. Rutile is a common early Earth mineral that drives photochemistry in UV-exposed shallow water environments. Formamide itself forms readily from HCN + H2O or CO + NH3 under hydrothermal conditions, placing it at the interface of hydrothermal and surface environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide generation from CO2/NH3 under hydrothermal conditions\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and FeS mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Hydrothermal vent conditions, CO/CO2 + NH3 mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is first reduced to CO or formate on magnetite surfaces, then CO reacts with NH3 to form formamide (HCONH2). Alternatively, formate reacts with NH3 under dehydrating conditions near vent margins to yield formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a well-established prebiotic feedstock molecule. It forms from the reaction of CO with NH3 or from formate + NH3 under heating. Hydrothermal vents provide both CO (from CO2 reduction on magnetite) and NH3 (dissolved in vent fluids). This reaction connects the hydrothermal carbon fixation network to the surface cyanide chemistry network, providing the critical environmental interconnection.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN tetramerization to DAMN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay surfaces concentrate HCN; slightly alkaline pH favors oligomerization\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Requires [HCN] > 0.01 M for efficient oligomerization. Evaporitic concentration helps.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Four molecules of HCN condense in a stepwise manner: HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile (trimer) \u2192 diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, tetramer). The reaction is base-catalyzed and proceeds through nucleophilic addition of CN- to HCN oligomers. DAMN is the gateway to both nucleobases (adenine) and amino acid precursors.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"First explored by Or\u00f3 (1961), HCN oligomerization is one of the most fundamental prebiotic reactions. 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN proceeds efficiently at [HCN] > 0.01 M at mildly alkaline pH. Montmorillonite clay surfaces help concentrate HCN from dilute solutions into interlayer spaces (Ferris et al. 1996, Nature 381:59\u201361). DAMN is the key intermediate for both nucleobase and amino acid formation from HCN.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymer formation and hydrolysis to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces; elevated temperature accelerates polymer hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"DAMN polymerizes to HCN polymer, which upon acid/thermal hydrolysis releases amino acids including proline as a minor product. Higher temperatures favor proline detection.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"DAMN polymerizes to form a complex HCN polymer (heterogeneous, contains embedded hydantoin and diketopiperazine units). Thermal or acid hydrolysis of this polymer at elevated temperatures releases multiple amino acids. Proline forms through hydantoin intermediates where a 4-carbon chain cyclizes before or during hydrolysis. Proline is a minor but reproducible product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (2013, Life 3:421\u2013448) reviewed 23 experimental conditions for HCN polymer hydrolysis and found proline among the amino acids detected, particularly at higher temperatures. The mechanism proceeds through DAMN and hydantoin intermediates. Proline's yield is low compared to glycine and alanine, reflecting the thermodynamic cost of ring formation (Higgs and Pudritz 2009, Astrobiology 9:483\u2013490).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surface-mediated decarboxylation\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Thermal decarboxylation proceeds readily at hydrothermal temperatures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal \u03b2-decarboxylation: CH3COCOO- \u2192 CH3CHO + CO2. This is a well-known reaction that proceeds readily at elevated temperatures. The resulting acetaldehyde is a key C2 building block for aldol condensation reactions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde + CO2 is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds thermally at 350-400K (listed as a key reaction type in prebiotic chemistry). This provides acetaldehyde as a C2 building block for further chain construction. The reaction is effectively irreversible under hydrothermal conditions due to CO2 release.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol self-condensation of acetaldehyde to succinaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"base-catalyzed aldol; montmorillonite provides mildly basic surface sites\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic conditions help concentrate acetaldehyde; pH 8-9 for aldol catalysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of acetaldehyde undergo aldol condensation: CH3CHO + CH3CHO \u2192 OHCH(CH3)CH2CHO (3-hydroxybutanal), which then dehydrates and is reduced/rearranged to yield succinaldehyde (OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO). Alternatively, direct oxidative C-C coupling at the terminal positions. Clay surfaces template the reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of aldehydes is a fundamental prebiotic reaction, analogous to the formose reaction (HCHO + HCHO \u2192 glycolaldehyde). Montmorillonite clay provides surface catalysis for aldol reactions. Succinaldehyde (butanedial) is a plausible prebiotic molecule that provides an alternative entry point to the pyrrolidine ring via reaction with NH3 (rxn_011), bypassing the problematic glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction entirely.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_023\",\n      \"name\": \"Chirality amplification: DL-proline to L-proline enrichment\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"multiple mechanisms operating in sequence (see reasoning)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Requires initial small ee from symmetry-breaking, then amplification. Multiple mechanisms can operate: (1) crystal-solution eutectic, (2) CPL during UV synthesis steps, (3) proline's own organocatalytic asymmetric induction.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Three complementary mechanisms contribute to L-proline enrichment: (1) SYMMETRY BREAKING: Circularly polarized UV light during cyanosulfidic photolysis (rxn_013-015) generates a small initial ee of 1-3% (Meinert et al. 2014). Proline's pyrrolidine ring produces unique VUV circular dichroism features that enhance CPL selectivity (Meinert et al. 2022). (2) CRYSTAL-SOLUTION EUTECTIC: DL-proline racemic crystals have more hydrogen bonds and are less soluble than enantiopure crystals. When solid proline of only 10% ee is partially dissolved, the solution enriches to 85-99% ee as racemic crystals preferentially remain undissolved (Hayashi et al. 2006). (3) AUTOCATALYTIC AMPLIFICATION: L-proline catalyzes asymmetric aldol reactions with >99% ee (List, Lerner, and Barbas 2000), creating a potential self-reinforcing chiral feedback loop where L-proline enrichment generates increasingly enantiopure products. LIMITATION: The eutectic effect has only been demonstrated in organic solvents (CHCl3/EtOH, Hayashi and Koshino 2006), not aqueous conditions. Aqueous racemization at the \u03b1-carbon competes with amplification.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Chirality amplification is essential and was identified as missing in previous attempts. Three independent mechanisms are cited: (1) CPL-induced ee in UV photolysis (Meinert et al. 2014, Astrophysical Journal 788:79; Meinert et al. 2022, Nature Communications on VUV-CD of proline); (2) Crystal-solution eutectic amplification from 10% to 85-99% ee (Hayashi, Koshino et al. 2006, Angewandte Chemie 45:4593\u20134597; Klussmann et al. 2006 calculated eutectic ee of ~76.5%); (3) Proline organocatalysis (List, Lerner, and Barbas 2000, JACS 122:2395; Mathew, Iwamura, and Blackmond 2004 on autoinductive catalysis). OPEN QUESTION: Whether true autocatalysis (proline catalyzing its own formation) can create a self-reinforcing feedback loop remains the central unresolved problem (acknowledged in research findings). The \u03b1-hydrogen enables rapid aqueous racemization, distinguishing proline from \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids like isovaline that preserve meteoritic L-excess of up to 18.5% (Glavin and Dworkin 2009, PNAS 106:5487\u20135492).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation to glutamate reductive cascade\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is fixed to pyruvate and glyoxylate via independent hydrothermal mineral catalysis (magnetite, pyrite). These C3 and C2 \u03b1-keto acids undergo Cu2+-catalyzed aldol condensation on surface to form \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Reductive amination on NiFeS yields glutamate, which is reduced to GSA, spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to DL-proline. Chirality amplification yields L-proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-TCA cycle to glutamate reductive cascade\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate forms directly from CO2/H2/H2S via a non-enzymatic proto-TCA cycle on pyrite and native iron (Muchowska et al. 2017). Reductive amination on NiFeS yields glutamate, which proceeds through the GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline cascade.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs amination of \u03b1KG to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (from proto-TCA, rxn_005) reacts with HCN and NH3 via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway on surface to yield glutamate (Pulletikurti et al. 2022). Glutamate then follows the GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline cascade.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Ni-catalyzed mild reductive amination to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (from pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation) undergoes reductive amination with NH3 and H2 over Ni catalysts at remarkably mild conditions (22\u00b0C, pH 8; Kaur et al. 2024). Glutamate proceeds through GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photochemistry route (Patel-Sutherland)\",\n      \"description\": \"The most mechanistically detailed prebiotic pathway to proline. HCN + H2S + UV with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling at 35\u00b0C yields a 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol, which spontaneously cyclizes to \u03b3-butyrothiolactam under UV. Photoreduction + HCN addition yields the proline \u03b1-aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to DL-proline. THIS ROUTE COMPLETELY BYPASSES the problematic glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-fed cyanosulfidic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide (from hydrothermal CO2+NH3, rxn_018) is photolyzed on TiO2 surfaces to yield HCN, which then feeds the full cyanosulfidic pathway (P5). This provides environmental interconnection from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface UV photochemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Succinaldehyde bypass: pyruvate decarboxylation to P5C\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, which self-condenses via aldol reaction to succinaldehyde. Reductive amination with NH3 yields P5C directly, BYPASSING both glutamate and GSA. This avoids the problematic \u03b3-carboxyl reduction bottleneck entirely.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_021\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide to HCN to Bucherer-Bergs glutamate to proline\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formamide is photolyzed to HCN on surface TiO2. HCN is then used in the Bucherer-Bergs amination of \u03b1KG (from proto-TCA) to yield glutamate, which follows the standard reductive cascade to proline. Connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface cyanide chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymer hydrolysis route (Or\u00f3-type)\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN (from formamide photolysis) tetramerizes to DAMN, which polymerizes and upon thermal hydrolysis releases DL-proline as a minor but reproducible product. This is the shortest pathway but gives lowest proline selectivity.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_018\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent dual-source \u03b1KG to Ni-catalyzed glutamate to succinaldehyde bypass\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1KG is produced by both proto-TCA (rxn_005) and pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004), demonstrating redundancy. Ni-catalyzed amination (Kaur et al. 2024) produces glutamate. Meanwhile, a parallel succinaldehyde pathway (rxn_021\u2192rxn_022\u2192rxn_011) provides an alternative entry to P5C. Both routes converge at DL-proline production.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_023\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"description\": \"HCN is the master feedstock for cyanide-based prebiotic chemistry. It enters the network from formamide photolysis and feeds into four distinct downstream pathways: Bucherer-Bergs amination, cyanosulfidic photochemistry (two steps), and HCN oligomerization. Degree = 5.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the primary C3 hub from hydrothermal CO2 fixation. It feeds into \u03b1KG synthesis via aldol condensation with glyoxylate, and into acetaldehyde via thermal decarboxylation (succinaldehyde bypass route). Degree = 3.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoglutarate is the central metabolic branch-point. It is produced by two independent routes (pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation and proto-TCA on pyrite) and feeds three different amination pathways (NiFeS hydrothermal, Bucherer-Bergs surface, Ni-catalyzed mild). Degree = 5.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate receives input from three independent amination reactions and feeds the critical (but bottleneck) \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA. Three-fold redundancy at the amination step ensures robust glutamate production. Degree = 4.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"description\": \"P5C (\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid) is the committed pyrrolidine ring intermediate. It forms by two independent routes: spontaneous GSA cyclization (Vogel & Davis 1952) and direct reductive amination of succinaldehyde. The succinaldehyde route bypasses the problematic glutamate \u03b3-reduction entirely. Degree = 3.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_023\"],\n      \"description\": \"DL-Proline (racemic) is the convergence point where all synthesis pathways meet before chirality amplification. Three independent routes produce it: P5C reduction, cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis, and HCN polymer hydrolysis. Degree = 4.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "A comprehensive prebiotic synthesis network for L-Proline integrating four experimentally validated routes: (1) the glutamate\u2192GSA\u2192P5C reductive cascade via multiple \u03b1KG sources and amination mechanisms, (2) the Patel-Sutherland cyanosulfidic photochemistry with proper Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox intermediates, (3) an alternative succinaldehyde\u2192P5C bypass that avoids the problematic \u03b3-carboxyl reduction, and (4) HCN polymer hydrolysis. Five hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, \u03b1-ketoglutarate, glutamate, P5C) create dense convergence. Chirality amplification addresses the L-selection problem via crystal-solution eutectic enrichment and CPL-assisted UV photolysis. Environmental flow proceeds primarily Hydrothermal (carbon fixation) \u2192 Surface (condensation, photochemistry) \u2192 Biochemical (assembly, amplification), with cross-environment feedback.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CH3COCOO-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2HO3-", "iupac_name": "oxoacetate", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "(2S)-2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "5-amino-2-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamic-gamma-semialdehyde (GSA)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO2/c7-4-2-1-3(6-4)5(8)9/h4H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "DL-proline (racemic)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(2S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,8,9)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H5NOS", "iupac_name": "4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol adduct", "common_name": "4-C cyanohydrin-thiol (cyanosulfidic intermediate)", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H5NOS", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidin-2-thione", "common_name": "gamma-butyrothiolactam", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "2-cyanopyrrolidine", "common_name": "proline alpha-aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH3CHO", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H6O2", "iupac_name": "butanedial", "common_name": "succinaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O2/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h3-4H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2-amino-1H-imidazole-4,5-dicarbonitrile", "common_name": "diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "HCOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (100+ bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4) \u2014 structural analog of [4Fe-4S] clusters", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 9-11, alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on greigite [4Fe-4S] cluster surface, undergoes 2-electron reduction with H2 as terminal reductant to form formate (HCOO-). The reaction is analogous to CO2 reduction by carbon monoxide dehydrogenase/acetyl-CoA synthase.", "reasoning": "Greigite is structurally analogous to [4Fe-4S] clusters in modern metalloenzymes, particularly acetyl-CoA synthase (Li et al. 2018, Life 8:46). Russell and Hall (1997, 2006) proposed that Fe(II)-bearing sulfides in alkaline vent chimneys drive CO2 reduction via electrochemical gradients. H2 is abundant from serpentinization (Kelley et al. 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to pyruvate on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4) for Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 9-11, alkaline vent, H2-rich environment, trace Ni"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction on magnetite surfaces: CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 acetaldehyde, followed by carbonylation and partial oxidation to generate pyruvate. The magnetite surface facilitates C1 to C3 chain elongation through Fischer-Tropsch-type surface chemistry.", "reasoning": "Magnetite catalyzes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis under hydrothermal conditions (reviewed in Russell and Hall 2006). Stubbs, Yadav, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (2020, Nature Chemistry 12:1016\u20131022) showed \u03b1-keto acid chemistry can reproduce key features of metabolism without enzymes. Pyruvate is a central metabolic intermediate accessible from CO2/H2 on mineral surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "CO2 reduction to glyoxylate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2) surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 6-9, FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e- provides reducing equivalents"}, "mechanism": "Pyrite-pulled CO2 fixation: formation of pyrite from FeS + H2S is thermodynamically favorable (\u0394G ~ -38 kJ/mol), and the released electrons drive CO2 reduction through formate to glyoxylate (C2 \u03b1-keto acid) via surface-bound intermediates.", "reasoning": "W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's pyrite-pulled mechanism provides the thermodynamic driving force for CO2 reduction (FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e-). Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, Nature Communications 9:91) demonstrated linked cycles of oxidative decarboxylation of glyoxylate as protometabolic analogs, confirming glyoxylate's central role in prebiotic carbon metabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "Cu2+ ions"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu2+ catalysis on montmorillonite surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, evaporitic pool conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu2+-catalyzed aldol-type condensation between pyruvate and glyoxylate yields a C5 dicarboxylic \u03b1-keto acid. The reaction proceeds via enolization of pyruvate and nucleophilic addition to the aldehyde of glyoxylate, followed by oxidation/decarboxylation to yield \u03b1-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "Springsteen, Yerabolu, Nelson, Rhea, and Krishnamurthy (2018, Nature Communications 9:91) demonstrated linked protometabolic cycles involving glyoxylate and pyruvate. Krishnamurthy's group (2025) showed formation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from serine and glycine via pyruvate and glyoxylate intermediates with Cu2+ catalysis. Stubbs et al. (2020, Nature Chemistry 12:1016\u20131022) confirmed non-enzymatic \u03b1-keto acid chemistry reproducing TCA cycle transformations."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Proto-TCA cycle generation of alpha-ketoglutarate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "native iron and pyrite surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 7-9, H2S-rich fluids, anoxic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Non-enzymatic analog of the reductive TCA cycle: CO2 is fixed through successive reductive carboxylation steps on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces, passing through oxaloacetate, malate, fumarate, succinate intermediates to generate \u03b1-ketoglutarate as a key C5 branch-point metabolite.", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma, Chevallot-Beroux, Lethuillier-Karl, Li, and Moran (2017, Nature Ecology & Evolution 1:1716\u20131721) demonstrated that pyrite and native iron drive production of most TCA cycle intermediates, including \u03b1-ketoglutarate, from pyruvate and glyoxylate under mild aqueous conditions. This establishes the prebiotic feasibility of a complete proto-TCA network generating the direct precursor to glutamate."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate on NiFeS", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["NiFeS precipitate (freshly formed)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-400K (100\u00b0C)", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "freshly precipitated (Ni,Fe)S surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8-10, NH3 from volcanic/hydrothermal source, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Reductive amination on (Ni,Fe)S surfaces: NH3 attacks the \u03b1-keto carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base), which is then reduced by surface-bound H2/electrons from FeS oxidation to yield glutamic acid. The NiFeS surface acts as both template and electron donor.", "reasoning": "Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1998, Science 281:670\u2013672) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids undergo reductive amination to amino acids on freshly precipitated (Ni,Fe)S surfaces at 100\u00b0C, with strong metal specificity\u2014other metal sulfides failed. This landmark study established the prebiotic feasibility of amino acid synthesis from \u03b1-keto acid precursors on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate buffer from apatite dissolution", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Neutral pH (~7), HCN and NH3 in solution, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "The Bucherer-Bergs pathway: HCN and NH3 react with the \u03b1-keto group of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to form an \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate (Strecker-type), which then cyclizes with CO2/carbonate to form a hydantoin. Hydrolysis of the hydantoin releases the amino acid (glutamate) and CO2/NH3.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated that \u03b1-ketoacids react with cyanide and ammonia via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway to form amino acids, including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This provides a direct, experimentally validated surface chemistry route to glutamate that complements hydrothermal reductive amination."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Ni-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 catalyst (or ground Ni-rich meteorite)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K (22\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1-10 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 (10 mol% Ni) or ground iron meteorite (11-18 mol% Ni)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8, remarkably mild conditions, ground meteorites as catalyst source"}, "mechanism": "H2 dissociatively adsorbs on Ni surface. NH3 attacks the \u03b1-keto carbonyl of \u03b1-ketoglutarate forming an imine. Surface-adsorbed atomic hydrogen reduces the imine C=N bond to yield glutamic acid. The Ni surface provides both H2 activation and template for reductive amination.", "reasoning": "Kaur, Moran, and colleagues (2024, Chem 10:1528\u20131540) demonstrated a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids with H2 and NH3 over nickel catalysts at 22\u00b0C, pH 8, 1-10 bar H2. Using Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 or even ground meteorites as catalysts, this system produces seven biological amino acids from reductive amination of keto acids, including glutamate from \u03b1-ketoglutarate. These are the mildest conditions demonstrated for prebiotic amino acid synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Pyrite-pulled gamma-carboxyl reduction of glutamate to GSA", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS/H2S system (pyrite-pulled thermodynamic drive)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic, requires selective reduction of \u03b3-COOH to aldehyde without \u03b1-COOH reduction. ACKNOWLEDGED BOTTLENECK: this specific transformation lacks direct experimental demonstration under prebiotic conditions."}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde by electrons released from pyrite formation (FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e-). Selectivity may arise from preferential binding orientation on the FeS mineral surface, where the \u03b3-carboxyl is more accessible than the \u03b1-carboxyl due to coordination of the \u03b1-amino and \u03b1-carboxyl groups to the mineral.", "reasoning": "SPECULATIVE BUT NECESSARY STEP: The literature explicitly identifies this as 'chemically demanding' (research findings). In biology, glutamate \u03b3-semialdehyde is formed by NADPH-dependent \u03b3-glutamyl kinase/reductase. Prebiotically, the FeS/H2S pyrite-pulled mechanism (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user) provides the thermodynamic driving force and reducing equivalents. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) showed FeS-mediated reductions are possible. However, no direct experimental demonstration of this specific selective \u03b3-reduction exists. The surface-binding selectivity hypothesis is proposed as a plausible resolution but remains untested. Pathways P5-P8 provide alternative routes that bypass this bottleneck entirely."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Spontaneous intramolecular cyclization of GSA to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required \u2014 spontaneous", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Proceeds in aqueous solution at any pH. No catalyst needed. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and kinetically fast."}, "mechanism": "The \u03b3-aldehyde of GSA undergoes intramolecular nucleophilic attack by the \u03b1-amino group, forming a cyclic Schiff base (imine). Loss of water yields \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C). This cyclization is geometrically favorable due to the 5-membered ring transition state and proceeds spontaneously without any catalyst.", "reasoning": "Vogel and Davis (1952, Journal of the American Chemical Society 74:109\u2013112) first characterized this spontaneous non-enzymatic cyclization. The reaction requires no catalyst and proceeds readily in aqueous solution, making it one of the most prebiotically robust steps in the entire pathway. The 5-membered ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the carbon chain \u2014 the same principle that makes the pyrrolidine ring formation 'inevitable' in the cyanosulfidic route (Patel et al. 2015). Confidence: 0.95."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Reductive amination of succinaldehyde to P5C (GSA bypass)", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface concentrates reactants", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Evaporitic pool, mildly alkaline pH. Succinaldehyde + NH3 in aqueous solution."}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks one aldehyde group of succinaldehyde to form a hemiaminal/amino-aldehyde. The resulting 4-aminobutanal undergoes spontaneous intramolecular cyclization via the remaining aldehyde and the amine, forming the cyclic imine \u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid (P5C) after oxidation at C2, or forming 1-pyrroline directly which can be carboxylated. Alternatively, an amino-aldehyde intermediate cyclizes to yield P5C.", "reasoning": "This route bypasses the problematic selective \u03b3-carboxyl reduction of glutamate (rxn_009) entirely. Succinaldehyde is a plausible prebiotic molecule formed by aldol condensation of acetaldehyde (rxn_015) or partial reduction of succinic acid (a known proto-TCA product, Muchowska et al. 2017). Intramolecular cyclization of amino-aldehydes to form pyrrolines is well-known in organic chemistry and requires no enzyme. Montmorillonite clay surfaces concentrate reactants in interlayer environments (Ferris et al. 1996, Nature 381:59\u201361)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Reduction of P5C to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "Fe2+ and FeS as electron donors; H2 from serpentinization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic, pH 7-10, Fe2+ abundant in reduced form"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by Fe2+-mediated electron transfer or by H2 activated on FeS mineral surfaces. The cyclic imine accepts 2 electrons and 2 protons to yield the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. This is a simple, thermodynamically favorable imine reduction.", "reasoning": "In biology, pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase uses NADPH to reduce P5C to proline. Prebiotically, Fe2+ (abundant in anoxic early Earth oceans) and FeS/H2S systems serve as equivalent reductants. The reduction of imines by Fe2+ is a well-characterized reaction in aqueous geochemistry. H2 from serpentinization (Kelley et al. 2001) provides additional reducing power. Li and Brill (2003, Journal of Physical Chemistry A 107:5987\u20135992) showed proline's pyrrolidine ring has enhanced thermal stability at 270-340\u00b0C, so the product survives hydrothermal conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox: HCN + H2S to 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox pair", "TiO2 (anatase)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K (35\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling is ESSENTIAL", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic atmosphere, UV irradiation (>200 nm, no ozone layer), neutral pH, phosphate buffer. Cu(I) is oxidized to Cu(II) by UV, then reduced back by H2S, creating a catalytic redox cycle."}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes reductive homologation in the presence of H2S and UV light with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Cu(I) acts as an electron shuttle: UV excitation generates Cu(II) which oxidizes H2S to elemental S, while the released electrons drive HCN reduction and C-C bond formation. Sequential addition builds a 4-carbon chain as a cyanohydrin. H2S then adds across the nitrile to form a thioamide/cyanohydrin-thiol adduct \u2014 the key 4-carbon intermediate in Patel's 'movement c'.", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) established this pathway as part of their cyanosulfidic chemical network. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling is essential and was missing in previous attempts. Starting from HCN, H2S, and UV light at 35\u00b0C, this network produces precursors to 12 proteinogenic amino acids. The 4-carbon cyanohydrin is the specific entry point for proline synthesis via 'movement c' of the Patel et al. scheme."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "UV-driven cyclization of 4-C cyanohydrin-thiol to gamma-butyrothiolactam", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox pair", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K (35\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic, neutral pH, phosphate buffer. UV drives the cyclization and deoxygenation."}, "mechanism": "UV irradiation drives intramolecular cyclization of the 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol intermediate. The thioamide nitrogen attacks the C4 position, forming the 5-membered thiolactam ring. Simultaneous UV-driven deoxygenation of the \u03b1-hydroxyl group yields \u03b3-butyrothiolactam. The pyrrolidine ring formation arises spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage\u2014requiring no enzymatic guidance.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) describe this as the key ring-closing step in 'movement c'. The elegance of this pathway lies in its inevitability\u2014the pyrrolidine ring forms spontaneously from the geometric constraints of the 4-carbon chain at the thioamide stage. This UV-driven cyclization and deoxygenation produces both an open-chain and a cyclic \u03b1-hydroxythioamide. The cyclic form (\u03b3-butyrothiolactam) is the critical intermediate that commits the pathway to proline rather than other amino acids."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Photoreduction and HCN addition to form proline alpha-aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox pair", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "308K (35\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV light with Cu photoredox cycling", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Anoxic, UV irradiation, HCN in solution"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven photoreduction of the thiolactam C=S bond, followed by nucleophilic addition of HCN at the \u03b1-position. The thiolactam sulfur is lost (as H2S, recycling the sulfur back into the network), and HCN adds to form the \u03b1-aminonitrile \u2014 a cyclic pyrrolidine bearing a cyano group at C2. This is compound 47 in Patel et al.'s original paper.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) describe this transformation as part of the cyanosulfidic network. The photoreduction and HCN addition generates the \u03b1-aminonitrile precursor of proline (compound 47 in the original paper). This is the penultimate step before hydrolysis to proline. The released H2S can re-enter the catalytic cycle, demonstrating the self-sustaining nature of the cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrolysis of proline alpha-aminonitrile to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required \u2014 acid or base hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous solution, mildly acidic to neutral pH. Can proceed at ambient temperature over extended timescales."}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-C\u2261N) of the proline \u03b1-aminonitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to an amide (-CONH2), then to the carboxylic acid (-COOH), yielding DL-proline. This is the classic Strecker synthesis endpoint\u2014aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acid.", "reasoning": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis to amino acids is the final step of the classical Strecker synthesis and is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry 7:301\u2013307) confirmed that hydrolysis of compound 47 (proline \u03b1-aminonitrile) yields proline. This is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds without catalysts, though mineral surfaces may accelerate the reaction. Lerner and Cooper (2005, Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta 69:2901\u20132906) found evidence of Strecker-type reactions on meteorite parent bodies."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "UV photolysis/thermolysis of formamide to HCN", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis, mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV irradiation (strong, no ozone layer), mineral surfaces. Formamide dehydration/decomposition."}, "mechanism": "Formamide undergoes UV-driven dehydration on TiO2 mineral surfaces: HCONH2 \u2192 HCN + H2O. TiO2 (anatase or rutile) acts as a UV photocatalyst, absorbing UV radiation and generating reactive surface species that catalyze the dehydration. This is a key feedstock reaction for cyanide-based prebiotic chemistry.", "reasoning": "Saladino et al. (2017) demonstrated prebiotic synthesis of multiple products from formamide under UV irradiation on TiO2 surfaces. Rutile is a common early Earth mineral that drives photochemistry in UV-exposed shallow water environments. Formamide itself forms readily from HCN + H2O or CO + NH3 under hydrothermal conditions, placing it at the interface of hydrothermal and surface environments."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Formamide generation from CO2/NH3 under hydrothermal conditions", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and FeS mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Hydrothermal vent conditions, CO/CO2 + NH3 mixtures"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is first reduced to CO or formate on magnetite surfaces, then CO reacts with NH3 to form formamide (HCONH2). Alternatively, formate reacts with NH3 under dehydrating conditions near vent margins to yield formamide.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a well-established prebiotic feedstock molecule. It forms from the reaction of CO with NH3 or from formate + NH3 under heating. Hydrothermal vents provide both CO (from CO2 reduction on magnetite) and NH3 (dissolved in vent fluids). This reaction connects the hydrothermal carbon fixation network to the surface cyanide chemistry network, providing the critical environmental interconnection."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "HCN tetramerization to DAMN", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay surfaces concentrate HCN; slightly alkaline pH favors oligomerization", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Requires [HCN] > 0.01 M for efficient oligomerization. Evaporitic concentration helps."}, "mechanism": "Four molecules of HCN condense in a stepwise manner: HCN \u2192 aminomalononitrile (trimer) \u2192 diaminomaleonitrile (DAMN, tetramer). The reaction is base-catalyzed and proceeds through nucleophilic addition of CN- to HCN oligomers. DAMN is the gateway to both nucleobases (adenine) and amino acid precursors.", "reasoning": "First explored by Or\u00f3 (1961), HCN oligomerization is one of the most fundamental prebiotic reactions. 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN proceeds efficiently at [HCN] > 0.01 M at mildly alkaline pH. Montmorillonite clay surfaces help concentrate HCN from dilute solutions into interlayer spaces (Ferris et al. 1996, Nature 381:59\u201361). DAMN is the key intermediate for both nucleobase and amino acid formation from HCN."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "HCN polymer formation and hydrolysis to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces; elevated temperature accelerates polymer hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "DAMN polymerizes to HCN polymer, which upon acid/thermal hydrolysis releases amino acids including proline as a minor product. Higher temperatures favor proline detection."}, "mechanism": "DAMN polymerizes to form a complex HCN polymer (heterogeneous, contains embedded hydantoin and diketopiperazine units). Thermal or acid hydrolysis of this polymer at elevated temperatures releases multiple amino acids. Proline forms through hydantoin intermediates where a 4-carbon chain cyclizes before or during hydrolysis. Proline is a minor but reproducible product.", "reasoning": "Ruiz-Bermejo, Zorzano, and Osuna-Esteban (2013, Life 3:421\u2013448) reviewed 23 experimental conditions for HCN polymer hydrolysis and found proline among the amino acids detected, particularly at higher temperatures. The mechanism proceeds through DAMN and hydantoin intermediates. Proline's yield is low compared to glycine and alanine, reflecting the thermodynamic cost of ring formation (Higgs and Pudritz 2009, Astrobiology 9:483\u2013490)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "mineral surface-mediated decarboxylation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Thermal decarboxylation proceeds readily at hydrothermal temperatures"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal \u03b2-decarboxylation: CH3COCOO- \u2192 CH3CHO + CO2. This is a well-known reaction that proceeds readily at elevated temperatures. The resulting acetaldehyde is a key C2 building block for aldol condensation reactions.", "reasoning": "Decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde + CO2 is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds thermally at 350-400K (listed as a key reaction type in prebiotic chemistry). This provides acetaldehyde as a C2 building block for further chain construction. The reaction is effectively irreversible under hydrothermal conditions due to CO2 release."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Aldol self-condensation of acetaldehyde to succinaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "base-catalyzed aldol; montmorillonite provides mildly basic surface sites", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Evaporitic conditions help concentrate acetaldehyde; pH 8-9 for aldol catalysis"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of acetaldehyde undergo aldol condensation: CH3CHO + CH3CHO \u2192 OHCH(CH3)CH2CHO (3-hydroxybutanal), which then dehydrates and is reduced/rearranged to yield succinaldehyde (OHC-CH2-CH2-CHO). Alternatively, direct oxidative C-C coupling at the terminal positions. Clay surfaces template the reaction.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of aldehydes is a fundamental prebiotic reaction, analogous to the formose reaction (HCHO + HCHO \u2192 glycolaldehyde). Montmorillonite clay provides surface catalysis for aldol reactions. Succinaldehyde (butanedial) is a plausible prebiotic molecule that provides an alternative entry point to the pyrrolidine ring via reaction with NH3 (rxn_011), bypassing the problematic glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction entirely."}, {"id": "rxn_023", "name": "Chirality amplification: DL-proline to L-proline enrichment", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "multiple mechanisms operating in sequence (see reasoning)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Requires initial small ee from symmetry-breaking, then amplification. Multiple mechanisms can operate: (1) crystal-solution eutectic, (2) CPL during UV synthesis steps, (3) proline's own organocatalytic asymmetric induction."}, "mechanism": "Three complementary mechanisms contribute to L-proline enrichment: (1) SYMMETRY BREAKING: Circularly polarized UV light during cyanosulfidic photolysis (rxn_013-015) generates a small initial ee of 1-3% (Meinert et al. 2014). Proline's pyrrolidine ring produces unique VUV circular dichroism features that enhance CPL selectivity (Meinert et al. 2022). (2) CRYSTAL-SOLUTION EUTECTIC: DL-proline racemic crystals have more hydrogen bonds and are less soluble than enantiopure crystals. When solid proline of only 10% ee is partially dissolved, the solution enriches to 85-99% ee as racemic crystals preferentially remain undissolved (Hayashi et al. 2006). (3) AUTOCATALYTIC AMPLIFICATION: L-proline catalyzes asymmetric aldol reactions with >99% ee (List, Lerner, and Barbas 2000), creating a potential self-reinforcing chiral feedback loop where L-proline enrichment generates increasingly enantiopure products. LIMITATION: The eutectic effect has only been demonstrated in organic solvents (CHCl3/EtOH, Hayashi and Koshino 2006), not aqueous conditions. Aqueous racemization at the \u03b1-carbon competes with amplification.", "reasoning": "Chirality amplification is essential and was identified as missing in previous attempts. Three independent mechanisms are cited: (1) CPL-induced ee in UV photolysis (Meinert et al. 2014, Astrophysical Journal 788:79; Meinert et al. 2022, Nature Communications on VUV-CD of proline); (2) Crystal-solution eutectic amplification from 10% to 85-99% ee (Hayashi, Koshino et al. 2006, Angewandte Chemie 45:4593\u20134597; Klussmann et al. 2006 calculated eutectic ee of ~76.5%); (3) Proline organocatalysis (List, Lerner, and Barbas 2000, JACS 122:2395; Mathew, Iwamura, and Blackmond 2004 on autoinductive catalysis). OPEN QUESTION: Whether true autocatalysis (proline catalyzing its own formation) can create a self-reinforcing feedback loop remains the central unresolved problem (acknowledged in research findings). The \u03b1-hydrogen enables rapid aqueous racemization, distinguishing proline from \u03b1-dialkyl amino acids like isovaline that preserve meteoritic L-excess of up to 18.5% (Glavin and Dworkin 2009, PNAS 106:5487\u20135492)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation to glutamate reductive cascade", "description": "CO2 is fixed to pyruvate and glyoxylate via independent hydrothermal mineral catalysis (magnetite, pyrite). These C3 and C2 \u03b1-keto acids undergo Cu2+-catalyzed aldol condensation on surface to form \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Reductive amination on NiFeS yields glutamate, which is reduced to GSA, spontaneously cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to DL-proline. Chirality amplification yields L-proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Proto-TCA cycle to glutamate reductive cascade", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate forms directly from CO2/H2/H2S via a non-enzymatic proto-TCA cycle on pyrite and native iron (Muchowska et al. 2017). Reductive amination on NiFeS yields glutamate, which proceeds through the GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline cascade.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs amination of \u03b1KG to proline", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (from proto-TCA, rxn_005) reacts with HCN and NH3 via the Bucherer-Bergs pathway on surface to yield glutamate (Pulletikurti et al. 2022). Glutamate then follows the GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline cascade.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_005", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Ni-catalyzed mild reductive amination to proline", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate (from pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation) undergoes reductive amination with NH3 and H2 over Ni catalysts at remarkably mild conditions (22\u00b0C, pH 8; Kaur et al. 2024). Glutamate proceeds through GSA\u2192P5C\u2192proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photochemistry route (Patel-Sutherland)", "description": "The most mechanistically detailed prebiotic pathway to proline. HCN + H2S + UV with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling at 35\u00b0C yields a 4-carbon cyanohydrin-thiol, which spontaneously cyclizes to \u03b3-butyrothiolactam under UV. Photoreduction + HCN addition yields the proline \u03b1-aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to DL-proline. THIS ROUTE COMPLETELY BYPASSES the problematic glutamate \u03b3-carboxyl reduction.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formamide-fed cyanosulfidic route", "description": "Formamide (from hydrothermal CO2+NH3, rxn_018) is photolyzed on TiO2 surfaces to yield HCN, which then feeds the full cyanosulfidic pathway (P5). This provides environmental interconnection from hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface UV photochemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_018", "rxn_017", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_016", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_005", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Succinaldehyde bypass: pyruvate decarboxylation to P5C", "description": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, which self-condenses via aldol reaction to succinaldehyde. Reductive amination with NH3 yields P5C directly, BYPASSING both glutamate and GSA. This avoids the problematic \u03b3-carboxyl reduction bottleneck entirely.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_021", "rxn_022", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Formamide to HCN to Bucherer-Bergs glutamate to proline", "description": "Hydrothermal formamide is photolyzed to HCN on surface TiO2. HCN is then used in the Bucherer-Bergs amination of \u03b1KG (from proto-TCA) to yield glutamate, which follows the standard reductive cascade to proline. Connects hydrothermal carbon fixation to surface cyanide chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_018", "rxn_017", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_005", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "HCN polymer hydrolysis route (Or\u00f3-type)", "description": "HCN (from formamide photolysis) tetramerizes to DAMN, which polymerizes and upon thermal hydrolysis releases DL-proline as a minor but reproducible product. This is the shortest pathway but gives lowest proline selectivity.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_018", "rxn_017", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Convergent dual-source \u03b1KG to Ni-catalyzed glutamate to succinaldehyde bypass", "description": "\u03b1KG is produced by both proto-TCA (rxn_005) and pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004), demonstrating redundancy. Ni-catalyzed amination (Kaur et al. 2024) produces glutamate. Meanwhile, a parallel succinaldehyde pathway (rxn_021\u2192rxn_022\u2192rxn_011) provides an alternative entry to P5C. Both routes converge at DL-proline production.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_023"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_005", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_017"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_015", "rxn_019"], "description": "HCN is the master feedstock for cyanide-based prebiotic chemistry. It enters the network from formamide photolysis and feeds into four distinct downstream pathways: Bucherer-Bergs amination, cyanosulfidic photochemistry (two steps), and HCN oligomerization. Degree = 5."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_006", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_021"], "description": "Pyruvate is the primary C3 hub from hydrothermal CO2 fixation. It feeds into \u03b1KG synthesis via aldol condensation with glyoxylate, and into acetaldehyde via thermal decarboxylation (succinaldehyde bypass route). Degree = 3."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "description": "\u03b1-Ketoglutarate is the central metabolic branch-point. It is produced by two independent routes (pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation and proto-TCA on pyrite) and feeds three different amination pathways (NiFeS hydrothermal, Bucherer-Bergs surface, Ni-catalyzed mild). Degree = 5."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "description": "Glutamate receives input from three independent amination reactions and feeds the critical (but bottleneck) \u03b3-carboxyl reduction to GSA. Three-fold redundancy at the amination step ensures robust glutamate production. Degree = 4."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"], "description": "P5C (\u03941-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid) is the committed pyrrolidine ring intermediate. It forms by two independent routes: spontaneous GSA cyclization (Vogel & Davis 1952) and direct reductive amination of succinaldehyde. The succinaldehyde route bypasses the problematic glutamate \u03b3-reduction entirely. Degree = 3."}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_016", "rxn_020"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_023"], "description": "DL-Proline (racemic) is the convergence point where all synthesis pathways meet before chirality amplification. Three independent routes produce it: P5C reduction, cyanosulfidic aminonitrile hydrolysis, and HCN polymer hydrolysis. Degree = 4."}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 569601.8829345703, "success": true, "error_message": null}
